var documenterSearchIndex = {"docs":
[{"category":"section","location":"man/database/#The-database","page":"The database","text":"ModelManager records every project's structure in a single SQLite database living in the data directory. The database is the source of truth for what has been run: it is what makes re-runs cheap, lets you query results, and keeps the trial hierarchy reproducible.","title":"The database"},{"category":"section","location":"man/database/#What-the-database-stores","page":"The database","text":"The schema is generated from the project's locations, so the exact columns depend on inputs.toml. The core tables are:\n\nsimulations — one row per Simulation. Holds the simulator version, one input-folder ID per location, one variation ID per varied location, and a status code.\nmonads, samplings, trials — the higher levels of the trial hierarchy. Their constituent IDs are stored as compressed lists (see recordConstituentIDs and compressIDs).\nper-location folder tables (e.g. configs) — registered input folders.\n<simulator>_versions — the simulator's version table (name supplied by the backend via simulatorVersionTableName).\ncalibrations — calibration runs (see Calibration).\na status-codes table with the values from recognizedStatusCodes: \"Not Started\", \"Queued\", \"Running\", \"Completed\", \"Failed\".\n\nPer-folder variations are not stored in the central database. Each input folder that supports variation gets its own small SQLite database (e.g. config_variations.db) inside the folder, reached via locationVariationsDatabase. This keeps variation rows next to the inputs they modify. See Variations.\n\ninitializeDatabase creates the schema if needed; createMMTable and insertFolder are the building blocks backends use to register tables and folders.","title":"What the database stores"},{"category":"section","location":"man/database/#Querying","page":"The database","text":"Most read access goes through a few helpers that return DataFrames:\n\n# Run an arbitrary query.\ndf = queryToDataFrame(\"SELECT * FROM simulations WHERE status_code_id = 5;\")\n\n# Build a SELECT against a known table.\nq  = constructSelectQuery(\"monads\", \"WHERE monad_id = 12;\")\ndf = queryToDataFrame(q)\n\n# Parameterized statements (safe interpolation of values).\ndf = stmtToDataFrame(\"SELECT * FROM simulations WHERE config_id = ?;\", [3])\n\nUseful building blocks:\n\nconstructSelectQuery — assemble a SELECT with an optional WHERE/condition and column selection.\nbuildWhereClause — turn a vector of IDs plus a filter Dict into a WHERE clause.\ntableExists, tableColumns — introspect the schema.\ntableIDName — the primary-key column name for a table.\n\nFor inspecting what has been run, simulationsTable returns a tidy, human-readable table of simulations with their parameter values expanded into columns; pass short_names=false for raw XML-path column names.","title":"Querying"},{"category":"section","location":"man/database/#Consistency-diagnostics","page":"The database","text":"After initializeModelManager succeeds, it launches databaseDiagnostics in a background task. These are five read-only checks that verify the database and filesystem agree (DB↔filesystem sync, orphaned entries, constituent-ID integrity, and simulation status). Because they run in the background, their output may appear shortly after initialization returns; call waitForDiagnostics if you need them to finish first (useful in short scripts or tests).\n\nSee the Database API reference for the complete set of functions.","title":"Consistency diagnostics"},{"category":"section","location":"man/space_filling/#Space-filling-designs","page":"Space-filling designs","text":"When you attach several variations to a trial, the sampling method decides which combinations of values are actually run. The default enumerates every combination; the space-filling designs sample the parameter space more efficiently for high-dimensional sweeps. The method is the optional first argument to createTrial and run.\n\nAll four methods are subtypes of AddVariationMethod.","title":"Space-filling designs"},{"category":"section","location":"man/space_filling/#GridVariation-(default)","page":"Space-filling designs","text":"GridVariation takes the full factorial grid — every combination of every discrete variation's values. With three variations of 3, 4, and 2 values that is 3 × 4 × 2 = 24 monads.\n\nrun(GridVariation(), inputs, dv1, dv2)   # or just: run(inputs, dv1, dv2)\n\nGrids are exhaustive and exact, but the count grows multiplicatively — use a space-filling design when the dimension is high.","title":"GridVariation (default)"},{"category":"section","location":"man/space_filling/#LHSVariation","page":"Space-filling designs","text":"LHSVariation draws a Latin Hypercube Sample of size n: each parameter's range is split into n equal-probability bins and sampled so every bin is used exactly once. Good coverage with far fewer points than a grid.\n\nrun(LHSVariation(100), inputs, dist1, dist2)\nrun(LHSVariation(100; add_noise=true, orthogonalize=true), inputs, dist1, dist2)\n\nadd_noise — jitter within each bin instead of using bin centers.\northogonalize — use an orthogonal LHS for better space coverage (on by default).","title":"LHSVariation"},{"category":"section","location":"man/space_filling/#SobolVariation","page":"Space-filling designs","text":"SobolVariation uses a Sobol low-discrepancy quasi-random sequence — deterministic, highly uniform coverage that is the basis for Sobol' sensitivity analysis.\n\nrun(SobolVariation(128), inputs, dist1, dist2)\nrun(SobolVariation(; pow2=7), inputs, dist1, dist2)   # n = 2^7 = 128\n\nn_matrices, randomization, skip_start, and include_one control the sequence; the pow2 keyword is a convenience for power-of-two sample sizes.","title":"SobolVariation"},{"category":"section","location":"man/space_filling/#RBDVariation","page":"Space-filling designs","text":"RBDVariation builds a Random Balance Design, used by RBD-FAST sensitivity analysis. With the default Sobol-based construction, n must be within one of a power of two.\n\nrun(RBDVariation(128), inputs, dist1, dist2)\nrun(RBDVariation(100; use_sobol=false), inputs, dist1, dist2)   # random-sequence variant","title":"RBDVariation"},{"category":"section","location":"man/space_filling/#Choosing-a-design","page":"Space-filling designs","text":"Method Best for Notes\nGridVariation Small, exhaustive sweeps over discrete values Count grows multiplicatively\nLHSVariation General-purpose sampling of continuous ranges Even 1-D coverage of each parameter\nSobolVariation Variance-based Sobol' sensitivity Deterministic, low discrepancy\nRBDVariation RBD-FAST sensitivity n near a power of two (Sobol mode)\n\nThe space-filling methods pair naturally with DistributedVariations, since they sample distributions rather than enumerate fixed values. For analyses built directly on these designs, see Sensitivity analysis. For the result types (AddVariationsResult and its subtypes) and orthogonalLHS, see the Variations API reference.","title":"Choosing a design"},{"category":"section","location":"man/sensitivity_analysis/#Sensitivity-analysis","page":"Sensitivity analysis","text":"Global sensitivity analysis (GSA) asks how much each input parameter contributes to the variability of a model output. ModelManager provides three generic GSA methods that work with any backend: Morris one-at-a-time screening, Sobol' variance decomposition, and RBD-FAST.\n\nAll three are subtypes of GSAMethod and share one entry point — run:\n\nrun(method, inputs, variations; functions = [f1, f2, ...])\n\ninputs — the base InputFolders (or a reference monad).\nvariations — the parameters to analyze, as DistributedVariations (or CoVariations), so each can be sampled across its range.\nfunctions — output functions of the form monad_id -> Real. Each defines one scalar output whose sensitivity to the inputs is computed.\n\nrun builds the appropriate sampling design, runs the simulations, evaluates your output functions, and returns a GSASampling result holding the sensitivity indices.","title":"Sensitivity analysis"},{"category":"section","location":"man/sensitivity_analysis/#MOAT-—-Morris-screening","page":"Sensitivity analysis","text":"MOAT (Morris One-At-A-Time) is a cheap screening method: it perturbs one parameter at a time around a set of base points and measures the resulting \"elementary effects.\" Good for quickly ranking which parameters matter before committing to a more expensive analysis.\n\ngsa = run(MOAT(15), inputs, [dist1, dist2, dist3]; functions=[final_count])\ngsa = run(MOAT(10; add_noise=true), inputs, dists; functions=[final_count])\n\nThe integer is the number of base points (trajectories).","title":"MOAT — Morris screening"},{"category":"section","location":"man/sensitivity_analysis/#Sobol'-—-variance-decomposition","page":"Sensitivity analysis","text":"Sobolʼ computes variance-based first-order and total-order indices: the fraction of output variance attributable to each parameter alone, and including all its interactions.\n\ngsa = run(Sobolʼ(256), inputs, dists; functions=[final_count])\ngsa = run(Sobolʼ(256; sobol_index_methods=(first_order=:Jansen1999, total_order=:Jansen1999)),\n          inputs, dists; functions=[final_count])\n\nnote: Typing the name\nThe type is spelled Sobolʼ (with a rasp/prime, \\rasp<tab> in the Julia REPL or VS Code) to avoid clashing with the Sobol package. The ASCII alias SobolMM is identical if you prefer to avoid the Unicode character.","title":"Sobol' — variance decomposition"},{"category":"section","location":"man/sensitivity_analysis/#RBD-FAST","page":"Sensitivity analysis","text":"RBD (Random Balance Design / Fourier Amplitude Sensitivity Test) estimates first-order indices from a single design by analyzing the output's frequency content.\n\ngsa = run(RBD(128), inputs, dists; functions=[final_count])\ngsa = run(RBD(128; num_harmonics=10), inputs, dists; functions=[final_count])","title":"RBD-FAST"},{"category":"section","location":"man/sensitivity_analysis/#Working-with-the-result","page":"Sensitivity analysis","text":"The returned GSASampling carries the underlying Sampling and the computed indices. Helpers include:\n\ncalculateGSA! — (re)compute indices for a set of output functions.\ngetMonadIDDataFrame — the monad-ID design matrix used.\nsimulationIDs — the simulations that were run.\nmethodString — a label for the method/design.\n\nBecause GSA is built on the same space-filling designs and the same runner, its simulations are deduplicated and reused like any other trial. See the Sensitivity analysis API reference for full details.","title":"Working with the result"},{"category":"section","location":"man/hpc/#HPC-support","page":"HPC support","text":"ModelManager can dispatch each simulation as a SLURM job instead of a local task, so the same script that runs on a laptop scales to a cluster without modification.","title":"HPC support"},{"category":"section","location":"man/hpc/#Detection","page":"HPC support","text":"isRunningOnHPC returns true when the sbatch command is available on the PATH. initializeModelManager checks this at startup and stores the result; when SLURM is detected, the runner submits each pending simulation as a job rather than running it in a local task.\n\nYou can override the auto-detected value with useHPC:\n\nuseHPC(true)    # force HPC mode on\nuseHPC(false)   # force local execution even on a cluster login node","title":"Detection"},{"category":"section","location":"man/hpc/#Job-options","page":"HPC support","text":"SLURM job parameters are held in a Dict of sbatch options. defaultJobOptions provides sensible defaults; setJobOptions merges your overrides in:\n\nsetJobOptions(Dict(\n    \"time\"      => \"02:00:00\",\n    \"mem\"       => \"8G\",\n    \"partition\" => \"compute\",\n))\n\nThese options are applied to every job the runner submits for the current session.","title":"Job options"},{"category":"section","location":"man/hpc/#How-jobs-are-launched","page":"HPC support","text":"When HPC mode is active, the runner wraps each simulation command for sbatch submission (see prepareHPCCommand and prepCmdForWrap in the runner) instead of spawning a local process. From your script's perspective nothing changes — you still call run on a trial; the runner decides per-simulation whether to execute locally or submit a job.","title":"How jobs are launched"},{"category":"section","location":"man/hpc/#Filesystem-safety-on-shared-clusters","page":"HPC support","text":"Some shared filesystems intermittently fail or delay unlink/rm operations. Use rm_hpc_safe instead of rm when removing files inside ModelManager workflows on HPC; it tolerates these transient failures. resetDatabase and the deletion helpers use it internally (see Managing data).\n\nSee the HPC support API reference for the full set of functions.","title":"Filesystem safety on shared clusters"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/utilities/#Utilities","page":"Utilities","text":"Small generic helpers shared across the package.","title":"Utilities"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/utilities/#Public-API","page":"Utilities","text":"","title":"Public API"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/utilities/#Private-API","page":"Utilities","text":"","title":"Private API"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/utilities/#ModelManager.quietRun-Tuple{Cmd}","page":"Utilities","text":"quietRun(cmd::Cmd)\n\nRun the command with stdout and stderr redirected to devnull so no output goes to the console.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.quietRun"},{"category":"section","location":"man/building_a_simulator/#building_a_simulator","page":"Building a Simulator Backend","text":"This is the guide for the audience ModelManager exists to serve: developers writing a Julia package that drives a particular simulator. You implement one interface — AbstractSimulator — and ModelManager provides the trial hierarchy, variations, database, runner, sensitivity analysis, and calibration on top of it.\n\nPhysiCellModelManager.jl is the reference implementation; this page describes the contract it (and your package) fulfills.","title":"Building a Simulator Backend"},{"category":"section","location":"man/building_a_simulator/#The-big-picture","page":"Building a Simulator Backend","text":"your package                         ModelManager\n────────────                         ────────────\nMySimulator <: AbstractSimulator\n  runSimulation(sim, spec)  ◀──────  runner dispatches each pending simulation here\n  setupSampling / setupMonad ◀─────  prepareTrialHierarchy calls these before running\n  simulatorVersion* methods  ◀─────  database schema + version tracking\n  upgrade* methods           ◀─────  schema migrations\n  __init__ sets mm_globals_ref ────▶ initializeModelManager wires everything up\n\nYou supply a concrete type and a handful of methods; ModelManager calls them at the right moments. Anything you do not override falls back to a sensible default (no-op or error, depending on whether the method is optional or required).","title":"The big picture"},{"category":"section","location":"man/building_a_simulator/#1.-Define-the-simulator-type","page":"Building a Simulator Backend","text":"using ModelManager\n\nmutable struct MySimulator <: AbstractSimulator\n    dir::String\n    version::VersionNumber\n    # ...any state your backend needs\nend","title":"1. Define the simulator type"},{"category":"section","location":"man/building_a_simulator/#2.-Register-globals-in-__init__","page":"Building a Simulator Backend","text":"ModelManager keeps all per-project state in a ModelManagerGlobals accessed through mm_globals. Your package creates the instance and stores it in mm_globals_ref when it loads:\n\nfunction __init__()\n    ModelManager.mm_globals_ref[] = ModelManagerGlobals(simulator = MySimulator(\"/path\", v\"0.1.0\"))\nend","title":"2. Register globals in __init__"},{"category":"section","location":"man/building_a_simulator/#3.-Provide-an-initialization-entry-point","page":"Building a Simulator Backend","text":"Expose a function your users call to open a project. Do any backend-specific validation, then delegate to initializeModelManager, which opens the database, resolves/migrates the version, parses inputs.toml, builds the schema, and launches diagnostics:\n\nfunction initializeMyProject(path_to_data::AbstractString)\n    # ...validate paths, set simulator-specific globals...\n    return initializeModelManager(simulator(), path_to_data)\nend","title":"3. Provide an initialization entry point"},{"category":"section","location":"man/building_a_simulator/#4.-Implement-the-required-interface","page":"Building a Simulator Backend","text":"These methods have no default — ModelManager errors if they are called and not implemented. Dispatch each on your concrete type.","title":"4. Implement the required interface"},{"category":"section","location":"man/building_a_simulator/#Running-a-simulation","page":"Building a Simulator Backend","text":"ModelManager.runSimulation(sim::MySimulator, spec::SimulationSpec)::SimulationProcess\n\nThe workhorse. Called by the runner inside a task for each pending simulation. Setup has already happened (see below), so everything you need is in the SimulationSpec. Return a SimulationProcess describing the outcome. No keyword arguments — encode all per-simulation configuration in spec.","title":"Running a simulation"},{"category":"section","location":"man/building_a_simulator/#Setup-hooks","page":"Building a Simulator Backend","text":"ModelManager.setupSampling(sim::MySimulator, S::AbstractSampling; kwargs...)::Bool\nModelManager.setupMonad(sim::MySimulator, M::AbstractMonad; kwargs...)::Bool\n\nCalled by prepareTrialHierarchy before any simulation runs. setupSampling runs once per unique input-folder group (typically: compile shared custom code); setupMonad prepares each monad's varied input folders. Both return true/false for success. They accept the abstract types so they work for a bare Simulation or Monad without a wrapping object.","title":"Setup hooks"},{"category":"section","location":"man/building_a_simulator/#Simulator-metadata-and-versioning","page":"Building a Simulator Backend","text":"ModelManager.simulatorDir(sim::MySimulator)::String\nModelManager.simulatorInfo(sim::MySimulator)::String\nModelManager.simulatorVersionSchema(sim::MySimulator)::String\nModelManager.simulatorVersionIDName(sim::MySimulator)::String      # e.g. \"my_version_id\"\nModelManager.simulatorVersionTableName(sim::MySimulator)::String   # e.g. \"my_versions\"\nModelManager.resolveSimulatorVersionID(sim::MySimulator)::Int\nModelManager.currentSimulatorVersionID(sim::MySimulator)::Int\n\nThese let ModelManager build the database schema (one version table and one version-FK column per simulator) and stamp every simulation with the simulator version that produced it.","title":"Simulator metadata and versioning"},{"category":"section","location":"man/building_a_simulator/#Variation-row-writing","page":"Building a Simulator Backend","text":"ModelManager.addVariationRows(sim::MySimulator, inputs, reference_variation_id, loc_dicts)::Vector{VariationID}\n\nGiven the variation combinations ModelManager has computed, write them into the per-location variations databases and return the resulting VariationIDs. This is where your backend's knowledge of the input-file format lives.","title":"Variation row writing"},{"category":"section","location":"man/building_a_simulator/#Database-migration-interface","page":"Building a Simulator Backend","text":"To support schema upgrades as your package evolves:\n\nModelManager.packageName(sim::MySimulator)::String                 # e.g. \"MyModelManager\"\nModelManager.dbVersionTableName(sim::MySimulator)::String          # e.g. \"my_version\"\nModelManager.upgradeMilestones(sim::MySimulator)::Vector{VersionNumber}\nModelManager.upgradeToMilestone(sim::MySimulator, version, auto_upgrade)::Bool\n\nSee Database upgrades for how these are orchestrated by upgradePackage.","title":"Database migration interface"},{"category":"section","location":"man/building_a_simulator/#5.-Override-optional-hooks-as-needed","page":"Building a Simulator Backend","text":"These have working defaults; override only when your simulator needs them.\n\nMethod Default Override to…\npostInitDisplay prints generic fields prepend a logo/version banner\ncentralDBFileName \"mm.db\" use a custom database filename\npostSimulationProcessing no-op clean up or prune output after each run\ninitializeInputFolder no-op compile a template into a new input folder\ngetInputFolderDescription \"\" read folder metadata for the DB\nclearSimulatorArtifacts no-op remove compiled artifacts on database reset","title":"5. Override optional hooks as needed"},{"category":"section","location":"man/building_a_simulator/#Boundary-rules","page":"Building a Simulator Backend","text":"location is explicit. ModelManager does not resolve a variation target to a project location — your package must pass location when constructing variations (or provide convenience constructors that infer it). See Variations.\nNo simulator specifics leak into ModelManager. If you find yourself wanting ModelManager to know something about your simulator, that knowledge belongs behind one of these interface methods — add or override a hook rather than special-casing the core.\n\nFor the exact signatures and contracts of every method, see the AbstractSimulator interface API reference.","title":"Boundary rules"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/classes/#Trial-hierarchy","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"Simulation, Monad, Sampling, Trial, InputFolders, and VariationID.","title":"Trial hierarchy"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/classes/#Public-API","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"","title":"Public API"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/classes/#Private-API","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"","title":"Private API"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.AbstractMonad","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"AbstractMonad <: AbstractSampling\n\nAbstract type for Simulation and Monad.\n\nAll associated simulations share both input folders and variation IDs.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.AbstractMonad"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.AbstractSampling","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"AbstractSampling <: AbstractTrial\n\nAbstract type for Simulation, Monad, and Sampling.\n\nAll associated simulations share the same input folders; only variations differ.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.AbstractSampling"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.AbstractTrial","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"AbstractTrial\n\nAbstract type for the Simulation, Monad, Sampling, and Trial types.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.AbstractTrial"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.InputFolder","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"InputFolder\n\nHold the information for a single input folder (location + folder name + metadata).\n\nCreated automatically by InputFolders constructors.\n\nFields\n\nlocation::Symbol: The location key (e.g. :config, :custom_code).\nid::Int: Database row ID for this folder.\nfolder::String: Folder name within data/inputs/<path_from_inputs>/.\nbasename::Union{String,Missing}: Primary input file name, or missing.\nrequired::Bool: Whether this location is required.\nvaried::Bool: Whether this folder supports parameter variations.\npath_from_inputs::String: Relative path from data/inputs/ to this folder.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.InputFolder"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.InputFolders","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"InputFolders\n\nConsolidate the folder information for a simulation / monad / sampling.\n\nConstructors\n\nAll folders as keyword arguments (omitted ⟹ \"\"):\n\nInputFolders(; config=\"default\", custom_code=\"default\")\n\nRequired folders as positional args (alphabetical order), optional as kwargs:\n\nInputFolders(\"default\", \"default\"; ic_cell=\"cells_in_disc\")\n\nFields\n\ninput_folders::NamedTuple: Keys are location symbols; values are InputFolders.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.InputFolders"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.MMOutput","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"MMOutput{T<:AbstractTrial}\n\nHold the result of a run call.\n\nFields\n\ntrial::T: The trial that was run.\nn_scheduled::Int: Number of simulations scheduled in this run.\nn_success::Int: Number of simulations that completed successfully.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.MMOutput"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.Monad","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"Monad\n\nA group of identical-up-to-randomness simulations.\n\nConstructors\n\nMonad(inputs, variation_id; n_replicates=0, use_previous=true)\nMonad(monad_id; n_replicates=0, use_previous=true)\nMonad(simulation)\n\nFields\n\nid::Int\ninputs::InputFolders\nvariation_id::VariationID\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.Monad"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.Sampling","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"Sampling\n\nA group of monads sharing the same input folders but differing in parameter values.\n\nFields\n\nid::Int\ninputs::InputFolders\nmonads::Vector{Monad}\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.Sampling"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.Simulation","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"Simulation\n\nA single run of the model.\n\nConstructors\n\nSimulation(simulation_id)          # retrieve existing\nSimulation(inputs, variation_id)   # create new (inserts into DB)\nSimulation(monad)                  # new sim with same params as monad\n\nFields\n\nid::Int\ninputs::InputFolders\nvariation_id::VariationID\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.Simulation"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.Trial","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"Trial\n\nA group of samplings that may have different input folders.\n\nFields\n\nid::Int\nsamplings::Vector{Sampling}\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.Trial"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.VariationID","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"VariationID\n\nRecord the variation row IDs for each varied input location.\n\nA value of -1 means the location is not in use; 0 means the base (unvaried) file is being used.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.VariationID"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.constituentIDs-Tuple{String}","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"constituentIDs(T::AbstractTrial)\nconstituentIDs(::Type{T}, id::Int)\n\nRead the constituent IDs for trial T from its CSV file.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.constituentIDs"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.locationPath-Tuple{InputFolder}","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"locationPath(input_folder::InputFolder)\n\nReturn the full path to the input folder described by input_folder.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.locationPath"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.locationPath-Tuple{Symbol, AbstractSampling}","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"locationPath(location::Symbol, S::AbstractSampling)\n\nReturn the full path to the input folder for location used by sampling S.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.locationPath"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.monadIDs-Tuple{}","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"monadIDs()\n\nReturn all monad IDs in the database.  Overloaded forms accept a monad, sampling, or trial object.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.monadIDs"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.pathToOutputFolder-Tuple{Int64}","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"pathToOutputFolder(simulation_id::Int)\n\nReturn the path to the output folder for simulation_id.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.pathToOutputFolder"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.setNumberOfParallelSims-Tuple{Int64}","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"setNumberOfParallelSims(n::Int)\n\nSet the maximum number of parallel simulations.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.setNumberOfParallelSims"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.simulationIDs-Tuple{}","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"simulationIDs()\n\nReturn all simulation IDs in the database.  Overloaded forms accept a trial, sampling, monad, or simulation object.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.simulationIDs"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.trialFolder-Tuple{Type{<:AbstractTrial}, Int64}","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"trialFolder(T::Type{<:AbstractTrial}, id::Int)\ntrialFolder(T::AbstractTrial)\n\nReturn the output folder path for trial type T with the given ID.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.trialFolder"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.addSimulationID-Tuple{Monad, Int64}","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"addSimulationID(monad::Monad, simulation_id::Int)\n\nAppend simulation_id to monad's constituent IDs CSV (if not already present).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.addSimulationID"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.constituentType-Tuple{Type{Simulation}}","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"constituentType(T)\n\nReturn the type of the sub-objects of trial type T.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.constituentType"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.constituentTypeFilename-Tuple{Any}","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"constituentTypeFilename(T)\n\nReturn the CSV filename that stores the constituent IDs for type T.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.constituentTypeFilename"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.lowerClassString-Union{Tuple{Type{T}}, Tuple{T}} where T<:AbstractTrial","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"lowerClassString(T)\n\nReturn the lowercase name of T's concrete type (e.g. \"simulation\").\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.lowerClassString"},{"category":"function","location":"lib/classes/#ModelManager.printInputFolders","page":"Trial hierarchy","text":"printInputFolders(io::IO, input_folders::InputFolders, n_indent::Int=0)\n\nPrint the folder information for each used location in input_folders.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.printInputFolders"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/ModelManager/#ModelManager","page":"ModelManager","text":"The top-level module and the entry point for the API reference.\n\nModelManager re-exports its public API from the source files under src/. The individual symbols are documented on the grouped pages listed under Index in the sidebar:\n\nCore — Globals & initialization, User API, Utilities, Trial hierarchy\nProject & inputs — Project configuration & locations, Variations & designs, XML utilities\nRunning simulations — Runner, AbstractSimulator interface, Recorder, HPC & SLURM\nAnalysis & calibration — Sensitivity analysis (GSA), Calibration\nManagement & maintenance — Database, Deletion, Schema migrations, Package version\n\nTo find a specific symbol, use the Alphabetical index or the search box.","title":"ModelManager"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/project_configuration/#Project-configuration-and-locations","page":"Project configuration & locations","text":"inputs.toml parsing, ProjectLocations, and location-path helpers.","title":"Project configuration & locations"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/project_configuration/#Public-API","page":"Project configuration & locations","text":"","title":"Public API"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/project_configuration/#Private-API","page":"Project configuration & locations","text":"","title":"Private API"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/project_configuration/#ModelManager.ProjectLocations","page":"Project configuration & locations","text":"ProjectLocations\n\nA struct that contains information about the locations of input files in the project.\n\nCreated by reading the inputs.toml file in the data directory via parseProjectInputsConfigurationFile.\n\nFields\n\nall::NTuple{L,Symbol}: All registered location names (alphabetically sorted).\nrequired::NTuple{M,Symbol}: Locations whose input folder is mandatory.\nvaried::NTuple{N,Symbol}: Locations that support parameter variations.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.ProjectLocations"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/project_configuration/#ModelManager.folderIsVaried-Tuple{Symbol, String}","page":"Project configuration & locations","text":"folderIsVaried(location::Symbol, folder::String)\n\nReturn true if folder in location can have parameter variations applied.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.folderIsVaried"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/project_configuration/#ModelManager.locationFolder-Tuple{Union{String, Symbol}}","page":"Project configuration & locations","text":"locationFolder(location::Union{String,Symbol})\n\nReturn the name of the folder for location within data/inputs/. Defaults to locationTableName.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.locationFolder"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/project_configuration/#ModelManager.locationIDName-Tuple{Union{String, Symbol}}","page":"Project configuration & locations","text":"locationIDName(location)\n\nReturn the ID column name for location (e.g. \"config_id\").\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.locationIDName"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/project_configuration/#ModelManager.locationIDNames-Tuple{}","page":"Project configuration & locations","text":"locationIDNames()\n\nReturn an iterator over the ID column names for all locations.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.locationIDNames"},{"category":"function","location":"lib/project_configuration/#ModelManager.locationPath","page":"Project configuration & locations","text":"locationPath(location::Symbol[, folder])\n\nReturn the path to location's input directory.  If folder is given, join it.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.locationPath"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/project_configuration/#ModelManager.locationTableName-Tuple{Union{String, Symbol}}","page":"Project configuration & locations","text":"locationTableName(location)\n\nReturn the database table name for location (e.g. \"configs\").\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.locationTableName"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/project_configuration/#ModelManager.locationVariationIDName-Tuple{Union{String, Symbol}}","page":"Project configuration & locations","text":"locationVariationIDName(location)\n\nReturn the variation ID column name for location (e.g. \"config_variation_id\").\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.locationVariationIDName"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/project_configuration/#ModelManager.locationVariationIDNames-Tuple{}","page":"Project configuration & locations","text":"locationVariationIDNames()\n\nReturn an iterator over the variation ID column names for all varied locations.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.locationVariationIDNames"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/project_configuration/#ModelManager.locationVariationsDBName-Tuple{Union{String, Symbol}}","page":"Project configuration & locations","text":"locationVariationsDBName(location::Union{String,Symbol})\n\nReturn the filename of the per-folder variations SQLite database for location.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.locationVariationsDBName"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/project_configuration/#ModelManager.locationVariationsFolder-Tuple{Union{String, Symbol}}","page":"Project configuration & locations","text":"locationVariationsFolder(location)\n\nReturn the name of the variations folder for location.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.locationVariationsFolder"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/project_configuration/#ModelManager.locationVariationsTableName-Tuple{Union{String, Symbol}}","page":"Project configuration & locations","text":"locationVariationsTableName(location)\n\nReturn the name of the variations table for location (e.g. \"config_variations\").\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.locationVariationsTableName"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/project_configuration/#ModelManager.parseProjectInputsConfigurationFile-Tuple{}","page":"Project configuration & locations","text":"parseProjectInputsConfigurationFile()\n\nParse inputs.toml and update mm_globals with the resulting ProjectLocations and inputs_dict.\n\nReturns true on success, false if the file is missing or malformed.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.parseProjectInputsConfigurationFile"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/project_configuration/#ModelManager.pathToInputsConfig-Tuple{}","page":"Project configuration & locations","text":"pathToInputsConfig()\n\nReturn the path to inputs.toml.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.pathToInputsConfig"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/project_configuration/#ModelManager.sanitizePathElement-Tuple{String}","page":"Project configuration & locations","text":"sanitizePathElement(path_element::String)\n\nValidate and return path_element, raising an ArgumentError for unsafe values.\n\nDisallows \"..\", absolute paths, and characters in ~*?<>|:.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.sanitizePathElement"},{"category":"section","location":"man/project_configuration/#Project-configuration","page":"Project configuration","text":"A ModelManager project is rooted at a data directory (data/). Everything about a project — which input categories exist, where their folders live, the database — is derived from that directory and a single configuration file inside it: inputs.toml.","title":"Project configuration"},{"category":"section","location":"man/project_configuration/#The-data-directory","page":"Project configuration","text":"initializeModelManager takes the path to data/ and opens the project there:\n\ninitializeModelManager(MySimulator(...), \"/path/to/project/data\")\n\nInside data/ ModelManager expects:\n\ndata/\n├── inputs/\n│   ├── inputs.toml          # location configuration (see below)\n│   ├── configs/             # one folder per \"config\" input\n│   │   └── default/\n│   ├── custom_codes/\n│   └── ...                  # one subtree per registered location\n└── <database file>          # e.g. mm.db (name set by centralDBFileName)\n\nThe exact set of subfolders under inputs/ is not hard-coded — it is whatever inputs.toml declares. The database filename defaults to mm.db and can be overridden by a backend via centralDBFileName.\n\ndataDir returns the active data directory; pathToInputsConfig returns the path to inputs.toml; locationPath resolves the directory for a given location.","title":"The data directory"},{"category":"section","location":"man/project_configuration/#inputs.toml","page":"Project configuration","text":"inputs.toml declares the project's locations — the categories of input that a simulation draws from. Each top-level table is one location:\n\n[config]\nrequired = true\nvaried = true\nbasename = \"PhysiCell_settings.xml\"\n\n[custom_code]\nrequired = true\nvaried = false\n\n[ic_cell]\nrequired = false\nvaried = [\"cells.csv\", \"cells.xml\"]\nbasename = [\"cells.csv\", \"cells.xml\"]\npath_from_inputs = [\"ics\", \"cells\"]\n\nEach location table supports these keys:\n\nKey Meaning\nrequired Whether every simulation must supply a folder for this location.\nvaried Whether the location supports parameter variations. A Bool, or a Vector{Bool} (one per basename) for multi-file locations.\nbasename The primary input file(s) inside each folder. Required when varied is true. May be a Vector to allow alternative file names.\npath_from_inputs Optional relative path from inputs/ to the location's folders. Defaults to the pluralized location name (e.g. config → configs/). Path elements are validated by sanitizePathElement.\n\ninputs.toml is parsed by parseProjectInputsConfigurationFile, which validates the keys and stores the result in the project globals.","title":"inputs.toml"},{"category":"section","location":"man/project_configuration/#ProjectLocations","page":"Project configuration","text":"The parsed configuration is summarized by ProjectLocations, reachable via projectLocations:\n\njulia> projectLocations()\n\nIt exposes three tuples of location symbols:\n\nall — every registered location (alphabetically sorted),\nrequired — locations whose folder is mandatory,\nvaried — locations that support variations.\n\nThese drive the rest of the framework: InputFolders iterates all to build a canonical NamedTuple, the database schema generates one ID column per location, and VariationID tracks one entry per varied location.","title":"ProjectLocations"},{"category":"section","location":"man/project_configuration/#Location-naming-helpers","page":"Project configuration","text":"A family of small functions derives the database and filesystem names for a location from its symbol. These keep the schema and folder layout consistent:\n\nFunction Example (:config)\nlocationTableName \"configs\"\nlocationIDName \"config_id\"\nlocationVariationIDName \"config_variation_id\"\nlocationVariationsTableName \"config_variations\"\nlocationVariationsDBName \"config_variations.db\"\nlocationFolder \"configs\"\n\nBackends and advanced users generally rely on these rather than hard-coding column or table names. See the Project configuration API reference for the full list.","title":"Location naming helpers"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/#Alphabetical-index","page":"Alphabetical index","text":"Every documented symbol in ModelManager.jl, in alphabetical order.\n\n","title":"Alphabetical index"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/hpc/#HPC-and-SLURM","page":"HPC & SLURM","text":"SLURM detection and job-option configuration.","title":"HPC & SLURM"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/hpc/#Public-API","page":"HPC & SLURM","text":"","title":"Public API"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/hpc/#Private-API","page":"HPC & SLURM","text":"","title":"Private API"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/hpc/#ModelManager.isRunningOnHPC-Tuple{}","page":"HPC & SLURM","text":"isRunningOnHPC()\n\nReturn true if the current environment is an HPC environment, false otherwise.\n\nCurrently checks for a SLURM environment by probing for the sbatch command.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.isRunningOnHPC"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/hpc/#ModelManager.setJobOptions-Tuple{Dict}","page":"HPC & SLURM","text":"setJobOptions(options::Dict)\n\nMerge options into the global sbatch_options dictionary.\n\nEach key–value pair becomes a --key=value flag appended to the sbatch command when running simulations on an HPC. Values that are Functions are called with the simulation ID at runtime.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.setJobOptions"},{"category":"function","location":"lib/hpc/#ModelManager.useHPC","page":"HPC & SLURM","text":"useHPC([use::Bool=true])\n\nSet the global run_on_hpc flag to use.\n\nExamples\n\nuseHPC()        # enable sbatch wrapping\nuseHPC(true)    # same\nuseHPC(false)   # run simulations locally\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.useHPC"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/hpc/#ModelManager.defaultJobOptions-Tuple{}","page":"HPC & SLURM","text":"defaultJobOptions()\n\nReturn a Dict with default SLURM options.\n\nCurrent defaults:\n\n\"job-name\" — simulation_id -> \"S$(simulation_id)\"\n\"mem\" — \"1G\"\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.defaultJobOptions"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/hpc/#ModelManager.shellCommandExists-Tuple{Union{Cmd, String}}","page":"HPC & SLURM","text":"shellCommandExists(cmd::Union{String,Cmd})\n\nCheck if a shell command exists in the current environment.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.shellCommandExists"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/calibration/#calibration_lib","page":"Calibration","text":"Approximate Bayesian Computation (ABC-SMC) calibration: problem definition, methods, perturbation kernels, the simulation bank, distance functions, progress reporting, and posterior visualization. See the Calibration manual page for a narrative walkthrough.\n\nThe calibration code lives under src/calibration/; this page collects the docstrings from every file in that subdirectory.","title":"Calibration"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/calibration/#Public-API","page":"Calibration","text":"","title":"Public API"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/calibration/#Private-API","page":"Calibration","text":"","title":"Private API"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.ABCResult","page":"Calibration","text":"ABCResult\n\nHolds the result of an ABC-SMC calibration run.\n\nFields\n\ncalibration::Calibration: The calibration record (DB entry + folder).\ngenerations::Vector{GenerationResult}: Results per SMC generation, in order. Each GenerationResult.particles stores raw latent CDF coordinates.\nparameters::Vector{CalibrationParameter}: The calibrated parameters (same as stored in the CalibrationProblem), used to convert CDF coordinates to interpretable target values in posterior.\nmethod::ABCSMC: The settings used for this run.\n\nExamples\n\nresult = runABC(problem)\ndf, weights = posterior(result)                # final generation, target-value format\ndf, weights = posterior(result; generation=2)  # specific generation\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.ABCResult"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.Calibration","page":"Calibration","text":"Calibration\n\nRepresents a calibration run tracked in the database.\n\nCreated automatically by runABC. The associated output folder at data/outputs/calibrations/{id}/ contains:\n\ngenerations/generation_{NNN}_monads.csv: monad IDs evaluated per generation (written before each batch for crash safety).\ngenerations/generation_{NNN}.csv: human-readable per-generation results — target parameter values (and latent parameter samples for user-supplied LatentVariations), weights, distances, and monad IDs.\ngenerations/generation_{NNN}.toml: generation-level metadata (epsilon, acceptancerate, ess, nevaluations).\ngenerations/generation_cdfs/generation_{NNN}.csv: raw CDF coordinates for each accepted particle; used by resumeABC to reconstruct the internal particle state exactly.\nmethod.toml: serialized ABC-SMC settings (used by resumeABC).\nproblem.jld2: full serialized CalibrationProblem; enables resumeABC(Calibration(id)) with no further arguments.\nparameters.toml: human-readable mapping from display column names (used in generations/ CSVs) to database column names, with prior strings.\n\nFields\n\nid::Int: Unique ID, matched to the calibrations table in the database.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.Calibration"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.CalibrationProblem","page":"Calibration","text":"CalibrationProblem\n\nDefines a full calibration problem: model inputs, parameters to infer, observed data, and how to compare simulated to observed output.\n\nFields\n\ninputs::InputFolders: Base model configuration shared across all calibration runs.\nparameters::Vector{CalibrationParameter}: Parameters to calibrate, stored as CalibrationParameter objects that track both the original user-supplied variation and the derived LatentVariation used internally. Pass any combination of DistributedVariation, CoVariation{DistributedVariation}, or LatentVariation{<:Distribution} to the constructors — conversion is automatic.\nobserved_data: Observed summary statistic in whatever form the distance function expects as its second argument.\nsummary_statistic::Function: (monad_id::Int) → T for any T accepted by distance as its first argument. Called once per proposed particle. The user controls how to aggregate over simulationIDs(Monad, monad_id) (e.g. averaging, taking a single replicate).\ndistance::Function: (simulated, observed) → Float64. simulated is the return value of summary_statistic; observed is observed_data. Built-in: mseDistance — handles Dict, Vector, and scalar inputs.\nn_replicates::Int: Number of replicate simulations to run per proposed particle (default 1). Values > 1 reduce stochastic noise in each particle evaluation at the cost of N× more compute.\nreference_variation_id::VariationID: Base variation ID establishing fixed parameter values that apply to every particle evaluation. Obtain from a reference monad: createTrial(inputs, fixed_dvs...; n_replicates=0).variation_id.\n\nExamples\n\n# Short run for testing — set max_time via a reference\nref = createTrial(inputs, DiscreteVariation([\"overall\",\"max_time\"], 12.0); n_replicates=0)\n\nobserved = Dict(\"default\" => 100.0)\nproblem = CalibrationProblem(\n    ref,\n    [DistributedVariation(:config, xml_path, Uniform(1e-7, 1e-4))],\n    observed,\n    monad_id -> endpointPopulationCounts(monad_id),\n    mseDistance\n)\n\n# Covaried parameters — one latent CDF draw moves both targets together\nproblem2 = CalibrationProblem(\n    ref,\n    [CoVariation(dv_birth_rate, dv_death_rate)],\n    observed,\n    summary_fn,\n    mseDistance\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.CalibrationProblem"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.ConvergenceSummary","page":"Calibration","text":"ConvergenceSummary(result::ABCResult)\nConvergenceSummary(cal::Calibration)\n\nPer-generation convergence table for an ABC-SMC run. Supports plot(ConvergenceSummary(result)) via the RecipesBase recipe in visualize.jl, and behaves like a DataFrame for property access (cs.epsilon, etc.).\n\nColumns\n\nt: Generation index.\nepsilon: Maximum accepted distance.\nacceptance_rate: Fraction of proposals accepted.\nn_accepted: Number of accepted particles (equals population_size when accept_overflow=false; may be larger when accept_overflow=true).\ness: Effective sample size (1 / Σwᵢ²).\ness_fraction: ess / n_accepted — values near 1 mean uniform weights.\nn_evaluations: Total proposals evaluated (including rejected).\n\nExamples\n\ncs = ConvergenceSummary(result)\ncs = ConvergenceSummary(Calibration(42))\nplot(cs)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.ConvergenceSummary"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.GenerationResult","page":"Calibration","text":"GenerationResult\n\nResult of a single ABC-SMC generation.\n\nFields\n\nt::Int: Generation index (1-based).\nparticles::DataFrame: One row per accepted particle; columns are latent CDF coordinates (internal representation used by the ABC-SMC algorithm).\nweights::Vector{Float64}: Normalized importance weights (sum to 1).\ndistances::Vector{Float64}: Distance for each accepted particle.\nepsilon::Float64: Maximum distance among accepted particles (≤ the threshold used).\nn_evaluations::Int: Total proposals evaluated, including rejected ones.\nmonad_ids::Vector{Int}: Monad IDs for each accepted particle.\nacceptance_rate::Float64: Fraction of proposals that passed the epsilon threshold (n_accepted_total / n_evaluations). When accept_overflow=false, this equals length(distances) / n_evaluations; when accept_overflow=true, it may be slightly higher because overflow particles are counted but n_evaluations includes the full batch.\ness::Float64: Effective sample size, 1 / Σwᵢ². Equals population_size when weights are uniform (generation 1) and decreases as weights concentrate.\nrejected_proposals::Union{Nothing,DataFrame}: CDF-coordinate DataFrame of all rejected proposals in this generation (same column names as particles). Populated only when ABCSMC(store_rejected=true); always nothing for generation 1 (all Sobol proposals are accepted) and always nothing on resume. Used by the :transition visualization recipe; see also the lazy disk fallback in _lazyLoadRejected.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.GenerationResult"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.posterior-Tuple{ABCResult}","page":"Calibration","text":"posterior(result::ABCResult; generation::Union{Int,Symbol}=:final)\n\nExtract posterior samples from an ABCResult.\n\nConverts the internal CDF-coordinate particles to target-parameter space using the stored CalibrationParameter objects. For DVSource / CVSource parameters the columns are the actual calibrated parameter values; for LVSource parameters the latent parameter samples are prepended.\n\nReturns\n\ndf::DataFrame: One row per particle; columns are target parameter names. For LVSource parameters (user-supplied LatentVariation), the latent parameter samples are included as well.\nweights::Vector{Float64}: Importance weights (sum to 1).\n\nArguments\n\ngeneration: Integer generation index (1-based) or :final for the last generation.\n\nExamples\n\nresult = runABC(problem)\ndf, weights = posterior(result)                # final generation\ndf, weights = posterior(result; generation=1)  # first generation\nprintln(\"Posterior mean: \", sum(df[!, \"overall/max_time\"] .* weights))\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.posterior"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.posterior-Tuple{Calibration}","page":"Calibration","text":"posterior(calibration::Calibration; generation::Union{Int,Symbol}=:final)\n\nExtract posterior samples directly from disk for a completed calibration run.\n\nReads the human-readable generations/generation_{NNN}.csv file for the requested generation. Returns only the parameter columns (strips weight, distance, monad_id).\n\nUseful when you have only the calibration ID (e.g. after a session restart) and don't have an in-memory ABCResult.\n\nReturns\n\ndf::DataFrame: One row per particle; columns are target parameter names.\nweights::Vector{Float64}: Importance weights (sum to 1).\n\nExamples\n\n# Retrieve results after a session restart\ndf, weights = posterior(Calibration(42))\ndf, weights = posterior(Calibration(42); generation=3)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.posterior"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.CalibrationParameter","page":"Calibration","text":"CalibrationParameter\n\nInternal type pairing an AbstractCalibrationSource (the original user-supplied variation) with the derived LatentVariation{<:Distribution} used by the ABC-SMC algorithm.\n\nCalibrationParameter objects are stored in a CalibrationProblem and are passed through the calibration loop. The source is used only for:\n\nWriting human-readable display CSVs with interpretable target parameter values.\nSerializing to problem.jld2 via JLD2 for resumeABC without re-supplying the original problem.\n\nUsers never construct CalibrationParameter directly — it is created automatically when building a CalibrationProblem from DistributedVariation, CoVariation{DistributedVariation}, or LatentVariation{<:Distribution} arguments.\n\nFields\n\nsource::Union{DVSource,CVSource,LVSource}: The original variation type for provenance.\nlv::LatentVariation{<:Distribution}: The derived latent variation used internally by the ABC-SMC loop.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.CalibrationParameter"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.ABCSMC","page":"Calibration","text":"ABCSMC\n\nSettings for ABC-SMC (Approximate Bayesian Computation — Sequential Monte Carlo) calibration (Toni et al. 2009, Beaumont et al. 2009).\n\nFields\n\npopulation_size::Int: Number of accepted particles per generation (default 100).\nmax_nr_populations::Int: Maximum number of SMC generations (default 10).\nminimum_epsilon::Float64: Stop when the maximum accepted distance drops to or below this value (default 0.01). Acts as a hard floor: the algorithm always runs a full generation at this threshold before stopping, ensuring all accepted particles satisfy it.\nepsilon_quantile::Float64: Quantile of accepted distances used to set the next generation's threshold when no epsilon_schedule is supplied (default 0.5, i.e. median). Ignored when epsilon_schedule is provided.\nperturbation_kernel::AbstractKernel: Kernel for perturbing resampled particles. Accepts GaussianKernel, ComponentwiseKernel, LocalNNKernel, or LocalNNCovKernel. Default GaussianKernel() uses twice the weighted covariance (Beaumont et al. 2009).\nepsilon_schedule::Union{Nothing,Vector{Float64}}: Optional explicit decreasing sequence of acceptance thresholds. When supplied, generation t uses epsilon_schedule[t-1] instead of the adaptive quantile rule. If the schedule is shorter than max_nr_populations, the adaptive rule resumes for remaining generations. All values must be positive and strictly decreasing. Default nothing.\nmin_acceptance_rate::Float64: Stop after any generation whose acceptance rate (accepted / proposed) falls below this value. 0.0 disables this check (default 0.0).\nmin_epsilon_decrease::Float64: Stop after any generation where the proportional (relative) decrease in epsilon is less than this value. Formally, stop when (ε_{t-1} - ε_t) / ε_{t-1} < min_epsilon_decrease. A value of 0.1 requires at least a 10 % reduction each generation; 0.0 disables this check (default 0.0).\nmin_ess_fraction::Float64: Stop after any generation where the effective sample size as a fraction of population_size falls below this value. ESS = 1 / Σwᵢ². A value of 0.2 stops when fewer than 20 % of particles carry meaningful weight. 0.0 disables this check (default 0.0).\naccept_overflow::Bool: When true, keep all particles that pass the epsilon threshold in a batch, even if their count exceeds population_size. population_size then acts as a minimum rather than an exact target. When false (default), any overflow from the final batch is discarded so each generation contains exactly population_size particles. The ESS stopping criterion always compares against population_size regardless of this flag; the log line reports ESS as a fraction of the actual accepted count.\ncdf_grid_k::Union{Nothing,Int}: Base grid resolution for CDF-grid snapping. When set, proposal CDF coordinates are snapped to the dyadic grid {j/2^k : j=1,...,2^k-1} at generation 1, with effective resolution doubling each generation (2^(k+t-1) points). The snap box radius at generation t is 1/2^(k+t). Bank entries within the snap box are reused without re-simulation; if none, the proposal snaps to the grid for a fresh simulation. Duplicate monad proposals within a generation are allowed — the same monad can appear as multiple particles (each receiving its own weight). The bank is updated between generations with all newly evaluated monads. Generation 1 uses a Sobol low-discrepancy sequence for good prior coverage. nothing (default) disables snapping. At runtime, the effective base resolution is raised to satisfy (2^k-1)^d ≥ population_size; an @info is emitted when this correction fires.\nmax_evaluations::Union{Nothing,Int}: Maximum total number of evaluated particles (monads) across the entire calibration run. Each entry in any evaluate_batch result counts as one evaluation, regardless of whether the monad was a fresh simulation or a bank reuse. When the budget is reached, the current batch is fully processed, the completed portion of the current generation is saved (possibly with fewer than population_size accepted particles), and the run stops. nothing (default) disables the budget. Persisted to method.toml.\nstore_rejected::Bool: When true, each GenerationResult (for generations t > 1) stores all rejected proposal CDF coordinates in rejected_proposals::DataFrame (same column names as particles; converted to target space at plot time). Useful for the :transition visualization recipe, which can also recover rejected proposals from disk via a lazy lookup when this is false (default). Not persisted to disk; always nothing on resume and for generation 1.\n\nExamples\n\n# Fully adaptive run\nmethod = ABCSMC(population_size=200, max_nr_populations=15, minimum_epsilon=0.005)\n\n# Manual epsilon schedule with acceptance-rate safety stop\nmethod = ABCSMC(\n    population_size = 100,\n    epsilon_schedule = [50.0, 20.0, 5.0, 1.0],\n    min_acceptance_rate = 0.01,\n)\n\nresult = runCalibration(problem, method)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.ABCSMC"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.AbstractCalibrationMethod","page":"Calibration","text":"AbstractCalibrationMethod\n\nAbstract supertype for calibration methods. Concrete subtypes define the algorithm and its settings.\n\nCurrent implementations:\n\nABCSMC: Approximate Bayesian Computation — Sequential Monte Carlo\n\nFuture implementations may include GP-accelerated ABC, Bayesian optimization, etc.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.AbstractCalibrationMethod"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.ComponentwiseKernel","page":"Calibration","text":"ComponentwiseKernel(scale = 2.0)\n\nDiagonal-covariance perturbation kernel: independent 1D Gaussians per parameter, using scale × weighted_variance for each dimension. More robust than GaussianKernel in high dimensions where off-diagonal covariance estimation is noisy with small populations.\n\nscale semantics are identical to GaussianKernel.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.ComponentwiseKernel"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.GaussianKernel","page":"Calibration","text":"GaussianKernel(scale = 2.0)\n\nFull multivariate Gaussian perturbation kernel using scale × weighted_covariance (Beaumont et al. 2009).\n\nscale may be a scalar Float64 (constant across generations) or a Vector{Float64} generation schedule: generation t uses scale[min(t, end)].\n\nDefault scale=2.0 preserves the Beaumont et al. rule of thumb.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.GaussianKernel"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.LocalNNCovKernel","page":"Calibration","text":"LocalNNCovKernel(; k = 10, scale = 1.0)\n\nPer-particle local covariance kernel: for each previous-generation particle j, its perturbation kernel is N(θ_j, scale × Σ_local,j) where Σ_local,j is the sample covariance of particle j's k nearest neighbors. Unlike LocalNNKernel, the covariance direction adapts locally — useful for banana-shaped or anisotropic posteriors.\n\nCost: N Cholesky factorizations per generation (one per particle). For N ≤ 5000, d ≤ 10, this is fast in practice.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.LocalNNCovKernel"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.LocalNNKernel","page":"Calibration","text":"LocalNNKernel(; k = 10, scale = 1.0)\n\nPer-particle bandwidth kernel: h_j = scale × dist(θ_j, θ_j^{(k)}) where θ_j^{(k)} is the k-th nearest neighbor of particle j (Chebyshev metric). All particles share the global weighted covariance shape Σ_global; only the scalar bandwidth h_j varies per particle. Proposal for parent j: N(θ_j, h_j² × Σ_global).\n\nBandwidth shrinks automatically as the particle cloud concentrates, so an explicit generation schedule is not needed. Requires only one Cholesky factorization per generation.\n\nFor fully local covariance (adapts direction as well as scale), see LocalNNCovKernel.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.LocalNNKernel"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.resumeABC-Tuple{Calibration}","page":"Calibration","text":"resumeABC(calibration::Calibration;\n          problem::Union{Nothing,CalibrationProblem}=nothing,\n          method::Union{Nothing,ABCSMC}=nothing,\n          run_kwargs::NamedTuple=(;)) → ABCResult\n\nResume a stopped or crashed ABC-SMC calibration from saved generation files.\n\nLoads ABCSMC settings from method.toml and the calibration problem from problem.jld2 (both written by the original run), then continues from the next generation.\n\nWhen problem= is required\n\nIf the original CalibrationProblem contained any anonymous functions (summary_statistic, distance, or any LatentVariation maps / inverse_maps defined as lambdas), JLD2 cannot serialize them and saves only a partial manifest.  In that case resumeABC requires the full problem to be re-supplied:\n\nresumeABC(Calibration(42); problem=my_problem)\n\nThe re-supplied problem is validated against the saved manifest:\n\nStructural check: parameter count, source types, names, targets, distributions.\nBehavioral check (all parameters): re-supplied maps are applied to the stored CDF particle data and the outputs are compared against the recorded target values.\nRound-trip check (LV parameters with inverse_maps): verifies inverse_map(map(lp)) ≈ lp on stored particles.\n\nEven when problem.jld2 contains a full CalibrationProblem (all named functions), the behavioral and round-trip checks are re-run on any LVSource parameters, because JLD2 saves only the function's name — if the function was redefined between runs the new definition is used silently. Passing problem= in this case forces full validation.\n\nArguments\n\nproblem: The original CalibrationProblem. Required when anonymous functions were present at save time; optional otherwise (loads from problem.jld2).\nmethod: Override the saved ABCSMC settings. If nothing, loads from method.toml.\nrun_kwargs: Forwarded to each run(sampling; ...) call.\nprogress: Console-feedback verbosity (:auto, :none, :generation, :batch, :bar); same semantics as in runABC.\n\nExamples\n\n# Session restart — only calibration ID needed (all named functions)\nresult = resumeABC(Calibration(42))\n\n# Re-supply the problem when anonymous functions were used\nresult = resumeABC(Calibration(42); problem=my_problem)\n\n# Override max generations on resume\nresult = resumeABC(Calibration(42); method=ABCSMC(max_nr_populations=15))\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.resumeABC"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.runABC-Tuple{CalibrationProblem}","page":"Calibration","text":"runABC(problem::CalibrationProblem; kwargs...) → ABCResult\n\nRun ABC-SMC parameter calibration. Convenience wrapper that constructs an ABCSMC method from keyword arguments and delegates to runCalibration.\n\nThe full CalibrationProblem is serialized to problem.jld2, enabling resumeABC(Calibration(id)) with no further arguments after a crash or session restart.\n\nKeyword Arguments\n\npopulation_size::Int=100, max_nr_populations::Int=10, minimum_epsilon::Float64=0.01, epsilon_quantile::Float64=0.5, perturbation_kernel::AbstractKernel=GaussianKernel()\nepsilon_schedule::Union{Nothing,Vector{Float64}}=nothing: explicit decreasing thresholds.\nmin_acceptance_rate::Float64=0.0, min_epsilon_decrease::Float64=0.0, min_ess_fraction::Float64=0.0: early stopping thresholds.\naccept_overflow::Bool=false: when true, keep all epsilon-passing particles per batch (population_size becomes a minimum, not an exact target).\ncdf_grid_k::Union{Nothing,Int}=nothing: base CDF-grid resolution for simulation bank snapping. When set, proposals are snapped to a dyadic grid of resolution 2^k in CDF space, tightening by one level each generation. If a SimulationBank has compatible existing monads, they are reused in preference to running new simulations; an empty bank is silently skipped and snapping proceeds normally.\nmax_evaluations::Union{Nothing,Int}=nothing: maximum total evaluated particles across the entire run. When reached, the current batch completes and the run stops (the generation may have fewer than population_size accepted particles).\nrun_kwargs::NamedTuple=(;): forwarded to each run(sampling; ...) call.\ndescription::String=\"\": stored in the calibrations DB row.\nprogress::Symbol=:auto: console-feedback verbosity (:auto, :none, :generation, :batch, :bar). :auto shows a live progress bar on an interactive terminal and per-generation milestones otherwise.\n\nExamples\n\nresult = runABC(problem; population_size=200, max_nr_populations=5)\ndf, weights = posterior(result)\nprintln(\"Posterior mean: \", sum(df[!, \"overall/max_time\"] .* weights))\n\n# Resume after crash\nresult2 = resumeABC(result.calibration)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.runABC"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.runCalibration-Tuple{CalibrationProblem, ABCSMC}","page":"Calibration","text":"runCalibration(problem::CalibrationProblem, method::ABCSMC; description=\"\") → ABCResult\n\nRun ABC-SMC calibration. See ABCSMC for method settings.\n\nThe full CalibrationProblem is serialized to problem.jld2 enabling resumeABC(Calibration(id)) with no further arguments. Per-generation results are saved in two forms:\n\ngenerations/generation_{t}.csv: human-readable target parameter values.\ngenerations/generation_cdfs/generation_{t}.csv: raw CDF coordinates for exact resume.\n\nArguments\n\nrun_kwargs::NamedTuple=(;): forwarded to each run(sampling; quiet=true, ...) call.\ndescription::String=\"\": stored in the calibrations DB row.\nprogress::Symbol=:auto: console-feedback verbosity. One of :auto, :none, :generation, :batch, :bar. :auto resolves to :bar on an interactive terminal and :generation otherwise. See _resolveVerbosity.\n\nExamples\n\nmethod = ABCSMC(population_size=200, max_nr_populations=5)\nresult = runCalibration(problem, method)\ndf, weights = posterior(result)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.runCalibration"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.mseDistance-Tuple{Dict{String}, Dict{String}}","page":"Calibration","text":"mseDistance(simulated, observed)\n\nBuilt-in distance functions for use as distance in a CalibrationProblem. Three calling conventions are supported:\n\nmseDistance(sim::Dict{String,<:Any}, obs::Dict{String,<:Any}) — mean of per-key MSE contributions, averaged across all keys in obs. Scalar keys contribute (sim−obs)²; vector keys contribute mean((sim .- obs).^2). Keys missing from sim are treated as zero. Keys in sim not in obs are ignored (with a one-time warning).\nmseDistance(sim::AbstractVector{<:Real}, obs::AbstractVector{<:Real}) — sum of squared differences Σ(simᵢ−obsᵢ)². Throws DimensionMismatch when lengths differ.\nmseDistance(sim::Real, obs::Real) — squared difference (sim − obs)².\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.mseDistance"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.calibrationFolder-Tuple{Int64}","page":"Calibration","text":"calibrationFolder(calibration_id::Int)\n\nReturn the path to the output folder for a given calibration run.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.calibrationFolder"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.calibrationMonadIDs-Tuple{Calibration}","page":"Calibration","text":"calibrationMonadIDs(calibration::Calibration) → Vector{Int}\n\nReturn all monad IDs evaluated during this calibration run, aggregated across all per-generation monad files (generation_*_monads.csv) in evaluation order.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.calibrationMonadIDs"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.calibrationsDir-Tuple{}","page":"Calibration","text":"calibrationsDir()\n\nReturn the path to the top-level calibrations output directory: data/outputs/calibrations/.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.calibrationsDir"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.createCalibration-Tuple{String}","page":"Calibration","text":"createCalibration(method::String; description::String=\"\") → Calibration\n\nInsert a new row into the calibrations table and create the output folder. Returns the resulting Calibration object.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.createCalibration"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.CVSource","page":"Calibration","text":"CVSource <: AbstractCalibrationSource\n\nTracks that a CalibrationParameter originated from a CoVariation{DistributedVariation}. Stored for display-format CSV reconstruction and JLD2 persistence.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.CVSource"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.DVSource","page":"Calibration","text":"DVSource <: AbstractCalibrationSource\n\nTracks that a CalibrationParameter originated from a DistributedVariation. Stored for display-format CSV reconstruction and JLD2 persistence.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.DVSource"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.LVSource","page":"Calibration","text":"LVSource <: AbstractCalibrationSource\n\nTracks that a CalibrationParameter originated from a user-supplied LatentVariation{<:Distribution}. Stored for display-format CSV reconstruction and JLD2 persistence.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.LVSource"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._StrippedLVSource","page":"Calibration","text":"_StrippedLVSource\n\nSerializable substitute for LVSource used when the associated LatentVariation contains anonymous-function maps that JLD2 cannot serialize. Stores all data fields of the LatentVariation (distributions, names, targets, types) but omits maps and inverse_maps. Saved by _saveProblem when anonymous functions are detected; at resume time the user must re-supply the full CalibrationProblem and the maps are validated against stored particle data.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._StrippedLVSource"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._displayColumns-Tuple{CalibrationParameter}","page":"Calibration","text":"_displayColumns(cp::CalibrationParameter) → Vector{String}\n\nReturn the column names used in human-readable generation CSVs for this parameter.\n\nDVSource: one column — variationName(dv), i.e. the user-supplied name (or its shortVariationName default). This is the friendly name, not the raw DB column.\nCVSource: one column per covaried target — variationName(v) for each individual DistributedVariation in the CoVariation.\nLVSource: latent parameter names (user-supplied, actual sampled values not CDFs) followed by columnName.(lv.targets) for the target columns.\n\nThe mapping from display names back to DB column names is written to parameters.toml by _writeParametersTOML.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._displayColumns"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._distString-Tuple{Distributions.Distribution}","page":"Calibration","text":"_distString(d::Distribution) → String\n\nReturn a concise human-readable string representation of a distribution for use in parameters.toml. Uses the type name and named field values (e.g. \"Uniform(a=0.0, b=1.0)\", \"Normal(μ=0.0, σ=1.0)\"). Not intended for eval/roundtrip.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._distString"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._isAnonymousFunction-Tuple{Function}","page":"Calibration","text":"_isAnonymousFunction(f::Function) → Bool\n\nReturn true if f is an anonymous function or compiler-generated closure (i.e. nameof(f) starts with #). Named functions defined with function foo(...) end or foo(...) = ... return false.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._isAnonymousFunction"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._particleRowToDisplay-Tuple{CalibrationParameter, Vector{Float64}}","page":"Calibration","text":"_particleRowToDisplay(cp::CalibrationParameter, cdf_vals::Vector{Float64}) → Vector{Float64}\n\nConvert a row of CDF coordinates to human-readable display values.\n\nDVSource / CVSource: returns the actual target parameter value(s). The internal LatentVariation applies quantile(prior, cdf) (and the user's map) to obtain interpretable values.\nLVSource: returns the latent parameter samples — i.e., quantile(D_i, cdf_i) for each latent dimension — followed by the target parameter values.\n\nThe returned vector corresponds element-wise to _displayColumns.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._particleRowToDisplay"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._toCalibrationParameter-Tuple{DistributedVariation}","page":"Calibration","text":"_toCalibrationParameter(av::AbstractVariation) → CalibrationParameter\n\nConvert a user-supplied variation to a CalibrationParameter.\n\nAccepted inputs:\n\nDistributedVariation → DVSource-wrapped parameter\nCoVariation{DistributedVariation} → CVSource-wrapped parameter\nLatentVariation{<:Distribution} → LVSource-wrapped parameter\n\nRejected inputs throw ArgumentError.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._toCalibrationParameter"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.AbstractKernel","page":"Calibration","text":"AbstractKernel\n\nAbstract supertype for ABC-SMC perturbation kernels. Concrete subtypes define how particles are perturbed between generations.\n\nCurrent implementations:\n\nGaussianKernel: Full multivariate Gaussian using weighted covariance.\nComponentwiseKernel: Diagonal covariance — independent 1D Gaussians per parameter.\nLocalNNKernel: Global covariance shape scaled per-particle by k-NN bandwidth.\nLocalNNCovKernel: Per-particle local covariance estimated from k nearest neighbors.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.AbstractKernel"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._ProblemManifest","page":"Calibration","text":"_ProblemManifest\n\nSerializable representation of a CalibrationProblem. Always written to problem.jld2 by _saveProblem — the full CalibrationProblem is never serialized directly (DVSource/CVSource closures would get session-specific compiler names that break across Julia sessions).\n\nNamed summary_statistic and distance functions are stored directly (JLD2 saves the function name); anonymous ones become nothing. Named LVSource map functions are stored directly inside their LVSource; anonymous ones become _StrippedLVSource. DVSource and CVSource are always stored as-is (their closures are never serialized — maps are always reconstructed from source data at load time via _manifestToProblem).\n\nAt resume time:\n\nComplete manifest (no nothing fields, no _StrippedLVSource): _manifestToProblem reconstructs the CalibrationProblem automatically.\nIncomplete manifest: user must re-supply the full problem via problem= in resumeABC.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._ProblemManifest"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._buildDisplayDF-Tuple{GenerationResult, Vector{CalibrationParameter}}","page":"Calibration","text":"_buildDisplayDF(gen::GenerationResult, cps::Vector{CalibrationParameter}) → DataFrame\n\nBuild the human-readable display DataFrame for a completed generation.\n\nFor each CalibrationParameter, raw CDF coordinates in gen.particles are converted to interpretable values via _particleRowToDisplay. If cps is empty, returns a copy of gen.particles unchanged (useful for tests that build GenerationResult directly).\n\nweight, distance, and monad_id columns are always appended.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._buildDisplayDF"},{"category":"function","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._buildEvaluateBatch","page":"Calibration","text":"_buildEvaluateBatch(problem, calibration, max_nr_populations, run_kwargs) → Function\n\nBuild the evaluate_batch callback expected by _runABCSMC. The returned function:\n\nTakes (t::Int, proposals::Vector{Tuple{Dict{String,Float64}, Union{Nothing,Int}}}) — generation index and one (latent_cdfs, known_mid) pair per proposed particle. known_mid is an Int for bank/mid-generation reuses (monad already in DB) and nothing for fresh grid snaps (monad created here).\nCreates or retrieves a Monad for each proposal: known-mid proposals use Monad(mid; ...) (one SELECT); nothing-mid proposals use _createMonadForParams (INSERT OR IGNORE + SELECT).\nRecords all monad IDs evaluated so far in this generation to generation_{NNN}_monads.csv using compressIDs before launching simulations (crash safety). The file is overwritten on each batch call so it always contains a single fully-compressed entry spanning all batches in the generation.\nAssembles all monads into a Sampling and calls run(sampling; quiet=true, run_kwargs...). When verbosity is :batch or higher a batch-start line is logged; when it is :bar a live per-simulation progress bar is rendered via the runner's on_progress hook.\nReturns a Vector{Tuple{Float64,Int}} (distance, monad_id) in proposal order.\n\nverbosity is a resolved level (see _resolveVerbosity); a per-generation batch counter is maintained across calls so batch milestones can be numbered within each generation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._buildEvaluateBatch"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._createMonadForParams-Tuple{CalibrationProblem, Dict{String, Float64}}","page":"Calibration","text":"_createMonadForParams(problem, latent_cdfs) → Monad\n\nCreate a Monad at the given parameter values. latent_cdfs maps each latent parameter name to its CDF value (drawn by the ABC-SMC algorithm). Each CalibrationParameter in problem.parameters converts those CDF values into concrete target DiscreteVariations via its lv's maps. Uses use_previous=true so that exact-match reuse of existing simulations happens transparently.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._createMonadForParams"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._findLastGenerationCSVs-Tuple{Calibration}","page":"Calibration","text":"_findLastGenerationCSVs(calibration) → Union{Nothing, Tuple{String,String}}\n\nReturn (cdf_csv_path, display_csv_path) for the last saved generation, or nothing if no generations have been written yet.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._findLastGenerationCSVs"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._generationMonadsPath-Tuple{Calibration, Int64, Int64}","page":"Calibration","text":"_generationMonadsPath(calibration, t, max_nr_populations) → String\n\nPath to the monad-ID record for generation t: generations/generation_{NNN}_monads.csv.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._generationMonadsPath"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._generationTag-Tuple{Int64, Int64}","page":"Calibration","text":"_generationTag(t, max_nr_populations) → String\n\nZero-padded generation index string, e.g. \"03\" for t=3, max=10 or \"003\" for max=100.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._generationTag"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._isCompleteManifest-Tuple{ModelManager._ProblemManifest}","page":"Calibration","text":"_isCompleteManifest(manifest::_ProblemManifest) → Bool\n\nReturn true when manifest can be reconstructed into a full CalibrationProblem without re-supplying the original problem — i.e. neither summary_statistic nor distance is nothing, and no source is a _StrippedLVSource.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._isCompleteManifest"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._loadGenerations-Tuple{Calibration, Vector{String}, Int64}","page":"Calibration","text":"_loadGenerations(calibration, param_names, max_nr_populations) → Vector{GenerationResult}\n\nLoad saved generation results from generation_cdfs/ (raw CDF coordinates), reconstructing the internal particle state needed for resumeABC.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._loadGenerations"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._loadMethod-Tuple{Calibration}","page":"Calibration","text":"_loadMethod(calibration::Calibration) → ABCSMC\n\nLoad saved ABCSMC settings from method.toml.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._loadMethod"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._loadProblem-Tuple{Calibration}","page":"Calibration","text":"_loadProblem(calibration::Calibration) → _ProblemManifest\n\nLoad problem.jld2 and return a _ProblemManifest.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._loadProblem"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._manifestToProblem-Tuple{ModelManager._ProblemManifest}","page":"Calibration","text":"_manifestToProblem(manifest::_ProblemManifest) → CalibrationProblem\n\nReconstruct a CalibrationProblem from a complete manifest. DVSource and CVSource maps are always regenerated from their distribution data (avoiding any reliance on session-specific closure names). LVSource functions are used as stored.\n\nErrors if any source is a _StrippedLVSource (use _isCompleteManifest first).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._manifestToProblem"},{"category":"function","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._saveGeneration","page":"Calibration","text":"_saveGeneration(calibration, gen, max_nr_populations[, cps])\n\nSave a generation result. Writes:\n\ngenerations/generation_{NNN}.csv: human-readable display format.\ngenerations/generation_cdfs/generation_{NNN}.csv: raw CDF coordinates for resume.\ngenerations/generation_{NNN}.toml: generation-level metadata.\n\nWhen called with the 2-directory form _saveGeneration(dir, cdf_dir, gen, ...), the caller controls both directories (used in tests).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._saveGeneration"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._saveMethod-Tuple{Calibration, ABCSMC}","page":"Calibration","text":"_saveMethod(calibration::Calibration, method::ABCSMC)\n\nSave the ABCSMC settings to method.toml for resume support.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._saveMethod"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._saveProblem-Tuple{Calibration, CalibrationProblem}","page":"Calibration","text":"_saveProblem(calibration::Calibration, problem::CalibrationProblem)\n\nSerialize the CalibrationProblem to problem.jld2 as a _ProblemManifest.\n\nAlways saves the manifest format — never the full CalibrationProblem directly — to avoid relying on session-specific compiler names for DVSource/CVSource closures.\n\nNamed summary_statistic, distance, and LatentVariation map functions are preserved in the manifest (JLD2 stores them by name). Anonymous ones become nothing / _StrippedLVSource, and a @warn is emitted instructing the user to re-supply the problem at resume time.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._saveProblem"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._validateLVMaps-Tuple{CalibrationProblem, Calibration}","page":"Calibration","text":"_validateLVMaps(problem, calibration; rtol=1e-6)\n\nValidate LVSource maps for a problem loaded directly from problem.jld2 (named functions). Because JLD2 saves only the function name (not its implementation), a user could redefine a named function between runs; this check detects that by comparing map outputs against stored particle data. Skipped silently when no LVSource parameters are present or when no generations have been saved yet.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._validateLVMaps"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._validateParticleConsistency-Tuple{Vector{CalibrationParameter}, Any, DataFrames.DataFrame, DataFrames.DataFrame}","page":"Calibration","text":"_validateParticleConsistency(cps, src_list, cdf_df, display_df; rtol=1e-6)\n\nFor each CalibrationParameter in cps:\n\nApplies _particleRowToDisplay to every row of cdf_df and compares against the corresponding display columns in display_df.  Used to confirm that the re-supplied (or JLD2-loaded) maps reproduce the values that were recorded during the original run.\nFor LVSource parameters with inverse_maps, also runs a round-trip check: CDF → latent values → target values → recovered latent values.\n\nOnly runs for parameters whose saved source is _StrippedLVSource OR LVSource (i.e. only for LV parameters); DV/CV parameters are skipped because their maps are deterministically reconstructed from the distribution data and cannot silently change.\n\nWhen called from _validateResumedProblem (user re-supplied all parameters), DV/CV parameters are also validated to catch accidental wrong-problem re-passing.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._validateParticleConsistency"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._validateResumedProblem-Tuple{CalibrationProblem, ModelManager._ProblemManifest, Calibration}","page":"Calibration","text":"_validateResumedProblem(provided, manifest, calibration; rtol=1e-6)\n\nFull validation of a re-supplied CalibrationProblem against a saved _ProblemManifest. Runs structural checks, then behavioral checks against stored particle data for all re-supplied parameters (DV, CV, and LV alike).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._validateResumedProblem"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._validateStructuralMatch-Tuple{CalibrationParameter, Any, Int64}","page":"Calibration","text":"_validateStructuralMatch(cp, src, i)\n\nVerify that CalibrationParameter cp (from the re-supplied problem) is structurally consistent with saved source src. Throws an informative error on mismatch.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._validateStructuralMatch"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._writeParametersTOML-Tuple{Calibration, Vector{CalibrationParameter}}","page":"Calibration","text":"_writeParametersTOML(calibration::Calibration, cps::Vector{CalibrationParameter})\n\nWrite parameters.toml to the calibration output folder. This file provides a human-readable mapping from the display column names used in generations/generation_NNN.csv to the underlying database column names (XML paths), along with the prior distributions.\n\nComplements problem.jld2 (the machine-readable full serialization) for quick inspection without loading Julia.\n\nEach entry in the [[parameters]] array has a source_type field (\"DVSource\", \"CVSource\", or \"LVSource\") and source-specific fields:\n\nDVSource: display_name, db_column, prior\nCVSource: covariation_name, display_names, db_columns, priors\nLVSource: lv_name, latent_display_names, latent_priors, target_display_names, db_columns\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._writeParametersTOML"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._ParticleResult","page":"Calibration","text":"_ParticleResult\n\nInternal: result of evaluating a single ABC-SMC particle.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._ParticleResult"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._adaptEpsilon-Tuple{Vector{Float64}, Float64, Float64}","page":"Calibration","text":"_adaptEpsilon(distances, quantile_val, minimum_epsilon) → Float64\n\nCompute the next generation's epsilon as a quantile of the current distances, clamped to minimum_epsilon.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._adaptEpsilon"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._bankBoxCandidates-Tuple{ModelManager.SimulationBank, Vector{Float64}, Float64}","page":"Calibration","text":"_bankBoxCandidates(bank, query_cdf, radius) → Vector{Int}\n\nReturn all monad IDs in bank whose CDF coordinates lie within the L∞ box of radius around query_cdf along with their index in the bank. An empty vector is returned when the bank is empty. query_cdf need not be snapped to the grid.\n\nUses the pre-built KD-tree (bank.tree) with the Chebyshev metric for O(log n + k) queries instead of a linear scan.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._bankBoxCandidates"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._bankBoxRadius-Tuple{Int64}","page":"Calibration","text":"_bankBoxRadius(k_eff) → Float64\n\nReturn the L∞ box radius for bank lookup at effective grid resolution k_eff.\n\nEqual to half the grid spacing at that resolution: 1 / 2^(k_eff + 1).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._bankBoxRadius"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._buildGenerationResult-Tuple{Int64, Vector{ModelManager._ParticleResult}, Vector{Float64}, Int64, Int64, Vector{String}}","page":"Calibration","text":"_buildGenerationResult(t, accepted, weights, n_evaluations, n_accepted, param_names) → GenerationResult\n\nAssemble a GenerationResult from accepted particles, computing diagnostics.\n\nn_accepted is the total number of proposals that passed the epsilon criterion across all batches in this generation — not capped at population_size. This is larger than length(accepted) when the final batch overshoots the target population, and gives the correct (unbiased) acceptance rate for the proposal-distribution/epsilon pair.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._buildGenerationResult"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._cdfToGridKey-Tuple{Vector{Float64}, Int64}","page":"Calibration","text":"_cdfToGridKey(snapped_cdf, k_eff) → Vector{Int}\n\nConvert a snapped CDF vector to integer grid indices for use as a set membership key.\n\nEach component is round(Int, snapped_cdf[i] * 2^k_eff), which recovers the integer j from j/2^k_eff. Safe to call only on already-snapped values (no rounding error).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._cdfToGridKey"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._computeWeights-Tuple{Vector{ModelManager._ParticleResult}, Vector{String}, GenerationResult, ModelManager.AbstractFittedKernel}","page":"Calibration","text":"_computeWeights(accepted, param_names, prev, fitted) → Vector{Float64}\n\nCompute and normalize importance weights for generation t > 1.\n\nw_i = π(θ_i) / Σ_j [ w_j^{t-1} · K(θ_i | θ_j^{t-1}) ]\n\nwhere π is the prior density and K is evaluated via _kernelDensity.\n\nABC-SMC operates entirely in CDF-coordinate space where all dimensions have a Uniform(0,1) prior, so π(u) = 1.0 for every particle regardless of the underlying latent parameter distributions.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._computeWeights"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._effectiveK-Tuple{Int64, Int64}","page":"Calibration","text":"_effectiveK(k_base, t) → Int\n\nReturn the effective CDF grid resolution at generation t with base k_base.\n\nThe grid doubles each generation: at generation t the grid is G(k_eff) = {j/2^k_eff : j=1,...,2^k_eff-1} where k_eff = k_base + t - 1.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._effectiveK"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._fitKernel-Tuple{GaussianKernel, DataFrames.DataFrame, Vector{Float64}, Vector{String}, Int64}","page":"Calibration","text":"_fitKernel(kernel, particles, weights, param_names, t; k_eff) → AbstractFittedKernel\n\nFit the perturbation kernel to the previous generation's weighted particles. Called once per generation before proposals are drawn.\n\nk_eff is the effective CDF grid resolution for this generation. When provided, the minimum diagonal variance is set to (1/2^(k_eff+1))^2 so perturbations span at least one grid cell even if particles have collapsed to a single point.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._fitKernel"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._kernelDensity-Tuple{ModelManager.FittedGaussianKernel, Dict{String, Float64}, Dict{String, Float64}, Vector{String}}","page":"Calibration","text":"_kernelDensity(fitted, from_particle, to_particle, param_names) → Float64\n\nEvaluate the kernel density K(to | from) — used in the importance weight denominator.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._kernelDensity"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._lookupAndSnap-Tuple{Dict{String, Float64}, Vector{String}, Int64, Float64, ModelManager.SimulationBank, Vector{Tuple{Vector{Float64}, Int64}}}","page":"Calibration","text":"_lookupAndSnap(latent_cdfs, param_names, k_eff, radius, bank, mid_gen_additions)\n→ Tuple{Dict{String,Float64}, Union{Nothing,Int}}\n\nCore bank-lookup and fallback-snap step for a single proposed CDF vector.\n\nLookup order: both the KD-tree bank and the mid_gen_additions list are searched concurrently. If any candidates lie within the L∞ box of radius around latent_cdfs, one is chosen at random and its stored coordinates and monad ID are returned. Otherwise the proposal is snapped to the nearest interior grid point of G(k_eff) and nothing is returned for the monad ID (resolved later by evaluate_batch).\n\nDuplicate monad IDs are intentional — the same monad may appear as multiple particles within a generation, each receiving its own weight.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._lookupAndSnap"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._proposeParticle-Tuple{ModelManager.FittedGaussianKernel, Dict{String, Float64}, Vector{String}}","page":"Calibration","text":"_proposeParticle(fitted, parent_particle, param_names) → Dict or nothing\n\nPerturb a parent particle using the fitted kernel. Returns nothing if the perturbed particle falls outside [0, 1] in any dimension (rejection step).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._proposeParticle"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._runABCSMC-Tuple{ABCSMC, Vector{String}, Vector{<:Distributions.Distribution}, Function, Function}","page":"Calibration","text":"_runABCSMC(method, param_names, priors, evaluate_batch, on_generation;\n           bank, start_generations, verbosity)\n\nRun the ABC-SMC algorithm. This is the framework-agnostic core.\n\nGeneration 1 samples fresh from the prior (no warm-start bias). Exact-match reuse of previously evaluated parameter points is handled by the caller's evaluate_batch (e.g. Monad(...; use_previous=true)) — this keeps the gen-1 population an unbiased prior sample while still avoiding redundant simulation work.\n\nArguments\n\nmethod::ABCSMC: Algorithm settings.\nparam_names::Vector{String}: Parameter names (column order in results).\npriors::Vector{<:Distribution}: Prior distributions, one per parameter.\nevaluate_batch::Function: (t::Int, proposals::Vector{Tuple{Dict{String,Float64},Union{Nothing,Int}}}) → Vector{Tuple{Float64,Any}}. Each proposal is (latent_cdfs, known_mid) where known_mid is an Int for bank/mid-generation reuses and nothing for fresh grid snaps. Returns (distance, monad_id) for each in the same order. Receiving t allows the caller to route provenance records to a per-generation file.\non_generation::Function: (gen::GenerationResult) → nothing. Called after each completed generation (for persistence / logging).\nbank::SimulationBank: Pre-built registry of existing monads in CDF space, built once at calibration start by _buildSimulationBank. Passed through to generation runners for use by the CDF-grid snapping proposal logic. Defaults to an empty bank (snapping disabled).\nstart_generations::Vector{GenerationResult}: Previously-completed generations to resume from (empty for a fresh run).\nverbosity::Symbol: Resolved console-feedback level (see _resolveVerbosity). :generation (the default) and higher emit the generation-start, generation-finish, and stopping-reason @info lines; :none suppresses them entirely.\n\nReturns\n\nVector{GenerationResult}: All completed generations (including resumed ones).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._runABCSMC"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._runFirstGeneration-Tuple{ABCSMC, Vector{String}, Vector{<:Distributions.Distribution}, Function, ModelManager.SimulationBank}","page":"Calibration","text":"_runFirstGeneration(method, param_names, priors, evaluate_batch, bank;\n                    k_base_eff, mid_gen_additions, budget, budget_hit)\n\nRun generation 1: place population_size particles using a Sobol low-discrepancy sequence and accept all.\n\nGeneration 1 uses a Sobol sequence (from Sobol.jl) instead of a random prior sample to guarantee good prior coverage: no region of (0,1)^d is over- or under-represented. The sequence naturally avoids 0 and 1.\n\nWithout CDF-grid snapping: evaluates the Sobol points directly as a single batch.\n\nWith CDF-grid snapping: each Sobol point is passed through _lookupAndSnap. Nearby bank or mid-generation monads are reused (mid known); otherwise the point snaps to the base grid (mid = nothing, resolved by evaluate_batch). mid_gen_additions is updated after the batch with newly resolved monads.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._runFirstGeneration"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._runSubsequentGeneration-Tuple{ABCSMC, Vector{String}, Vector{<:Distributions.Distribution}, Function, GenerationResult, Float64, Int64, ModelManager.SimulationBank}","page":"Calibration","text":"_runSubsequentGeneration(method, param_names, priors, evaluate_batch, prev, epsilon, t, bank;\n                         k_base_eff, mid_gen_additions, budget, budget_hit)\n\nRun generation t > 1: resample from previous generation, perturb, accept if distance ≤ epsilon.\n\nProposals are batched and evaluated concurrently; batching repeats until population_size accepted particles are collected. Batch sizing: ceil(n_needed / acceptance_rate_est), updated after each round.\n\nWith CDF-grid snapping: each perturbed proposal is processed by _lookupAndSnap. Duplicate monad IDs are allowed within and across batches — the same monad may appear as multiple particles, each receiving its own weight. mid_gen_additions accumulates all new grid evaluations within this generation and is shared between batches (growing throughout).\n\nBudget accounting is delegated to _updateBudget!. When budget_hit is set, the completed portion of the generation is returned (possibly fewer than population_size).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._runSubsequentGeneration"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._sampleFromPrior-Tuple{Vector{String}}","page":"Calibration","text":"_sampleFromPrior(param_names) → Dict{String,Float64}\n\nDraw one CDF value from the joint prior (independent marginals).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._sampleFromPrior"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._snapToCDFGrid-Tuple{Float64, Int64}","page":"Calibration","text":"_snapToCDFGrid(u, k_eff) → Float64\n\nSnap a scalar CDF value u ∈ [0,1] to the nearest interior grid point at resolution k_eff, i.e. the nearest value in {j/2^k_eff : j=1,...,2^k_eff-1}.\n\nBoundary clamping: u=0 snaps to 1/2^k_eff; u=1 snaps to (2^k_eff-1)/2^k_eff.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._snapToCDFGrid"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._stoppingReason-Tuple{ABCSMC, Vector{GenerationResult}}","page":"Calibration","text":"_stoppingReason(method, generations; budget_hit=false) → Union{Nothing, String}\n\nCheck all stopping criteria against the most recent generation. Returns a human-readable reason string if any criterion is met, nothing otherwise.\n\nbudget_hit=true is checked first and supersedes all other criteria.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._stoppingReason"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._systematicResample-Tuple{Vector{Float64}, Int64}","page":"Calibration","text":"_systematicResample(weights, n) → Vector{Int}\n\nDraw n parent indices from a categorical distribution defined by weights using systematic resampling (Kitagawa 1996).\n\nA single uniform draw u ~ Uniform(0, 1/n) places n evenly-spaced points u, u+1/n, ..., u+(n-1)/n on [0, 1]. A single left-to-right walk through the cumulative weight distribution assigns each point to the particle whose CDF interval contains it. The result is that particle i appears exactly ⌊n·wᵢ⌋ or ⌈n·wᵢ⌉ times — strictly lower variance than n independent multinomial draws, at O(n) cost.\n\nNote: n is the number of samples to draw, not the number of parent-generation particles. When n is small relative to the population some parents will receive 0 copies, which is correct; callers that need more proposals simply call again with a fresh u.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._systematicResample"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._updateBankFromGeneration-Tuple{ModelManager.SimulationBank, Vector{Tuple{Vector{Float64}, Int64}}}","page":"Calibration","text":"_updateBankFromGeneration(bank, mid_gen_additions) → SimulationBank\n\nAdd all newly evaluated monads from mid_gen_additions to the bank and rebuild the KD-tree. Called between generations so the next generation's lookups can reuse monads evaluated in all prior generations.\n\nMonads already in the bank (by monad ID) are skipped to avoid duplicates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._updateBankFromGeneration"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._updateBudget!-Tuple{Ref{Int64}, Ref{Bool}, Int64, Union{Nothing, Int64}}","page":"Calibration","text":"_updateBudget!(budget, budget_hit, n, max_evaluations)\n\nIncrement budget[] by n and set budget_hit[] = true if max_evaluations is reached. No-op when max_evaluations is nothing.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._updateBudget!"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._updateMidGenAdditions!-Tuple{Vector{Tuple{Vector{Float64}, Int64}}, Vector{Tuple{Dict{String, Float64}, Union{Nothing, Int64}}}, Vector{<:Tuple}, ModelManager.SimulationBank, Vector{String}}","page":"Calibration","text":"_updateMidGenAdditions!(mid_gen_additions, proposals, results, bank, param_names)\n\nUpdate mid_gen_additions after an evaluate_batch call. For each proposal whose monad ID was nothing (a fresh grid snap), the resolved monad ID from results is recorded alongside the proposal's CDF coordinates. Monads already in the bank or already tracked in mid_gen_additions are skipped to maintain the invariant that entries are unique and not in the bank.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._updateMidGenAdditions!"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.SimulationBank","page":"Calibration","text":"SimulationBank\n\nPre-built registry of existing monads whose calibrated parameters lie strictly within the prior support (0,1)^d in CDF space.\n\nBuilt once at calibration start by _buildSimulationBank and reused across all generations for approximate simulation reuse (CDF-grid snapping).\n\nFields\n\nmonad_ids::Vector{Int}: Monad IDs of eligible entries.\ncdf_coords::Matrix{Float64}: n_latent_dims × n_monads matrix of CDF-space coordinates for each eligible monad (columns correspond to monad_ids).\nparam_names::Vector{String}: Latent parameter names matching rows of cdf_coords.\ntree::Union{Nothing,NNTree}: KD-tree (Chebyshev metric) built from cdf_coords for O(log n) L∞ box queries. nothing when the bank is empty.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.SimulationBank"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager.SimulationBank-Tuple{Vector{Int64}, Matrix{Float64}, Vector{String}}","page":"Calibration","text":"SimulationBank(monad_ids, cdf_coords, param_names) → SimulationBank\n\nConvenience constructor that automatically builds the KD-tree from cdf_coords. tree is nothing when monad_ids is empty.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.SimulationBank"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._bankCdfCoords-Tuple{CalibrationParameter, Dict{String, Float64}}","page":"Calibration","text":"_bankCdfCoords(cp::CalibrationParameter, vals::Dict{String,Float64})\n\nConvert stored target-parameter values to latent CDF coordinates for the bank.\n\nReturns a Vector{Float64} with one entry per latent dimension, or nothing when conversion is not possible (missing column or lv.inverse_maps is nothing).\n\nDispatches to _bankCdfCoords(lv, vals) using the inverse maps stored on the LatentVariation. For DVSource- and CVSource-backed variations, inverse maps are auto-constructed at LatentVariation construction time. For LVSource, the user must supply inverse_maps when constructing the LatentVariation; otherwise this returns nothing.\n\nThe CVSource auto-constructed inverse map includes a joint-consistency check: if the recovered latent parameter value lp does not forward-map back to all other targets within relative tolerance 1e-8, the inverse map returns NaN, which is interpreted here as nothing.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._bankCdfCoords"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._bankColDistribution-Tuple{CalibrationParameter, String}","page":"Calibration","text":"_bankColDistribution(cp::CalibrationParameter, col::String) → Distribution or nothing\n\nReturn the prior distribution associated with database column col for cp.\n\nUsed in _buildSimulationBank to determine the prior support bounds for pre-filtering candidate variation rows. Returns nothing for LVSource (no distribution over target space) or when col does not match any target of cp.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._bankColDistribution"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._buildSimulationBank-Tuple{CalibrationProblem}","page":"Calibration","text":"_buildSimulationBank(problem::CalibrationProblem) → SimulationBank\n\nQuery the database for all existing monads compatible with problem whose calibrated parameters lie strictly within (0,1)^d in CDF space.\n\nTerminology used below:\n\nParameter: a user-supplied CalibrationParameter target (may or may not have a column in the variation DB yet).\nColumn: a parameter that already has a column in the variation DB.\n\nCompatibility criteria for each monad:\n\nAll location folder IDs match problem.inputs.\nFor every varied location with no calibrated parameters, the variation ID exactly matches problem.reference_variation_id[loc].\nFor each calibrated location, the variation row must pass:\nNon-calibrated columns must exactly match the reference variation row value.\nCalibrated columns (parameters that already have a column in the DB): the row value must lie in [minimum(dist), maximum(dist)] of the prior.\nCalibrated parameters without a column yet (never varied before): the base value is read from the config file via getColumnDefaults. Because no variation row can give a different value, any failure to read or parse the value, or a value outside the prior support, means no monad anywhere is usable — an empty bank is returned immediately. If the value is within the support, all candidate variation IDs inherit that base value for CDF computation.\nCVSource joint consistency: the latent CDF recovered from the first target must forward-map back to all other targets within relative tolerance 1e-8. Monads that do not lie on the co-variation curve are excluded.\nAll CDF coordinates are strictly in (0, 1).\n\nLVSource parameters without inverse_maps disable the bank (returns empty, informational log emitted). LVSource parameters with inverse_maps are supported: target-space bounds checks are skipped for their columns (Phase 2) and Phase 3 CDF inversion filters via 0 < u < 1.\n\nReturns a SimulationBank with zero columns when no compatible monads exist.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._buildSimulationBank"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._batchProgressCallback-Tuple{Symbol, AbstractString}","page":"Calibration","text":"_batchProgressCallback(verbosity, desc) → Union{Nothing,Function}\n\nBuild the on_progress callback passed to run for a single evaluation batch.\n\nReturns nothing unless verbosity is :bar, in which case it returns a closure that lazily constructs a ProgressMeter.Progress on the :init event (sized to the batch's pending simulation count), advances it on each :step, and finalizes it on :finish. desc labels the bar (e.g. \"  gen 2 batch 1 \").\n\nWhen a batch has zero pending simulations (all monads reused), no bar is created.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._batchProgressCallback"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._logBatchStart-Tuple{Symbol, Int64, Int64, Int64}","page":"Calibration","text":"_logBatchStart(verbosity, t, batch_index, n_proposals)\n\nEmit the batch-start milestone when verbosity is :batch or higher.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._logBatchStart"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._logGenerationStart-Tuple{Symbol, Int64, Union{Nothing, Float64}, Int64}","page":"Calibration","text":"_logGenerationStart(verbosity, t, epsilon, population_size)\n\nEmit the generation-start milestone when verbosity is :generation or higher. epsilon is the target acceptance threshold for generations t > 1, or nothing for generation 1 (prior sampling, no threshold yet).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._logGenerationStart"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#ModelManager._resolveVerbosity-Tuple{Symbol}","page":"Calibration","text":"_resolveVerbosity(progress::Symbol) → Symbol\n\nResolve a user-supplied progress setting to a concrete verbosity level. :auto becomes :bar when stdout is an interactive terminal and :generation otherwise. Any of :none, :generation, :batch, :bar pass through unchanged. Throws an ArgumentError on an unrecognized value.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._resolveVerbosity"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#RecipesBase.apply_recipe-Tuple{AbstractDict{Symbol, Any}, ABCResult, Symbol}","page":"Calibration","text":"plot(result::ABCResult, style::Symbol; kwargs...)\n\nDispatch to specialized visualization recipes for ABCResult:\n\n:ridgeline — posterior narrowing plot: stacked 1D KDE curves per generation per parameter. space keyword: :target (default) or :cdf.\n:transition — generation transition plot: gen-t KDE overlaid with gen-(t+1) proposal points (accepted in green, rejected in red). Keywords:\ngeneration::Int — which generation to show the KDE for (proposals = gen+1). Default: length(result.generations) - 1 (the last complete gen→gen+1 transition). For :ridgeline and other non-transition styles the default is length(result.generations).\nshow_particles::Bool — overlay gen-t particles beneath the KDE (default false).\nspace::Symbol — :target (default) or :cdf.\naggregate_duplicates::Bool — group coincident proposals into bubbles (default true).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"RecipesBase.apply_recipe"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#RecipesBase.apply_recipe-Tuple{AbstractDict{Symbol, Any}, Calibration, Symbol}","page":"Calibration","text":"plot(cal::Calibration, style::Symbol; kwargs...)\n\nDispatch to specialized visualization recipes for a disk-resident Calibration:\n\n:ridgeline — posterior narrowing plot loaded from generation CSVs on disk. No prior (gen 0) is shown since the problem definition cannot always be recovered from disk.\n:transition — generation transition plot. Keywords:\ngeneration::Int — which generation to use as the KDE base (proposals = gen+1). Defaults to the penultimate completed generation.\nshow_particles::Bool — overlay gen-t particles beneath the KDE (default false).\naggregate_duplicates::Bool — group coincident proposals into bubbles (default true).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"RecipesBase.apply_recipe"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/calibration/#RecipesBase.apply_recipe-Tuple{AbstractDict{Symbol, Any}, ModelManager._CornerPlotData}","page":"Calibration","text":"plot(result::ABCResult; generation=:final, space=:target)\nplot(cal::Calibration; generation=:final, space=:target)\n\nCorner plot of an ABC-SMC posterior generation. Diagonal panels show weighted 1D KDE marginals; off-diagonal lower-triangle panels show weighted 2D KDE contours overlaid with a weighted scatter (opacity ∝ weight).\n\ngeneration is an integer index (1-based) or :final (default). space=:target (default) shows biological-unit parameter values; space=:cdf shows ABC internal CDF coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"RecipesBase.apply_recipe"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/xml_utilities/#XML-utilities","page":"XML utilities","text":"Helpers for reading and resolving XML parameter targets.","title":"XML utilities"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/xml_utilities/#Public-API","page":"XML utilities","text":"","title":"Public API"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/xml_utilities/#Private-API","page":"XML utilities","text":"","title":"Private API"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/xml_utilities/#ModelManager.columnNameToXMLPath-Tuple{String}","page":"XML utilities","text":"columnNameToXMLPath(column_name::String)\n\nReturn the XML path corresponding to the given column name.\n\nInverse of columnName.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.columnNameToXMLPath"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/xml_utilities/#ModelManager.getSimpleContent-Tuple{LightXML.XMLDocument, Vector{<:AbstractString}}","page":"XML utilities","text":"getSimpleContent(xml_doc::XMLDocument, xml_path::Vector{<:AbstractString}; required::Bool=true)\n\nGet the content of the element in the XML document that matches the given path. See retrieveElement.\n\nValidates that the element is terminal (has no child elements) and contains non-empty text content. Throws AssertionError if either condition is not met.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.getSimpleContent"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/xml_utilities/#ModelManager.retrieveElement-Tuple{LightXML.XMLDocument, Vector{<:AbstractString}}","page":"XML utilities","text":"retrieveElement(xml_doc::XMLDocument, xml_path::Vector{<:AbstractString}; required::Bool=true)\n\nRetrieve the element in the XML document that matches the given path.\n\nIf required is true, an error is thrown if the element is not found. Otherwise, nothing is returned if the element is not found.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.retrieveElement"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/xml_utilities/#ModelManager.createXMLFile-Tuple{Symbol, AbstractMonad}","page":"XML utilities","text":"createXMLFile(location::Symbol, M::AbstractMonad)\n\nCreate (if needed) the variation XML file for location in monad M and return its path.\n\nThe file is written to <location_folder>/<variations_subfolder>/<location>_variation_<id>.xml. If the file already exists it is returned immediately. After writing, calls postVariationXMLProcessing to allow simulator-specific post-processing.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.createXMLFile"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/xml_utilities/#ModelManager.elementIsTerminal-Tuple{LightXML.XMLElement}","page":"XML utilities","text":"elementIsTerminal(e::XMLElement)\n\nCheck if an XML element is terminal (i.e., has no child elements). Returns true if the element has no children, false otherwise.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.elementIsTerminal"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/xml_utilities/#ModelManager.getChildByAttribute-Tuple{LightXML.XMLElement, Vector{<:AbstractString}}","page":"XML utilities","text":"getChildByAttribute(parent_element::XMLElement, path_element_split::Vector{<:AbstractString})\n\nGet the child element of parent_element that matches the given tag and attribute.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.getChildByAttribute"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/xml_utilities/#ModelManager.getChildByChildContent-Tuple{LightXML.XMLElement, AbstractString}","page":"XML utilities","text":"getChildByChildContent(current_element::XMLElement, path_element::AbstractString)\n\nGet the child element of current_element that matches the given tag and child content.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.getChildByChildContent"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/xml_utilities/#ModelManager.postVariationXMLProcessing-Tuple{Symbol, String}","page":"XML utilities","text":"postVariationXMLProcessing(location::Symbol, path_to_xml::String)\npostVariationXMLProcessing(::AbstractSimulator, location::Symbol, path_to_xml::String)\n\nHook called immediately after createXMLFile writes a variation XML file at path_to_xml for location. Default is a no-op.\n\nSimulator packages may override postVariationXMLProcessing(::TheirSimulator, location, path) for location-specific post-processing (e.g. splitting out embedded SBML files).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.postVariationXMLProcessing"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/xml_utilities/#ModelManager.prepareBaseFile-Tuple{InputFolder}","page":"XML utilities","text":"prepareBaseFile(input_folder::InputFolder)\nprepareBaseFile(::AbstractSimulator, input_folder::InputFolder)\n\nReturn the path to the base input file for input_folder, or nothing if the folder has no base file.\n\nDefault implementation: joinpath(locationPath(input_folder), input_folder.basename), or nothing if input_folder.basename is missing.\n\nSimulator packages may override prepareBaseFile(::TheirSimulator, input_folder) for location types that require special handling (e.g. generating a base file on demand).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.prepareBaseFile"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/xml_utilities/#ModelManager.prepareVariedInputFolder-Tuple{Symbol, AbstractMonad}","page":"XML utilities","text":"prepareVariedInputFolder(location::Symbol, M::AbstractMonad)\n\nCreate the variation XML file for location in monad M, if the location is varied.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.prepareVariedInputFolder"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/xml_utilities/#ModelManager.prepareVariedInputFolder-Tuple{Symbol, Sampling}","page":"XML utilities","text":"prepareVariedInputFolder(location::Symbol, sampling::Sampling)\n\nCreate the variation XML file for each monad in sampling for location, if varied.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.prepareVariedInputFolder"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/xml_utilities/#ModelManager.retrieveElementError-Tuple{Vector{<:AbstractString}, String}","page":"XML utilities","text":"retrieveElementError(xml_path::Vector{<:AbstractString}, path_element::String)\n\nThrow an error if the element defined by xml_path is not found in the XML document, including the path element that caused the error.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.retrieveElementError"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/xml_utilities/#ModelManager.setSimpleContent-Tuple{LightXML.XMLDocument, Vector{<:AbstractString}, Union{Real, String}}","page":"XML utilities","text":"setSimpleContent(xml_doc::XMLDocument, xml_path::Vector{<:AbstractString}, new_value::Union{Int,Real,String})\n\nUpdate the content of the element in the XML document that matches the given path with the new value. See retrieveElement.\n\nValidates that the element is terminal (has no child elements) before setting content. Throws AssertionError if the element has child elements.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.setSimpleContent"},{"category":"section","location":"man/managing_data/#Managing-data","page":"Managing data","text":"Over a long campaign you accumulate simulations you no longer need — failed runs, abandoned sweeps, stale parameterizations. ModelManager provides targeted deletion at every level of the trial hierarchy and a full project reset, all keeping the database and filesystem consistent.","title":"Managing data"},{"category":"section","location":"man/managing_data/#Deleting-by-level","page":"Managing data","text":"Each level has a deletion function that, by default, also cleans up the levels it depends on:\n\ndeleteSimulations([12, 13, 14])   # delete specific simulations\ndeleteSimulation(12)              # singular alias\ndeleteAllSimulations()            # every simulation in the project\n\ndeleteMonad([5])                  # delete monads (and, by default, their simulations)\ndeleteSampling([3])               # delete samplings\ndeleteTrial([1])                  # delete trials\n\nThe delete_subs / delete_supers keywords control how far the cascade reaches:\n\ndelete_subs (default true) — also delete the constituent (lower-level) entities.\ndelete_supers (default true) — also delete the containing (higher-level) entities that would be left incomplete.\n\ndeleteSimulations additionally accepts filters to restrict which rows are removed.","title":"Deleting by level"},{"category":"section","location":"man/managing_data/#Deleting-by-status","page":"Managing data","text":"To clear out failed runs (the most common cleanup):\n\ndeleteSimulationsByStatus([\"Failed\"])           # prompts before deleting\ndeleteSimulationsByStatus([\"Failed\"]; user_check=false)\n\nThe status values are those from recognizedStatusCodes.","title":"Deleting by status"},{"category":"section","location":"man/managing_data/#Resetting-a-project","page":"Managing data","text":"resetDatabase wipes the database and all generated output, returning the project to a clean state (input folders are preserved; simulator build artifacts are removed via the backend's clearSimulatorArtifacts hook):\n\nresetDatabase()                       # prompts for confirmation\nresetDatabase(; force_reset=true)     # skip the prompt (scripts/CI)\n\nThis is destructive and irreversible — every simulation, monad, sampling, and trial is deleted. Use it deliberately. resetFolder resets a single input folder's variation state without touching the rest of the project.","title":"Resetting a project"},{"category":"section","location":"man/managing_data/#Safe-removal-on-shared-filesystems","page":"Managing data","text":"The deletion helpers remove output directories with rm_hpc_safe rather than rm, so they tolerate the transient unlink failures common on shared HPC filesystems. If you write your own cleanup code in a ModelManager workflow on a cluster, prefer rm_hpc_safe for the same reason (see HPC support).\n\nSee the Deletion API reference for full signatures.","title":"Safe removal on shared filesystems"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/sensitivity/#Sensitivity-analysis-(GSA)","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"Global sensitivity analysis: MOAT, Sobol', and RBD-FAST.","title":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/sensitivity/#Public-API","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"","title":"Public API"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/sensitivity/#Private-API","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"","title":"Private API"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/sensitivity/#ModelManager.MOAT","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"MOAT <: GSAMethod\n\nMorris One-At-A-Time global sensitivity analysis.\n\nFields\n\nlhs_variation::LHSVariation\n\nExamples\n\nMOAT()      # default 15 base points\nMOAT(10)    # 10 base points\nMOAT(10; add_noise=true)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.MOAT"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/sensitivity/#ModelManager.RBD","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"RBD <: GSAMethod\n\nRandom Balance Design global sensitivity analysis.\n\nFields\n\nrbd_variation::RBDVariation\nnum_harmonics::Int\n\nExamples\n\nRBD(15)\nRBD(15; num_harmonics=10)\nRBD(15; use_sobol=false)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.RBD"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/sensitivity/#ModelManager.SobolMM","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"SobolMM\n\nASCII alias for Sobolʼ.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.SobolMM"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/sensitivity/#ModelManager.Sobolʼ","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"Sobolʼ <: GSAMethod\n\nSobol' variance-based global sensitivity analysis.\n\nThe ʼ (rasp) symbol avoids conflict with the Sobol module. Type \\rasp<tab> in VS Code. SobolMM is provided as a plain-ASCII alias.\n\nFields\n\nsobol_variation::SobolVariation\nsobol_index_methods::NamedTuple{(:first_order,:total_order),Tuple{Symbol,Symbol}}\n\nExamples\n\nSobolʼ(15)\nSobolʼ(15; sobol_index_methods=(first_order=:Jansen1999, total_order=:Jansen1999))\nSobolʼ(15; skip_start=true)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.Sobolʼ"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/sensitivity/#Base.run-Tuple{ModelManager.GSAMethod, InputFolders, AbstractVector{<:AbstractVariation}}","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"run(method::GSAMethod, inputs::InputFolders, avs; functions, kwargs...)\nrun(method::GSAMethod, reference::AbstractMonad, avs; functions, kwargs...)\n\nRun a global sensitivity analysis and return a GSASampling result.\n\nkwargs are forwarded to run(::Sampling; ...) and from there to the simulator hooks — pass any simulator-specific options here.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Base.run"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/sensitivity/#ModelManager.calculateGSA!-Tuple{ModelManager.GSASampling, AbstractVector{<:Function}}","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"calculateGSA!(gsa_sampling, functions)\n\nCalculate sensitivity indices for each function in functions.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.calculateGSA!"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/sensitivity/#ModelManager.simulationIDs-Tuple{ModelManager.GSASampling}","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"simulationIDs(gsa_sampling::GSASampling)\n\nReturn the simulation IDs run in the sensitivity analysis.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.simulationIDs"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/sensitivity/#ModelManager.GSAMethod","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"GSAMethod\n\nAbstract type for global sensitivity analysis methods.\n\nSubtypes\n\nMOAT, Sobolʼ, RBD\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.GSAMethod"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/sensitivity/#ModelManager.GSASampling","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"GSASampling\n\nAbstract type for global sensitivity analysis sampling results.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.GSASampling"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/sensitivity/#ModelManager.MOATSampling","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"MOATSampling <: GSASampling\n\nResult of a MOAT sensitivity analysis.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.MOATSampling"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/sensitivity/#ModelManager.RBDSampling","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"RBDSampling <: GSASampling\n\nResult of an RBD sensitivity analysis.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.RBDSampling"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/sensitivity/#ModelManager.SobolSampling","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"SobolSampling <: GSASampling\n\nResult of a Sobolʼ sensitivity analysis.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.SobolSampling"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/sensitivity/#ModelManager.evaluateFunctionOnSampling-Tuple{ModelManager.GSASampling, Function}","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"evaluateFunctionOnSampling(gsa_sampling, f)\n\nEvaluate f (a function of simulation_id) on each monad in the sampling, averaging replicates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.evaluateFunctionOnSampling"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/sensitivity/#ModelManager.getMonadIDDataFrame-Tuple{ModelManager.GSASampling}","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"getMonadIDDataFrame(gsa_sampling::GSASampling)\n\nReturn the DataFrame of monad IDs that define the sampling scheme.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.getMonadIDDataFrame"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/sensitivity/#ModelManager.methodString-Tuple{ModelManager.GSASampling}","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"methodString(gsa_sampling::GSASampling)\n\nReturn a lowercase string identifier for the GSA method (e.g. \"moat\", \"sobol\").\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.methodString"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/sensitivity/#ModelManager.perturbVariation-Tuple{ModelManager.ParsedVariations, InputFolders, VariationID, AbstractVector{<:Real}}","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"perturbVariation(pv, inputs, reference_variation_id, cdf_col)\n\nGenerate one-at-a-time perturbations of cdf_col for MOAT analysis.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.perturbVariation"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/sensitivity/#ModelManager.recordSensitivityScheme-Tuple{ModelManager.GSASampling}","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"recordSensitivityScheme(gsa_sampling)\n\nWrite the monad ID scheme to a CSV file inside the sampling's trial folder.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.recordSensitivityScheme"},{"category":"function","location":"lib/sensitivity/#ModelManager.runSensitivitySampling","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"runSensitivitySampling(method, inputs, pv; kwargs...)\n\nInternal dispatch: create the sampling design, run simulations, and return a GSASampling. kwargs are forwarded to run(::Sampling; ...).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.runSensitivitySampling"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/sensitivity/#ModelManager.sensitivityResults!-Tuple{ModelManager.GSASampling, AbstractVector{<:Function}}","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"sensitivityResults!(gsa_sampling, functions)\n\nCalculate sensitivity indices for functions and record the sampling scheme.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.sensitivityResults!"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/sensitivity/#ModelManager.variationsToMonads-Tuple{InputFolders, AbstractArray{VariationID}}","page":"Sensitivity analysis (GSA)","text":"variationsToMonads(inputs, variation_ids)\n\nReturn an array of Monads matching the shape of variation_ids.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.variationsToMonads"},{"category":"section","location":"man/installation/#Installation","page":"Installation","text":"ModelManager.jl is the base layer of a simulator ecosystem. How you install it depends on whether you are using a backend or building one.","title":"Installation"},{"category":"section","location":"man/installation/#Using-a-backend","page":"Installation","text":"If you just want to run simulations, you do not install ModelManager directly — you install a simulator package that depends on it, such as PhysiCellModelManager.jl. Installing that package pulls in ModelManager automatically. Follow that package's own installation instructions.","title":"Using a backend"},{"category":"section","location":"man/installation/#Building-a-backend","page":"Installation","text":"If you are developing a new simulator package on top of ModelManager:","title":"Building a backend"},{"category":"section","location":"man/installation/#1.-Add-the-registry","page":"Installation","text":"ModelManager and its sibling packages are published in the BergmanLabRegistry. Add it once:\n\npkg> registry add https://github.com/drbergman-lab/BergmanLabRegistry","title":"1. Add the registry"},{"category":"section","location":"man/installation/#2.-Add-ModelManager-as-a-dependency","page":"Installation","text":"From within your package's environment:\n\npkg> add ModelManager","title":"2. Add ModelManager as a dependency"},{"category":"section","location":"man/installation/#3.-Define-your-simulator-and-register-globals","page":"Installation","text":"using ModelManager\n\nmutable struct MySimulator <: AbstractSimulator\n    dir::String\n    # ...simulator-specific fields\nend\n\nfunction __init__()\n    ModelManager.mm_globals_ref[] = ModelManagerGlobals(simulator = MySimulator(\"/path\"))\nend\n\nThen implement the required interface methods and call initializeModelManager from your package's own initialization entry point. The full walkthrough is in Building a Simulator Backend.","title":"3. Define your simulator and register globals"},{"category":"section","location":"man/installation/#Julia-version-and-environment","page":"Installation","text":"ModelManager targets a recent stable Julia release; see the [compat] section of Project.toml for the supported range. As always, work inside a project environment rather than the global one:\n\njulia --project=.","title":"Julia version and environment"},{"category":"section","location":"man/installation/#Contributing-to-ModelManager-itself","page":"Installation","text":"Clone the repository and develop it in a fresh environment:\n\npkg> dev https://github.com/drbergman-lab/ModelManager.jl\n\nRun the test suite with:\n\njulia --project=. -e 'using Pkg; Pkg.test()'","title":"Contributing to ModelManager itself"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/user_api/#User-API","page":"User API","text":"High-level createTrial / run convenience wrappers over the trial hierarchy.","title":"User API"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/user_api/#Public-API","page":"User API","text":"","title":"Public API"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/user_api/#Private-API","page":"User API","text":"","title":"Private API"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/user_api/#Base.run-Tuple{ModelManager.AddVariationMethod, Vararg{Any}}","page":"User API","text":"run([method=GridVariation()], inputs_or_ref, avs...; kwargs...)\n\nCreate a trial from inputs_or_ref and avs, then run it. kwargs are forwarded to run(::AbstractTrial; ...), which passes them through to prepareTrialHierarchy and the simulator hooks.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Base.run"},{"category":"function","location":"lib/user_api/#ModelManager.createTrial","page":"User API","text":"createTrial([method=GridVariation()], inputs::InputFolders, avs::Vector{<:AbstractVariation}=AbstractVariation[];\n            n_replicates::Integer=1, use_previous::Bool=true)\n\nReturn an AbstractTrial (Simulation, Monad, or Sampling) from the given inputs and variations.\n\nThe method controls how the variation space is sampled (default: GridVariation()). Other options: LHSVariation, SobolVariation, RBDVariation.\n\nAlternate forms (all accept an optional leading method argument)\n\ncreateTrial(inputs, av::AbstractVariation; ...)            # single variation\ncreateTrial(reference::AbstractMonad, avs; ...)            # start from a reference monad\ncreateTrial(output_ref::MMOutput{<:AbstractMonad}, avs; ...)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.createTrial"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/user_api/#ModelManager._createTrial-Tuple{ModelManager.AddVariationMethod, InputFolders, VariationID, Vector{<:AbstractVariation}, Integer, Bool}","page":"User API","text":"_createTrial(method, inputs, reference_variation_id, avs, n_replicates, use_previous)\n\nInternal implementation of createTrial.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._createTrial"},{"category":"section","location":"misc/database_upgrades/#Database-upgrades","page":"Database upgrades","text":"As a simulator package evolves, its database schema may need to change. ModelManager provides a generic, milestone-based migration framework so a project database created by an older version of a backend can be brought up to date safely. This page explains the mechanism; backend authors implement the hooks described in Building a Simulator Backend.","title":"Database upgrades"},{"category":"section","location":"misc/database_upgrades/#When-migrations-run","page":"Database upgrades","text":"Every project database records the package version it was last migrated to, in a version table named by the backend (dbVersionTableName). During initializeModelManager, resolvePackageVersion compares that stored version to the running package version:\n\nversions match → nothing to do;\nthe database is older → upgradePackage runs the migration chain;\nwith auto_upgrade=false (the default), the backend may prompt before applying large or destructive changes.","title":"When migrations run"},{"category":"section","location":"misc/database_upgrades/#The-milestone-chain","page":"Database upgrades","text":"Not every release changes the schema. A backend declares the versions that do via upgradeMilestones — a sorted list of VersionNumbers. upgradePackage walks the milestones between the database's current version and the target version and, for each one, calls the backend's upgradeToMilestone(sim, version, auto_upgrade).\n\nEach upgradeToMilestone implementation is responsible for:\n\nprompting the user (when auto_upgrade is false) before any large or destructive change;\nmaking the necessary DDL/DML changes to the database;\nnot updating the version table — upgradePackage records the new version after a successful return.\n\nReturning false aborts the chain, leaving the database at the last successfully applied milestone.","title":"The milestone chain"},{"category":"section","location":"misc/database_upgrades/#Helpers-for-writing-migrations","page":"Database upgrades","text":"ModelManager provides utilities migrations commonly need:\n\npopulateTableOnFeatureSubset — copy rows from a source table into a target table whose columns are a subset (with optional column renaming via a mapping). Useful when a schema change splits or narrows a table.\ncontinueMilestoneUpgrade — the standard prompt/continue helper for gating a milestone behind user confirmation when auto_upgrade is false.","title":"Helpers for writing migrations"},{"category":"section","location":"misc/database_upgrades/#For-users","page":"Database upgrades","text":"You normally do not call any of this directly. When you open a project with a newer backend, initialization detects the older schema and offers to upgrade. Pass auto_upgrade=true to your backend's initialization entry point to apply migrations without prompting — appropriate for scripts and CI, but make sure you have a backup of important project data first, since some migrations are irreversible.\n\nSee the Database upgrades and Package version API references for the full set of functions.","title":"For users"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/up/#Schema-migrations","page":"Schema migrations","text":"The generic schema-migration framework.","title":"Schema migrations"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/up/#Public-API","page":"Schema migrations","text":"","title":"Public API"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/up/#Private-API","page":"Schema migrations","text":"","title":"Private API"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/up/#ModelManager.continueMilestoneUpgrade-Tuple{VersionNumber, Bool}","page":"Schema migrations","text":"continueMilestoneUpgrade(version::VersionNumber, auto_upgrade::Bool)\n\nPrint a warning about the schema change at version and prompt the user to confirm unless auto_upgrade is true. Returns true if the upgrade should proceed, false if the user aborted.\n\nCall this at the top of any upgradeToMilestone implementation that makes large or destructive changes to the database schema.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.continueMilestoneUpgrade"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/up/#ModelManager.populateTableOnFeatureSubset-Tuple{SQLite.DB, String, String}","page":"Schema migrations","text":"populateTableOnFeatureSubset(db::SQLite.DB, source_table::String, target_table::String; column_mapping::Dict{String,String}=Dict{String,String}())\n\nPopulate a target_table with rows from source_table. Columns in source_table that exist (possibly under a different name) in target_table are copied; extras are ignored. Use column_mapping to rename columns during the copy (source_name => target_name).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.populateTableOnFeatureSubset"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/up/#ModelManager.upgradePackage-Tuple{AbstractSimulator, SQLite.DB, VersionNumber, VersionNumber, Bool}","page":"Schema migrations","text":"upgradePackage(sim::AbstractSimulator, db::SQLite.DB, from_version::VersionNumber, to_version::VersionNumber, auto_upgrade::Bool)\n\nDrive the database migration from from_version to to_version for the simulator framework sim.\n\nFor each milestone v in upgradeMilestones(sim) with from_version < v ≤ to_version, calls upgradeToMilestone(sim, v, auto_upgrade). After a successful milestone upgrade the version table is updated immediately so that a partial upgrade is recoverable. If any milestone fails the chain is aborted and false is returned.\n\nAfter all milestones pass, if to_version is beyond the last milestone the version table is stamped with to_version (a \"no schema change\" bump).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.upgradePackage"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/deletion/#Deletion","page":"Deletion","text":"Deleting simulations and resetting the project database.","title":"Deletion"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/deletion/#Public-API","page":"Deletion","text":"","title":"Public API"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/deletion/#Private-API","page":"Deletion","text":"","title":"Private API"},{"category":"function","location":"lib/deletion/#ModelManager.deleteSimulation","page":"Deletion","text":"deleteSimulation(args...; kwargs...)\n\nAlias for deleteSimulations.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.deleteSimulation"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/deletion/#ModelManager.deleteSimulations-Tuple{AbstractVector{<:Union{Missing, Integer}}}","page":"Deletion","text":"deleteSimulations(simulation_ids; delete_supers, filters)\ndeleteSimulation(args...; kwargs...)\n\nDelete simulations from the database and from disk.\n\nIf delete_supers is true (default), also removes any monads/samplings/trials that become empty after the deletion.  filters adds extra SQL WHERE conditions.\n\nExamples\n\ndeleteSimulations(1:3)\ndeleteSimulations(4)\ndeleteSimulations(1:100; filters=Dict(\"config_id\" => 1))\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.deleteSimulations"},{"category":"function","location":"lib/deletion/#ModelManager.deleteSimulationsByStatus","page":"Deletion","text":"deleteSimulationsByStatus(status_codes_to_delete::Vector{String}=[\"Failed\"]; user_check::Bool=true)\ndeleteSimulationsByStatus(status_code_to_delete::String; user_check::Bool=true)\n\nDelete simulations filtered by status code.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.deleteSimulationsByStatus"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/deletion/#ModelManager.resetDatabase-Tuple{}","page":"Deletion","text":"resetDatabase(; force_reset, force_continue)\n\nReset the database after user confirmation: delete all output folders, clear all variation files, call clearSimulatorArtifacts on the active simulator, then reinitialize the database.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.resetDatabase"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/deletion/#ModelManager.rm_hpc_safe-Tuple{String}","page":"Deletion","text":"rm_hpc_safe(path::String; force, recursive)\n\nRemove path, using a .trash/ staging area on HPC (NFS) filesystems to avoid lock issues.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.rm_hpc_safe"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/deletion/#ModelManager.deleteAllSimulations-Tuple{}","page":"Deletion","text":"deleteAllSimulations(; kwargs...)\n\nDelete all simulations. See deleteSimulations for keyword arguments.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.deleteAllSimulations"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/deletion/#ModelManager.deleteMonad-Tuple{AbstractVector{<:Integer}}","page":"Deletion","text":"deleteMonad(monad_ids; delete_subs, delete_supers)\n\nDelete monads by ID, optionally cascading to their simulations and to empty samplings/trials above them.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.deleteMonad"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/deletion/#ModelManager.deleteSampling-Tuple{AbstractVector{<:Integer}}","page":"Deletion","text":"deleteSampling(sampling_ids; delete_subs, delete_supers)\n\nDelete samplings by ID, optionally cascading.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.deleteSampling"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/deletion/#ModelManager.deleteTrial-Tuple{AbstractVector{<:Integer}}","page":"Deletion","text":"deleteTrial(trial_ids; delete_subs)\n\nDelete trials by ID, optionally cascading to their samplings.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.deleteTrial"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/deletion/#ModelManager.resetFolder-Tuple{Symbol, String}","page":"Deletion","text":"resetFolder(location::Symbol, folder::String)\n\nRemove the variations DB and variations folder from folder in location.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.resetFolder"},{"category":"section","location":"man/variations/#Variations","page":"Variations","text":"A variation describes how to change one or more model parameters away from their base value. Variations are the unit of parameterization in ModelManager: you attach them to a set of InputFolders, and the framework expands them into monads, records them in the per-folder variations databases, and assigns each combination a VariationID.","title":"Variations"},{"category":"section","location":"man/variations/#Targeting-a-parameter:-XMLPath","page":"Variations","text":"Parameters live in XML input files, addressed by an XMLPath — the sequence of tags (and optional attributes) leading to the element to change. You usually pass the path as a plain vector of strings and let the variation constructor wrap it:\n\n[\"overall\", \"max_time\"]                          # <overall><max_time>…\n[\"cell_definitions\", \"cell_definition:name:tumor\", \"phenotype\", \"cycle\", \"rate\"]\n\nPath elements of the form tag:attribute:value select an element by an attribute, and the custom forms address custom data. ModelManager only locates the element; how the value is written into the file is the backend's concern.\n\nnote: location is explicit\nEvery variation needs a location (the project location the target lives in, e.g. :config). ModelManager requires it explicitly. Backends often add convenience constructors that infer the location from the path — but at this layer you pass it yourself.","title":"Targeting a parameter: XMLPath"},{"category":"section","location":"man/variations/#Elementary-variations","page":"Variations","text":"An ElementaryVariation varies a single target. There are two kinds.","title":"Elementary variations"},{"category":"section","location":"man/variations/#DiscreteVariation","page":"Variations","text":"DiscreteVariation enumerates a fixed list of values:\n\n# Three explicit values.\ndv = DiscreteVariation(:config, [\"overall\", \"max_time\"], [60.0, 120.0, 240.0])\n\n# A single value (e.g. to pin a parameter) — pass a scalar.\nfixed = DiscreteVariation(:config, [\"overall\", \"max_time\"], 120.0)\n\nWhen sampled on a grid, each value becomes one monad.","title":"DiscreteVariation"},{"category":"section","location":"man/variations/#DistributedVariation","page":"Variations","text":"DistributedVariation draws from a probability distribution (from Distributions.jl). It is the form used by sensitivity analysis and calibration, where parameters are sampled rather than enumerated:\n\nusing Distributions\ndist = DistributedVariation(:config, XMLPath([\"overall\", \"max_time\"]), Uniform(60.0, 240.0))\n\nTwo convenience constructors cover the common cases:\n\nUniformDistributedVariation(:config, XMLPath(path), 60.0, 240.0)\nNormalDistributedVariation(:config, XMLPath(path), 120.0, 30.0; lb=0.0)\n\nPass flip=true to invert the distribution (use the inverse-CDF of 1-x).","title":"DistributedVariation"},{"category":"section","location":"man/variations/#Covarying-parameters:-CoVariation","page":"Variations","text":"A CoVariation ties several elementary variations together so they move as one — a single draw (or grid index) sets all of them. Use it when parameters are physically coupled or when you want to reduce dimensionality. All constituents must be the same kind (all discrete or all distributed):\n\n# Distributed: one CDF draw moves both targets.\ncv = CoVariation(\n    ([\"cell\",\"birth_rate\"], Uniform(0.01, 0.05)),\n    ([\"cell\",\"death_rate\"], Uniform(0.001, 0.01)),\n)\n\n# Discrete: paired value lists of equal length.\ncv = CoVariation(\n    ([\"cell\",\"birth_rate\"], [0.01, 0.03, 0.05]),\n    ([\"cell\",\"death_rate\"], [0.001, 0.005, 0.01]),\n)","title":"Covarying parameters: CoVariation"},{"category":"section","location":"man/variations/#Reparameterizing:-LatentVariation","page":"Variations","text":"A LatentVariation introduces latent parameters and maps them to one or more target parameters through arbitrary functions. This lets you sample in a more natural or lower-dimensional space than the raw XML parameters. Each latent dimension is either a fixed vector of values or a distribution; maps turn the latent vector into target values:\n\n# Sample a single latent \"log rate\"; the target is exp(log_rate).\nlv = LatentVariation(\n    [Normal(-7, 1)],                 # latent parameter(s)\n    [XMLPath([\"cell\", \"rate\"])],     # target(s)\n    [lp -> exp(lp[1])],              # map: latent → target value(s)\n    [\"log_rate\"],                    # latent parameter name(s)\n    [:config];                       # target location(s)\n    inverse_maps = [tv -> log(tv[1])],\n)\n\nWhen you provide inverse_maps (required for distribution-based latents used in calibration), the constructor runs a round-trip check (_validateInverseMaps) to confirm they are consistent with the forward maps.","title":"Reparameterizing: LatentVariation"},{"category":"section","location":"man/variations/#Applying-variations","page":"Variations","text":"You normally hand variations to createTrial / run, which call addVariations for you (see The trial hierarchy and Running simulations):\n\noutput = run(inputs, dv1, dv2; n_replicates=3)\n\naddVariations writes the variation rows into each varied location's variations database and returns the resulting VariationIDs. How those combinations are generated — full grid versus a space-filling design — is controlled by the method argument, covered next in Space-filling designs.\n\nSee the Variations API reference for every type and helper.","title":"Applying variations"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/database/#Database","page":"Database","text":"Schema creation, queries, and consistency diagnostics.","title":"Database"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/database/#Public-API","page":"Database","text":"","title":"Public API"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/database/#Private-API","page":"Database","text":"","title":"Private API"},{"category":"function","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.constructSelectQuery","page":"Database","text":"constructSelectQuery(table_name::String, condition_stmt::String=\"\"; selection::String=\"*\")\n\nBuild a SELECT SQL string for table_name.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.constructSelectQuery"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.createMMTable-Tuple{String, String}","page":"Database","text":"createMMTable(table_name::String, schema::String; db::SQLite.DB=centralDB())\n\nCreate a table in the central database if it does not already exist.\n\nThe table name must end in \"s\" (for ID naming conventions) and the schema must include a PRIMARY KEY column named <table_singular>_id.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.createMMTable"},{"category":"function","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.insertFolder","page":"Database","text":"insertFolder(location::Symbol, folder::String, description::String=\"\")\n\nInsert folder into the database for location (if not already present), create its per-folder variations SQLite database, and call initializeInputFolder on the active simulator.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.insertFolder"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.locationVariationsDatabase-Tuple{Symbol, String}","page":"Database","text":"locationVariationsDatabase(location::Symbol, folder::String)\n\nReturn a SQLite.DB connection to the per-folder variations database for location/folder, nothing if the folder is empty (location unused), or missing if the variations DB file does not exist.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.locationVariationsDatabase"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.printSimulationsTable-Tuple","page":"Database","text":"printSimulationsTable(args...; sink=println, kwargs...)\n\nPrint a table of simulations and their varied values. See simulationsTable.\n\nKeyword Arguments\n\nsink: A function to receive the DataFrame (default println). Can also use CSV.write.\n\nExamples\n\nprintSimulationsTable([simulation_1, monad_3, sampling_2, trial_1])\n\nsim_ids = [1, 2, 3]\nprintSimulationsTable(sim_ids; remove_constants=false)\n\nusing CSV\nprintSimulationsTable(; sink=CSV.write(\"temp.csv\"))\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.printSimulationsTable"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.queryToDataFrame-Tuple{String}","page":"Database","text":"queryToDataFrame(query::String; db::SQLite.DB=centralDB(), is_row::Bool=false)\n\nExecute query and return the result as a DataFrame.\n\nIf is_row is true, asserts that exactly one row is returned.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.queryToDataFrame"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.shortLocationVariationID-Tuple{Symbol}","page":"Database","text":"shortLocationVariationID(fieldname::Symbol)\nshortLocationVariationID(fieldname::String)\nshortLocationVariationID(type::Type, fieldname)\n\nReturn the abbreviated column-name symbol for fieldname's variation ID in display tables.\n\nDispatches to shortLocationVariationID(simulator(), fieldname). The default implementation returns locationVariationIDName(fieldname) |> Symbol. Simulator packages should extend shortLocationVariationID(::TheirSimulator, fieldname::Symbol) to provide custom abbreviations.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.shortLocationVariationID"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.simulationsTable-Tuple{AbstractArray{<:AbstractTrial}}","page":"Database","text":"simulationsTable(args...; kwargs...)\n\nReturn a DataFrame with simulation data. See simulationsTableFromQuery for keyword arguments.\n\nargs... can be:\n\nAny AbstractTrial objects (or arrays thereof)\nA vector of simulation IDs\nOmitted (returns data for all simulations)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.simulationsTable"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.stmtToDataFrame-Tuple{SQLite.Stmt, Any}","page":"Database","text":"stmtToDataFrame(stmt_str, params; db::SQLite.DB=centralDB(), is_row::Bool=false)\nstmtToDataFrame(stmt::SQLite.Stmt, params; is_row::Bool=false)\n\nExecute a prepared statement with params and return the result as a DataFrame.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.stmtToDataFrame"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.tableColumns-Tuple{String}","page":"Database","text":"tableColumns(table_name::String; db::SQLite.DB=centralDB())\n\nReturn the column names of table_name in db.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.tableColumns"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.tableExists-Tuple{String}","page":"Database","text":"tableExists(table_name::String; db::SQLite.DB=centralDB())\n\nReturn true if table_name exists in db.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.tableExists"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.tableIDName-Tuple{String}","page":"Database","text":"tableIDName(table::String; strip_s::Bool=true)\n\nReturn the ID column name for table (e.g. \"config_id\" for \"configs\").\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.tableIDName"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager._snapshotMaxIDs-Tuple{}","page":"Database","text":"_snapshotMaxIDs() → Dict{Type{<:AbstractTrial}, Int}\n\nCapture the highest ID currently present for each trial type in both the database and the output folder tree. Called by initializeModelManager just before launching the background diagnostics task so that databaseDiagnostics only inspects entities that existed at initialization time and is not confused by in-progress runs started later in the same session.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._snapshotMaxIDs"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.abstractSamplingForeignReferenceSubSchema-Tuple{}","page":"Database","text":"abstractSamplingForeignReferenceSubSchema()\n\nReturn the SQL fragment for foreign key constraints referencing the simulator version table and all input tables.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.abstractSamplingForeignReferenceSubSchema"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.addFolderNameColumns!-Tuple{DataFrames.DataFrame}","page":"Database","text":"addFolderNameColumns!(df::DataFrame)\n\nAppend <location>_folder columns to df by looking up folder names.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.addFolderNameColumns!"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.appendVariations-Tuple{Symbol, DataFrames.DataFrame}","page":"Database","text":"appendVariations(location::Symbol, df::DataFrame; short_names::Bool=true)\n\nJoin the varied parameters for location onto df. When short_names=false, column names are kept as raw XML paths rather than being shortened by shortVariationName.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.appendVariations"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.buildWhereClause-Tuple{String, Vector{<:Integer}, Dict{<:AbstractString}}","page":"Database","text":"buildWhereClause(table_name::String, ids::Vector{<:Integer}, filters::Dict; db::SQLite.DB=centralDB())\n\nBuild a WHERE clause with ids and optional column filters.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.buildWhereClause"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.calibrationsSchema-Tuple{}","page":"Database","text":"calibrationsSchema()\n\nReturn the SQL schema string for the calibrations table.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.calibrationsSchema"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.columnsExist-Tuple{AbstractVector{<:AbstractString}, String}","page":"Database","text":"columnsExist(column_names, table_name::String; kwargs...)\ncolumnsExist(column_names, valid_column_names)\n\nReturn true if all column_names exist in the specified table (or list).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.columnsExist"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.createDefaultStatusCodesTable-Tuple{}","page":"Database","text":"createDefaultStatusCodesTable()\n\nCreate (if absent) and populate the status_codes table.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.createDefaultStatusCodesTable"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.createSchema-Tuple{}","page":"Database","text":"createSchema()\n\nCreate all tables in the central database.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.createSchema"},{"category":"function","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.databaseDiagnostics","page":"Database","text":"databaseDiagnostics(max_ids::Dict{Type{<:AbstractTrial},Int} = Dict{Type{<:AbstractTrial},Int}())\n\nCheck consistency between the database and the output folders. Prints warnings for any discrepancies found.\n\nWhen max_ids is provided (as returned by _snapshotMaxIDs), each check is restricted to IDs ≤ the snapshot value for that type. This prevents false positives from simulations that were created or started after initializeModelManager returned.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.databaseDiagnostics"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.initializeDatabase-Tuple{}","page":"Database","text":"initializeDatabase()\n\nInitialize the central database, creating the schema if it does not already exist.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.initializeDatabase"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.inputFolderID-Tuple{Symbol, String}","page":"Database","text":"inputFolderID(location::Symbol, folder::String)\n\nReturn the database row ID for folder in location.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.inputFolderID"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.inputFolderName-Tuple{Symbol, Int64}","page":"Database","text":"inputFolderName(location::Symbol, id::Int)\n\nReturn the folder name for the database row with id in location.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.inputFolderName"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.inputIDsSubSchema-Tuple{}","page":"Database","text":"inputIDsSubSchema()\n\nReturn the SQL fragment for all input ID columns.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.inputIDsSubSchema"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.inputVariationIDsSubSchema-Tuple{}","page":"Database","text":"inputVariationIDsSubSchema()\n\nReturn the SQL fragment for all variation ID columns.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.inputVariationIDsSubSchema"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.isStarted-Tuple{Int64}","page":"Database","text":"isStarted(simulation_id::Int[; new_status_code])\n\nReturn true if the simulation has been started.  Optionally update its status atomically (using an EXCLUSIVE transaction when a new status is provided).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.isStarted"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.locationVariationsTable-Tuple{String, SQLite.DB}","page":"Database","text":"locationVariationsTable(query::String, db::SQLite.DB; remove_constants::Bool=false)\n\nReturn a DataFrame from query against db, dropping the par_key column. Removes constant columns if remove_constants is true and there is more than one row.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.locationVariationsTable"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.locationVariationsTable-Tuple{Symbol, AbstractSampling}","page":"Database","text":"locationVariationsTable(location::Symbol, S::AbstractSampling; remove_constants::Bool=false, short_names::Bool=true)\n\nReturn a DataFrame of variation rows for the given location and sampling.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.locationVariationsTable"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.locationVariationsTable-Tuple{Symbol, Missing, AbstractVector{<:Integer}}","page":"Database","text":"locationVariationsTable(location::Symbol, ::Missing, variation_ids; kwargs...)\n\nReturn a single-column DataFrame for a location whose folder has no variations database (all IDs = 0).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.locationVariationsTable"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.locationVariationsTable-Tuple{Symbol, Nothing, AbstractVector{<:Integer}}","page":"Database","text":"locationVariationsTable(location::Symbol, ::Nothing, variation_ids; kwargs...)\n\nReturn a single-column DataFrame for a location that is not being used (all IDs = -1).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.locationVariationsTable"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.locationVariationsTable-Tuple{Symbol, SQLite.DB, AbstractVector{<:Integer}}","page":"Database","text":"locationVariationsTable(location::Symbol, variations_database::SQLite.DB, variation_ids::AbstractVector{<:Integer}; remove_constants::Bool=false, short_names::Bool=true)\n\nReturn a DataFrame of variation rows for variation_ids from variations_database. When short_names=false, column names are kept as raw XML paths (joined with /) rather than being passed through shortVariationName.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.locationVariationsTable"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.monadsSchema-Tuple{}","page":"Database","text":"monadsSchema()\n\nReturn the SQL schema string for the monads table.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.monadsSchema"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.necessaryInputsPresent-Tuple{}","page":"Database","text":"necessaryInputsPresent()\n\nReturn true if all required input directories exist.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.necessaryInputsPresent"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.recognizedStatusCodes-Tuple{}","page":"Database","text":"recognizedStatusCodes()\n\nReturn the list of valid simulation status code strings.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.recognizedStatusCodes"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.reinitializeDatabase-Tuple{}","page":"Database","text":"reinitializeDatabase()\n\nReinitialize the database, scanning data/inputs/ to register any new folders.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.reinitializeDatabase"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.samplingsSchema-Tuple{}","page":"Database","text":"samplingsSchema()\n\nReturn the SQL schema string for the samplings table.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.samplingsSchema"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.shortVariationName-Tuple{Symbol, String}","page":"Database","text":"shortVariationName(location::Symbol, name::String)\n\nReturn the display name for variation column name at location.\n\nDispatches to shortVariationName(simulator(), location, name). The default returns name unchanged. Simulator packages should extend shortVariationName(::TheirSimulator, location, name) to provide human-readable column names.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.shortVariationName"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.simulationsTableFromQuery-Tuple{String}","page":"Database","text":"simulationsTableFromQuery(query::String; remove_constants::Bool=true, sort_by=String[], sort_ignore=[:SimID; shortLocationVariationID.(projectLocations().varied)], short_names::Bool=true)\n\nReturn a DataFrame for the given SQL query on the simulations table.\n\nBy default, constant columns and raw ID columns are removed.\n\nArguments\n\nquery::String: The SQL query to execute.\n\nKeyword Arguments\n\nremove_constants::Bool: If true, removes columns that have the same value for all simulations. Defaults to true.\nsort_by::Vector{String}: A vector of column names to sort the table by. Defaults to all columns. To populate this argument, it is recommended to first print the table to see the column names.\nsort_ignore::Vector{String}: A vector of column names to ignore when sorting. Defaults to the simulation ID and the variation IDs associated with the simulations.\nshort_names::Bool: If true (default), column names are shortened via shortVariationName. Pass false to keep raw XML-path column names (e.g. for matching against parameters.toml db_column entries).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.simulationsTableFromQuery"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.statusCodeID-Tuple{String}","page":"Database","text":"statusCodeID(status_code::String)\n\nReturn the database ID for status_code.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.statusCodeID"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/database/#ModelManager.variationIDs-Tuple{Symbol, AbstractMonad}","page":"Database","text":"variationIDs(location::Symbol, M::AbstractMonad)\nvariationIDs(location::Symbol, sampling::Sampling)\n\nReturn the variation IDs for location associated with M or sampling.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.variationIDs"},{"category":"section","location":"man/trial_hierarchy/#The-trial-hierarchy","page":"The trial hierarchy","text":"Every run that ModelManager organizes is described by one of four nested types. They form a strict containment hierarchy, from a single execution up to an arbitrary collection:\n\nType What it is Shares\nSimulation One run of the model —\nMonad A group of identical-up-to-randomness simulations same inputs and variation\nSampling A group of monads same inputs, differing variations\nTrial A group of samplings (arbitrary)\n\nThe abstract supertypes capture what each level guarantees:\n\nAbstractTrial\n└── AbstractSampling          # all constituent sims share input folders\n    └── AbstractMonad         # all constituent sims also share variation IDs\n        ├── Simulation\n        └── Monad\n    └── Sampling\n└── Trial\n\nAbstractSampling — all associated simulations share the same InputFolders; only their variations differ.\nAbstractMonad — all associated simulations share both input folders and variation IDs (they differ only in their random seed). Simulation and Monad are both monads.\n\nThis is why a Simulation is an AbstractMonad: a single simulation trivially satisfies \"all constituents share inputs and variation.\"","title":"The trial hierarchy"},{"category":"section","location":"man/trial_hierarchy/#Replicates-and-deduplication","page":"The trial hierarchy","text":"Stochastic models need replicates. A Monad is exactly that: a set of simulations with one fixed parameterization, differing only by random seed. The n_replicates keyword controls how many it holds, and use_previous controls whether already-completed replicates count toward that target:\n\n# A monad targeting 5 replicates; reuse any that already exist.\nmonad = Monad(inputs, variation_id; n_replicates=5, use_previous=true)\n\nBecause monads are keyed in the database by (simulator version, input folders, variation IDs), constructing \"the same\" monad twice returns the same database row. This is the mechanism behind ModelManager's cheap re-runs: asking for a parameterization that has already been simulated does not launch new work.","title":"Replicates and deduplication"},{"category":"section","location":"man/trial_hierarchy/#InputFolders","page":"The trial hierarchy","text":"A Simulation, Monad, or Sampling does not store parameter files directly — it references input folders by location. InputFolders consolidates that reference. Which locations exist (and which are required or varied) is defined by the project's inputs.toml (see Project configuration).\n\n# Keyword form — omitted locations default to \"\" (unused).\ninputs = InputFolders(; config=\"default\", custom_code=\"default\")\n\n# Positional form — required locations in alphabetical order, optional ones as kwargs.\ninputs = InputFolders(\"default\", \"default\"; ic_cell=\"cells_in_disc\")\n\nEach entry is an InputFolder recording the location, the database row ID, the folder name, its primary file (basename), and whether it is required or varied.","title":"InputFolders"},{"category":"section","location":"man/trial_hierarchy/#VariationID","page":"The trial hierarchy","text":"A VariationID records, for each varied location, which variation row is in effect. By convention:\n\n0 — the base (unvaried) file,\n-1 — the location is not in use,\na positive integer — a specific variation row in that location's variations database.\n\nYou rarely construct a VariationID by hand; addVariations and createTrial produce them as a side effect of registering variations (see Variations).","title":"VariationID"},{"category":"section","location":"man/trial_hierarchy/#Building-trials-in-practice","page":"The trial hierarchy","text":"You almost never call these constructors directly. The User API — createTrial and run — picks the right level for you based on how many parameter combinations your variations produce:\n\none combination, n_replicates == 1 → a Simulation\none combination, n_replicates > 1 → a Monad\nmany combinations → a Sampling\n\n# One value, one replicate → Simulation\nsim = createTrial(inputs, DiscreteVariation(:config, [\"overall\",\"max_time\"], 120.0))\n\n# One value, several replicates → Monad\nmonad = createTrial(inputs, DiscreteVariation(:config, [\"overall\",\"max_time\"], 120.0);\n                    n_replicates=5)\n\n# Several values → Sampling (one monad per value)\nsampling = createTrial(inputs, DiscreteVariation(:config, [\"overall\",\"max_time\"], [60.0, 120.0, 240.0]))\n\nYou can also start from an existing reference monad to inherit its fixed parameters:\n\nnew_trial = createTrial(reference_monad, more_variations...)\n\nOnce you have a trial, hand it to run to execute it — see Running simulations. For the constructor-level details and helper functions (simulationIDs, constituentIDs, trialID, …), see the Trial hierarchy API reference.","title":"Building trials in practice"},{"category":"section","location":"man/overview/#What-ModelManager-is","page":"What ModelManager is","text":"ModelManager.jl is the generic, simulator-agnostic core of a family of Julia packages for running large agent-based modeling (ABM) campaigns. It owns everything that does not depend on a particular simulator:\n\nthe trial hierarchy (Simulation, Monad, Sampling, Trial),\nparameter variations and space-filling designs,\nthe SQLite database schema, queries, and migration framework,\nthe parallel runner (with SLURM/HPC support),\nglobal sensitivity analysis (MOAT, Sobol', RBD-FAST), and\nABC-SMC calibration.\n\nEverything that is simulator-specific — how a simulation is actually launched, what a \"version\" means, how input folders are compiled — is reached through a single extension point: the AbstractSimulator interface.","title":"What ModelManager is"},{"category":"section","location":"man/overview/#The-ecosystem","page":"What ModelManager is","text":"        ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n        │              ModelManager.jl                 │\n        │  trial hierarchy · variations · database ·    │\n        │  runner · sensitivity · calibration           │\n        └───────────────────────┬─────────────────────┘\n                                 │  AbstractSimulator interface\n            ┌────────────────────┼────────────────────┐\n            ▼                    ▼                     ▼\n   PhysiCellModelManager   BergiCell(MM)         (your backend)\n      (PhysiCell)            (BergiCell)            (MySimulator)\n\nA simulator package depends on ModelManager, defines MySimulator <: AbstractSimulator, implements the required interface methods, and registers its globals in __init__. The package's users then call the package's own entry points; ModelManager runs underneath, unaware of which simulator is plugged in.\n\nThis separation means a feature added here — say, a new sampling design or a calibration kernel — is immediately available to every backend without any simulator-specific code.","title":"The ecosystem"},{"category":"section","location":"man/overview/#Who-should-read-these-docs?","page":"What ModelManager is","text":"Backend authors building a new simulator package. Start with Building a Simulator Backend; the Core Concepts pages (beginning with The trial hierarchy) explain the machinery you are plugging into.\nAdvanced users of a backend (e.g. PCMM) who want to understand the generic layer — how variations are stored, how the runner deduplicates work, what the database schema looks like. The concepts here are shared verbatim with the backend you use.\nContributors to ModelManager itself.\n\nnote: Examples need a simulator\nBecause ModelManager has no simulator of its own, the runnable examples in these docs assume a backend has been loaded and initialized (i.e. initializeModelManager has succeeded and a ModelManagerGlobals instance with a concrete simulator is registered). The API shown is identical regardless of which backend provides it.","title":"Who should read these docs?"},{"category":"section","location":"man/overview/#A-minute-long-tour","page":"What ModelManager is","text":"Once a backend is initialized, the generic workflow looks like this:\n\n# 1. Describe which input folders a run uses (see Project configuration).\ninputs = InputFolders(; config=\"default\", custom_code=\"default\")\n\n# 2. Describe how to vary parameters (see Variations).\ndv = DiscreteVariation(:config, [\"overall\", \"max_time\"], [60.0, 120.0, 240.0])\n\n# 3. Build and run a trial. createTrial picks the right hierarchy level for you.\noutput = run(inputs, dv; n_replicates=3)\n\nrun builds the appropriate trial hierarchy object, writes the variations to the database, and dispatches each pending simulation to the runner. Re-running the same script is cheap: ModelManager matches existing simulations and only runs what is missing.\n\nFrom there you can layer on space-filling designs, sensitivity analysis, or calibration — all built on the same three steps.","title":"A minute-long tour"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/variations/#Variations-and-designs","page":"Variations & designs","text":"Parameter variations and space-filling sampling designs.","title":"Variations & designs"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/variations/#Public-API","page":"Variations & designs","text":"","title":"Public API"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/variations/#Private-API","page":"Variations & designs","text":"","title":"Private API"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.AbstractVariation","page":"Variations & designs","text":"AbstractVariation\n\nAbstract type for variations.\n\nSubtypes\n\nElementaryVariation, DiscreteVariation, DistributedVariation, CoVariation\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.AbstractVariation"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.AddGridVariationsResult","page":"Variations & designs","text":"AddGridVariationsResult <: AddVariationsResult\n\nResult of addVariations with GridVariation: the full factorial grid.\n\nFields\n\nvariation_ids::AbstractArray{VariationID}: One VariationID per grid point, i.e. per combination of the discrete variation values. The array's shape mirrors the grid axes (one dimension per varied parameter).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.AddGridVariationsResult"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.AddLHSVariationsResult","page":"Variations & designs","text":"AddLHSVariationsResult <: AddVariationsResult\n\nResult of addVariations with LHSVariation (Latin Hypercube Sampling).\n\nFields\n\ncdfs::Matrix{Float64}: The sampled CDF coordinates in [0, 1], one row per latent dimension and one column per sample point (shape (d, n)).\nvariation_ids::Vector{VariationID}: One VariationID per sample point, in the same order as the columns of cdfs.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.AddLHSVariationsResult"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.AddRBDVariationsResult","page":"Variations & designs","text":"AddRBDVariationsResult <: AddVariationsResult\n\nResult of addVariations with RBDVariation (Random Balance Design).\n\nFields\n\nvariation_ids::AbstractArray{VariationID}: One VariationID per sampled point, in CDF-sample order.\nvariation_matrix::Matrix{VariationID}: The same IDs re-sorted into the RBD layout — one column per latent parameter, rows ordered along each parameter's periodic RBD curve. This is the form consumed by the RBD-FAST spectral analysis.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.AddRBDVariationsResult"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.AddSobolVariationsResult","page":"Variations & designs","text":"AddSobolVariationsResult <: AddVariationsResult\n\nResult of addVariations with SobolVariation (Sobol quasi-random sequence).\n\nFields\n\ncdfs::Array{Float64,3}: The Sobol CDF coordinates in [0, 1], indexed by latent dimension, sample, and design matrix.\nvariation_ids::AbstractArray{VariationID}: One VariationID per sample, arranged with one row per sample and one column per design matrix (shape (n, n_matrices)).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.AddSobolVariationsResult"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.CoVariation","page":"Variations & designs","text":"CoVariation{T<:ElementaryVariation} <: AbstractVariation\n\nA co-variation of one or more ElementaryVariations that are varied together.\n\nEach constituent variation must be of the same subtype (all DiscreteVariation or all DistributedVariation).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.CoVariation"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.DiscreteVariation","page":"Variations & designs","text":"DiscreteVariation{T} <: ElementaryVariation\n\nThe location, target, and values of a discrete variation.\n\nFields\n\nlocation::Symbol: The location (input-folder category) for this variation.\ntarget::XMLPath: The XML path to the element being varied.\nvalues::Vector{T}: The possible values that the target can take on.\n\nA singleton value can be passed in place of values for convenience.\n\nlocation must be provided explicitly.  Simulator packages (e.g. PhysiCellModelManager) may provide convenience constructors that infer location from the target.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.DiscreteVariation"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.DistributedVariation","page":"Variations & designs","text":"DistributedVariation <: ElementaryVariation\n\nThe location, target, and distribution of a distributed variation.\n\nFields\n\nlocation::Symbol: The location (input-folder category) for this variation.\ntarget::XMLPath: The XML path to the element being varied.\ndistribution::Distribution: The distribution of the variation.\nflip::Bool=false: Whether to flip the distribution (iCDF of 1-x instead of x).\n\nlocation must be provided explicitly.  Simulator packages (e.g. PhysiCellModelManager) may provide convenience constructors that infer location from the target.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.DistributedVariation"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.ElementaryVariation","page":"Variations & designs","text":"ElementaryVariation <: AbstractVariation\n\nThe base type for variations of a single parameter.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.ElementaryVariation"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.GridVariation","page":"Variations & designs","text":"GridVariation <: AddVariationMethod\n\nEnumerate all combinations of discrete variation values (full factorial grid).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.GridVariation"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.LHSVariation","page":"Variations & designs","text":"LHSVariation <: AddVariationMethod\n\nLatin Hypercube Sampling.\n\nFields\n\nn::Int: Number of samples.\nadd_noise::Bool=false: Whether to add noise within each bin.\nrng::AbstractRNG=Random.GLOBAL_RNG\northogonalize::Bool=true\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.LHSVariation"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.LatentVariation","page":"Variations & designs","text":"LatentVariation{T<:Union{Vector{<:Real},<:Distribution}} <: AbstractVariation\n\nA variation that uses latent parameters to generate target parameter values via mapping functions.\n\nWhereas CoVariations enforce a 1D relationship between parameters, LatentVariations allow multi-dimensional relationships via user-supplied maps. The latent parameters themselves are not stored in the database; only the derived target values are.\n\nInternally, ParsedVariations converts all variations to LatentVariations for processing.\n\nFields\n\nlatent_parameters: Discrete value vectors or prior Distributions, one per latent dimension.\nlatent_parameter_names: User-friendly names for each latent dimension.\nlocations: XML location symbols, one per target.\ntargets: XML paths to each target parameter.\ntarget_names: User-friendly display names for each target parameter. Derived from the source variation names when constructed via factory methods (DistributedVariation, CoVariation). For direct construction, supply via the target_names keyword; defaults to shortVariationName(location, columnName(target)) for each target.\nmaps: Forward maps — each map_j(lp_vals::Vector) → scalar computes one target value from all latent values.\ninverse_maps: Optional inverse maps — each inv_map_i(target_vals::Vector{Float64}) → Float64 recovers the latent parameter value lp_i for latent dimension i from the full vector of target values (ordered by targets). The library applies cdf(dist_i, lp_i) internally to obtain the CDF coordinate. One inverse per latent dimension. Required for SimulationBank support with LVSource calibration parameters. Auto-constructed for DVSource/CVSource-backed LatentVariations. Supply via the inverse_maps keyword argument when constructing a user-defined LatentVariation{<:Distribution}. Monotonicity of the forward map is a user responsibility and is not validated at construction time beyond a round-trip accuracy check.\ntypes: Output eltype of each forward map's return value.\nname: User-supplied or default name.\n\nConstruction\n\nFrom existing variation types (preferred for single-parameter calibration)\n\n# From a DistributedVariation — inverse_maps auto-constructed\ndv = DistributedVariation(:config, XMLPath([\"tumor\", \"growth_rate\"]), Uniform(0.01, 0.5))\nlv = LatentVariation(dv)\n\n# From a CoVariation{DistributedVariation} — inverse_maps auto-constructed\ncv = CoVariation(DistributedVariation(:config, XMLPath([\"k1\"]), Uniform(0.1, 1.0)),\n                 DistributedVariation(:config, XMLPath([\"k2\"]), Uniform(0.5, 5.0)))\nlv = LatentVariation(cv)\n\nDirect construction with continuous latent parameters\n\nThe positional arguments are: LatentVariation(latent_parameters, targets, maps, lp_names, locations; inverse_maps, name)\n\n1 latent dim, 1 target — log-normal forward map:\n\n# lp ~ Normal(0,1); target = exp(lp)\nlv = LatentVariation(\n    [Normal(0.0, 1.0)],\n    XMLPath[XMLPath([\"tumor\", \"growth_rate\"])],\n    Function[lp -> exp(lp[1])],\n    [\"log_growth_rate\"],\n    Symbol[:config];\n    target_names=[\"growth rate\"],\n    inverse_maps=Function[tv -> log(tv[1])]   # returns lp, not CDF\n)\n\n2 latent dims, 2 targets — independent priors:\n\n# lp1 ~ Uniform(0,1), lp2 ~ Uniform(0,1); target1 = 4*lp1, target2 = 2*lp2\nlv = LatentVariation(\n    [Uniform(0.0, 1.0), Uniform(0.0, 1.0)],\n    XMLPath[XMLPath([\"k1\"]), XMLPath([\"k2\"])],\n    Function[lp -> 4.0 * lp[1], lp -> 2.0 * lp[2]],\n    [\"lp1\", \"lp2\"],\n    Symbol[:config, :config];\n    target_names=[\"rate k1\", \"rate k2\"],\n    inverse_maps=Function[tv -> tv[1] / 4.0, tv -> tv[2] / 2.0]\n)\n\n2 latent dims, 2 targets — coupled targets (e.g. p1 = lp1, p2 = lp1 + lp2):\n\nlv = LatentVariation(\n    [Uniform(0.0, 1.0), Uniform(0.0, 1.0)],\n    XMLPath[XMLPath([\"p1\"]), XMLPath([\"p2\"])],\n    Function[lp -> lp[1], lp -> lp[1] + lp[2]],\n    [\"lp1\", \"lp2\"],\n    Symbol[:config, :config];\n    target_names=[\"p1\", \"p2\"],\n    inverse_maps=Function[tv -> tv[1], tv -> tv[2] - tv[1]]\n)\n\nDirect construction with discrete latent parameters\n\n# Discrete index maps to named configurations\nlv = LatentVariation(\n    [[1.0, 2.0, 3.0]],\n    XMLPath[XMLPath([\"scenario\"])],\n    Function[lp -> lp[1]],\n    [\"scenario_index\"],\n    Symbol[:config]\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.LatentVariation"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.RBDVariation","page":"Variations & designs","text":"RBDVariation <: AddVariationMethod\n\nRandom Balance Design sampling.\n\nFields\n\nn::Int\nrng::AbstractRNG=Random.GLOBAL_RNG\nuse_sobol::Bool=true\npow2_diff::Union{Missing,Int}=missing\nnum_cycles::Union{Missing,Int,Rational}=missing\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.RBDVariation"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.SobolVariation","page":"Variations & designs","text":"SobolVariation <: AddVariationMethod\n\nSobol quasi-random sequence sampling.\n\nFields\n\nn::Int: Number of samples.\nn_matrices::Int=1: Number of design matrices.\nrandomization::RandomizationMethod=NoRand()\nskip_start::Union{Missing,Bool,Int}=missing\ninclude_one::Union{Missing,Bool}=missing\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.SobolVariation"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.XMLPath","page":"Variations & designs","text":"XMLPath\n\nHold an XML path as a vector of strings, where each element is a node in the path.\n\nA : in a path element denotes an attribute filter, e.g. \"cell_definition:name:default\" selects the <cell_definition> whose name attribute equals \"default\". A double-colon :: separates a parent tag from a child tag used as a filter.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.XMLPath"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.NormalDistributedVariation-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{Symbol, XMLPath, T, T}} where T<:Real","page":"Variations & designs","text":"NormalDistributedVariation(location, target, mu, sigma; lb=-Inf, ub=Inf, flip=false)\n\nCreate a (possibly truncated) DistributedVariation with a Normal distribution.\n\nlocation must be provided explicitly.  Simulator packages (e.g. PhysiCellModelManager) may provide convenience constructors that infer location from the target.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.NormalDistributedVariation"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.UniformDistributedVariation-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{Symbol, XMLPath, T, T}} where T<:Real","page":"Variations & designs","text":"UniformDistributedVariation(location, xml_path, lb, ub; flip=false)\n\nCreate a DistributedVariation with a Uniform(lb, ub) distribution.\n\nlocation must be provided explicitly.  Simulator packages (e.g. PhysiCellModelManager) may provide convenience constructors that infer location from the target.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.UniformDistributedVariation"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.columnName-Tuple{Vector{<:AbstractString}}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"columnName(xml_path::Vector{<:AbstractString})\n\nJoin an XML path vector into a slash-separated column name string.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.columnName"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.getAllParameterValues-Tuple{Sampling}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"getAllParameterValues(simulation_id::Int)\ngetAllParameterValues(S::AbstractSampling)\n\nGet all parameter values for the given simulation, monad, or sampling as a DataFrame. Simulation ID can also be passed directly as an integer.\n\nIdentifying attributes\n\nIf sibling elements have identical tags, attributes are programmatically searched to find one that can be used to identify them. Priority is given to \"name\", \"ID\", and \"id\" attributes. If sibling elements cannot be uniquely identified by an attribute, artificial IDs will be added to the XML paths to ensure uniqueness for the column names. These will show up as <tag>:temp_id:<index> in the column names. Search for them with contains(col_name, \":temp_id:\"). Note: these are not added to the XML files themselves. Users must manually insert such artificial IDs into their XML files to use PCMM to vary those parameters.\n\nConverting column names into XML paths\n\nTo convert the column names in the returned DataFrame back into XML paths, split the column names by '/':\n\ndf = getAllParameterValues(simulation_id)\ncol1 = names(df)[1]\nxml_path = split(col1, '/')\n\nAlternatively, columnNameToXMLPath can be used.\n\nxml_path = columnNameToXMLPath(col1)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.getAllParameterValues"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.getParameterValue-Tuple{AbstractMonad, Symbol, XMLPath}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"getParameterValue(M::AbstractMonad, location::Symbol, xp::XMLPath)\n\nGet the parameter value for xp at location from the monad's variations database if the column exists, otherwise fall back to the base XML file.\n\nBoolean strings (\"true\" / \"false\") are returned as Bool.\nNumeric strings are returned as Float64.\nEverything else is returned as-is.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.getParameterValue"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.parseValueFromString-Tuple{String}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"parseValueFromString(v::String)\n\nParse a string value: return Bool for \"true\"/\"false\", Float64 if numeric, or the original string otherwise.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.parseValueFromString"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.sqliteDataType-Tuple{ElementaryVariation}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"sqliteDataType(ev::ElementaryVariation)\nsqliteDataType(data_type::DataType)\n\nMap a Julia data type to its SQLite column type string.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.sqliteDataType"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.variationName-Tuple{ElementaryVariation}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"variationName(av::AbstractVariation)\n\nGet the user-facing name of a variation used in reports and sensitivity scheme headers. If no explicit name was provided to the constructor, this is a convention-based default derived from shortVariationName(location, columnName(target)).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.variationName"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.AddVariationMethod","page":"Variations & designs","text":"AddVariationMethod\n\nAbstract type for variation sampling methods.\n\nSubtypes\n\nGridVariation, LHSVariation, SobolVariation, RBDVariation\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.AddVariationMethod"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.AddVariationsResult","page":"Variations & designs","text":"AddVariationsResult\n\nAbstract type for the result of addVariations.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.AddVariationsResult"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.ColumnSetup","page":"Variations & designs","text":"ColumnSetup\n\nA struct to hold the setup for the columns in a variations database.\n\nFields\n\ndb::SQLite.DB: The database connection to the variations database.\ntable::String: The name of the table in the database.\nvariation_id_name::String: The name of the variation ID column in the table.\nordered_inds::Vector{Int}: Indexes into the concatenated static and varied values to get the parameters in the order of the table columns (excluding the variation ID and par_key columns).\nstatic_values_db::Vector{String}: The static values as strings for DB insertion.\nstatic_values_key::Vector{Float64}: The static values as floats for the par_key hash.\nfeature_str::String: The string representation of the features (columns) in the table.\ntypes::Vector{DataType}: The data types of the columns in the table.\nplaceholders::String: The string representation of the placeholders for the values in the table.\nstmt_insert::SQLite.Stmt: The prepared statement for inserting new rows into the table.\nstmt_select::SQLite.Stmt: The prepared statement for selecting existing rows from the table.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.ColumnSetup"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.ParsedVariations","page":"Variations & designs","text":"ParsedVariations{T<:LatentVariation}\n\nHolds all variations converted to LatentVariations, ready for sampling.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.ParsedVariations"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#Distributions.cdf-Tuple{DiscreteVariation, Real}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"cdf(ev::ElementaryVariation, x::Real)\n\nGet the cumulative distribution function value of the variation at x.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Distributions.cdf"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager._validateInverseMaps-Tuple{LatentVariation{<:Distributions.Distribution}}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"_validateInverseMaps(lv::LatentVariation{<:Distribution}; n_samples=20, rtol=1e-6)\n\nCheck that lv.inverse_maps are consistent with lv.maps via two round-trip tests.\n\nForward-then-inverse (u → lp → target_vals → lp′): for n_samples draws of u ∈ (0,1)^n, compute latent and target values via the forward maps, then recover latent parameter values via the inverse maps. Verifies lp′ ≈ lp_vals and that cdf(dist_i, lp′_i) ∈ (0,1).\n\nInverse-then-forward (lp → target_vals → lp′ → target_vals′): using the same draws, forward-maps lp′ back to target values and verifies target_vals′ ≈ target_vals.\n\nReturns nothing on success. Throws ArgumentError on the first failure with details. Returns immediately (no-op) if lv.inverse_maps is nothing.\n\nArguments\n\nn_samples: Number of random u draws to test (default 20).\nrtol: Relative tolerance for isapprox (default 1e-6).\n\nExample\n\nlv = LatentVariation([Normal(0,1)], [path], [lp -> exp(lp[1])], [\"log_rate\"], [:cell];\n                     inverse_maps=[tv -> log(tv[1])])\nModelManager._validateInverseMaps(lv)  # passes silently\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._validateInverseMaps"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.addCDFVariations-Tuple{InputFolders, ModelManager.ParsedVariations, VariationID, AbstractMatrix{Float64}}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"addCDFVariations(inputs, pv, reference_variation_id, cdfs)\n\nConvert CDF samples to parameter values and write new variation rows to the database. Used internally by LHS, Sobol, and RBD addVariations implementations.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.addCDFVariations"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.addColumns-Tuple{Symbol, Int64, Vector{DataType}, Vector{XMLPath}}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"addColumns(location::Symbol, folder_id::Int, loc_types::Vector{DataType}, loc_targets::Vector{XMLPath})\n\nAdd columns to the variations database for the given location and folder_id.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.addColumns"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.addVariationRow-Tuple{ModelManager.ColumnSetup, AbstractVector{<:Real}}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"addVariationRow(column_setup::ColumnSetup, varied_values::Vector{<:Real})\n\nAdd a new row to the location variations database using the prepared statement. If the row already exists, it returns the existing variation ID.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.addVariationRow"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.addVariationRows-Tuple{InputFolders, VariationID, Dict}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"addVariationRows(inputs::InputFolders, reference_variation_id::VariationID, loc_dicts::Dict)\n\nAdd new rows to the per-location variation databases and return the resulting variation IDs.\n\nloc_dicts maps each varied location symbol to a 3-tuple (values_matrix, types, targets) where values_matrix is a #targets × #samples numeric matrix.\n\nCalled by addVariations (Grid, LHS, Sobol, RBD) and addCDFVariations after the generic sampling logic computes the parameter values.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.addVariationRows"},{"category":"function","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.addVariations","page":"Variations & designs","text":"addVariations(method::AddVariationMethod, inputs::InputFolders, avs::Vector{<:AbstractVariation},\n              reference_variation_id::VariationID=VariationID(inputs))\n\nAdd variations to inputs using method and return an AddVariationsResult.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.addVariations"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.createSortedRBDMatrix-Tuple{Vector{VariationID}, Matrix{Int64}}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"createSortedRBDMatrix(variation_ids, rbd_sorting_inds)\n\nSort variation IDs according to the RBD parameter ordering.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.createSortedRBDMatrix"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.defaultLatentParameterNames-Tuple{Vector, Vector{XMLPath}}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"defaultLatentParameterNames(latent_parameters::Vector, targets::Vector{XMLPath})\n\nGenerate default names for latent parameters based on target column names.\n\nFor each latent parameter, the name is constructed as: \"<target_1> | <target_2> | ... | lp#<i>\" where <target_n> is the column name of the n-th target parameter and <i> is the index of the latent parameter.\n\nReturns\n\nVector{String}: A vector of default names for the latent parameters.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.defaultLatentParameterNames"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.generateLHSCDFs-Tuple{Int64, Int64}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"generateLHSCDFs(n::Int, d::Int; add_noise=false, rng=Random.GLOBAL_RNG, orthogonalize=true)\n\nGenerate a Latin Hypercube Sample of CDFs for n samples in d dimensions.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.generateLHSCDFs"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.generateRBDCDFs-Tuple{RBDVariation, Int64}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"generateRBDCDFs(rbd_variation::RBDVariation, d::Int)\n\nGenerate CDFs and sorting indices for a Random Balance Design in d dimensions.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.generateRBDCDFs"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.generateSobolCDFs-Tuple{Int64, Int64}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"generateSobolCDFs(n::Int, d::Int[; n_matrices::Int=1, randomization::RandomizationMethod=NoRand(), skip_start::Union{Missing, Bool, Int}=missing, include_one::Union{Missing, Bool}=missing])\n\nGenerate n_matrices Sobol sequences of the Cumulative Distribution Functions (CDFs) for n samples in d dimensions.\n\nThe subsequence of the Sobol sequence is chosen based on the value of n and the value of include_one. If it is one less than a power of 2, e.g. n=7, skip 0 and start from 0.5. Otherwise, it will always start from 0. If it is one more than a power of 2, e.g. n=9, include 1 (unless include_one is false).\n\nThe skip_start field can be used to control this by skipping the start of the sequence. If skip_start is true, skip to the smallest consecutive subsequence with the same denominator that has at least n elements. If skip_start is false, start from 0. If skip_start is an integer, skip that many elements in the sequence, e.g. skip_start=1 skips 0 and starts at 0.5.\n\nIf you want to include 1 in the sequence, set include_one to true. If you want to exclude 1 (in the case of n=9, e.g.), set include_one to false.\n\nArguments\n\nn::Int: The number of samples to take.\nd::Int: The number of dimensions to sample.\nn_matrices::Int=1: The number of matrices to use in the Sobol sequence (effectively, the dimension of the sample is d x n_matrices).\nrandomization::RandomizationMethod=NoRand(): The randomization method to use on the deterministic Sobol sequence.\nskip_start::Union{Missing, Bool, Int}=missing: Whether to skip the start of the sequence. missing means ModelManager will choose the best option.\ninclude_one::Union{Missing, Bool}=missing: Whether to include 1 in the sequence. missing means ModelManager will choose the best option.\n\nReturns\n\ncdfs::Array{Float64, 3}: The CDFs for the samples. First dimension is features, second is matrix index, third is sample points.\n\nExamples\n\ncdfs = ModelManager.generateSobolCDFs(11, 3)\nsize(cdfs)\n# output\n(3, 1, 11)\n\ncdfs = ModelManager.generateSobolCDFs(7, 5; n_matrices=2)\nsize(cdfs)\n# output\n(5, 2, 7)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.generateSobolCDFs"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.getColumnDefaults-Tuple{Symbol, Int64, Vector{XMLPath}}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"getColumnDefaults(location::Symbol, folder_id::Int, loc_targets::Vector{XMLPath})\ngetColumnDefaults(::AbstractSimulator, location::Symbol, folder_id::Int, loc_targets::Vector{XMLPath})\n\nReturn the default values (as strings) for loc_targets columns when they are first added to the variation database for location/folder_id. Called by addColumns.\n\nDefault implementation reads the base XML file for the location and extracts values via getSimpleContent. Simulator packages may override for non-XML variation sources.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.getColumnDefaults"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.orthogonalLHS-Tuple{Int64, Int64}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"orthogonalLHS(k::Int, d::Int)\n\nGenerate an orthogonal Latin Hypercube Sample in d dimensions with k subdivisions.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.orthogonalLHS"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.recurseToGetParameterValues!-Tuple{Dict{String, Any}, Vector{String}, LightXML.XMLElement}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"recurseToGetParameterValues!(D::Dict{String,Any}, current_path::Vector{String}, element::XMLElement)\n\nRecursively traverse the XML element tree to extract parameter values into D. Used by getAllParameterValues.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.recurseToGetParameterValues!"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.setUpColumns-Tuple{Symbol, Int64, Vector{DataType}, Vector{XMLPath}, Int64}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"setUpColumns(location::Symbol, folder_id::Int, loc_types::Vector{DataType}, loc_targets::Vector{XMLPath}, reference_variation_id::Int)\n\nSet up the columns for the variations database for the given location and folder_id.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.setUpColumns"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.validateParsBytes-Tuple{SQLite.DB, String}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"validateParsBytes(db::SQLite.DB, table_name::String)\n\nAssert that the par_key blob in every row of table_name matches the float64 reinterpretation of the other columns.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.validateParsBytes"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.variationDataType-Union{Tuple{DiscreteVariation{T}}, Tuple{T}} where T","page":"Variations & designs","text":"variationDataType(ev::ElementaryVariation)\n\nGet the data type of the variation values.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.variationDataType"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.variationLocation-Tuple{ElementaryVariation}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"variationLocation(av::AbstractVariation)\n\nGet the location of a variation as a Symbol.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.variationLocation"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.variationTarget-Tuple{ElementaryVariation}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"variationTarget(av::AbstractVariation)\n\nGet the XMLPath target(s) of a variation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.variationTarget"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.variationValues-Tuple{DiscreteVariation}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"variationValues(ev::ElementaryVariation[, cdf])\n\nGet the values of an ElementaryVariation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.variationValues"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.variationValues-Tuple{Function, Vararg{Any}}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"variationValues(f::Function, ev::ElementaryVariation[, cdf])\n\nApply a function f to each of the variation values.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.variationValues"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/variations/#ModelManager.variationValues-Tuple{LatentVariation{<:Vector{<:Real}}}","page":"Variations & designs","text":"variationValues(lv::LatentVariation)\n\nCompute the variation values for all combinations of discrete latent parameters.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.variationValues"},{"category":"section","location":"man/running_simulations/#Running-simulations","page":"Running simulations","text":"Once you have a trial, run executes it. The runner is generic: it prepares the trial, figures out which simulations are still pending, dispatches them in parallel, and writes results back to the database. The simulator backend only provides the per-simulation launch via runSimulation.","title":"Running simulations"},{"category":"section","location":"man/running_simulations/#The-two-phase-run","page":"Running simulations","text":"run is split into two phases so that setup happens once and execution can be parallelized:\n\nPreparation — prepareTrialHierarchy compiles shared code and materializes varied input folders for the whole trial. It calls the backend's setupSampling once per unique input-folder group and setupMonad for each monad.\nExecution — pendingSimulationSpecs returns a SimulationSpec for every simulation that has not yet completed, and the runner launches each one through the backend's runSimulation inside its own task.\n\nBecause preparation is separated from execution, the backend's runSimulation can assume the monad is fully prepared and receives everything it needs in the SimulationSpec — no keyword arguments are threaded through.\n\noutput = run(inputs, dv; n_replicates=3)     # build + run in one call\n# or, equivalently:\ntrial  = createTrial(inputs, dv; n_replicates=3)\noutput = run(trial)\n\nrun returns an MMOutput wrapping the trial that was executed, which you can pass straight back into createTrial/run to build follow-up trials from it.","title":"The two-phase run"},{"category":"section","location":"man/running_simulations/#Cheap-re-runs","page":"Running simulations","text":"The runner only launches pending simulations. Because monads are keyed in the database by their parameterization (see The database), re-running a script reuses everything that already completed and runs only what is missing. To force fresh runs, set use_previous=false when constructing the trial.","title":"Cheap re-runs"},{"category":"section","location":"man/running_simulations/#Parallelism","page":"Running simulations","text":"By default ModelManager runs one simulation at a time. Raise the concurrency with setNumberOfParallelSims:\n\nsetNumberOfParallelSims(9)   # up to 9 simulations at once\n\nBackends typically also honor an environment variable for this (for example PCMM reads PCMM_NUM_PARALLEL_SIMS) so the limit can be set without changing code:\n\nPCMM_NUM_PARALLEL_SIMS=9 julia scripts/GenerateData.jl\n\nThe runner schedules simulations across Julia tasks up to this limit, regardless of which backend is in use.","title":"Parallelism"},{"category":"section","location":"man/running_simulations/#Status-tracking","page":"Running simulations","text":"Each simulation moves through the status codes from recognizedStatusCodes — Not Started → Queued/Running → Completed or Failed. The runner updates these as work progresses (updateDatabaseOnCompletion), so a query against the simulations table always reflects the current state of the campaign. After each simulation finishes, the backend's postSimulationProcessing hook runs for any cleanup or pruning.\n\nFor cluster execution, see HPC support. For the complete runner API (SimulationSpec, prepareTrialHierarchy, pendingSimulationSpecs, SimulationProcess), see the Runner reference.","title":"Status tracking"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/runner/#Runner","page":"Runner","text":"Trial preparation, simulation specs, and the parallel runner.","title":"Runner"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/runner/#Public-API","page":"Runner","text":"","title":"Public API"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/runner/#Private-API","page":"Runner","text":"","title":"Private API"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/runner/#Base.run-Tuple{AbstractTrial}","page":"Runner","text":"run(T::AbstractTrial; quiet=false, kwargs...) -> MMOutput\n\nRun all pending simulations in T and return an MMOutput.\n\nKeyword arguments\n\nquiet::Bool=false: when true, suppresses per-simulation and per-trial console output. Per-sim \"Running simulation: N...\" lines, the leading \"Running ...\" header, and the trailing \"Finished ...\" block are all gated by this flag. Used by ABC-SMC calibration to keep console output focused on per-generation progress.\non_progress::Union{Nothing,Function}=nothing: optional progress hook. When supplied, it is called as on_progress(:init, n_simulation_tasks) once after the pending simulation count is known, on_progress(:step, 1) after each simulation completes, and on_progress(:finish, n_success) once at the end. When nothing (default) the runner behaves exactly as before — this keeps the per-simulation completion loop framework- agnostic while letting callers (e.g. ABC-SMC calibration) render a live progress bar.\nAll other kwargs flow through to prepareTrialHierarchy (which forwards them to the simulator's setupSampling / setupMonad hooks) and to postSimulationProcessing. Any simulator-specific flags flow through this channel. runSimulation takes no kwargs.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Base.run"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/runner/#ModelManager.SimulationProcess","page":"Runner","text":"SimulationProcess\n\nHolds the outcome of a single simulation run.\n\nFields\n\nsimulation::Simulation\nmonad_id::Int\nprocess::Union{Nothing,Base.Process}: nothing if the command could not be built.\nsuccess::Bool\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.SimulationProcess"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/runner/#ModelManager.SimulationSpec","page":"Runner","text":"SimulationSpec\n\nA pending simulation to be launched. Produced by pendingSimulationSpecs and consumed by run, which wraps each spec in a @task that calls runSimulation on the active simulator.\n\nmonad_id is always a real monad ID — prepareTrialHierarchy always runs before spec collection, so setup is guaranteed to have completed.\n\nFields\n\nsimulation::Simulation: The simulation to launch.\nmonad_id::Int: ID of the enclosing monad. setupMonad has already run for this monad before the spec was built.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.SimulationSpec"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/runner/#ModelManager.eraseSimulationIDFromConstituents-Tuple{Int64}","page":"Runner","text":"eraseSimulationIDFromConstituents(simulation_id::Int; monad_id)\n\nRemove simulation_id from its monad's constituent CSV.  If the monad becomes empty, the monad (and its superiors) are deleted.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.eraseSimulationIDFromConstituents"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/runner/#ModelManager.pendingSimulationSpecs-Tuple{Simulation}","page":"Runner","text":"pendingSimulationSpecs(T::AbstractTrial) → Vector{SimulationSpec}\n\nReturn a SimulationSpec for every simulation in T that has not yet started, marking each as \"Queued\" in the database. Always called after prepareTrialHierarchy so all monad folders and input files are in place.\n\nDispatch behaviour:\n\nSimulation: returns one spec (against the enclosing monad) if not started.\nMonad: returns one spec per unstarted simulation in the monad.\nSampling / Trial: recurse.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.pendingSimulationSpecs"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/runner/#ModelManager.prepCmdForWrap-Tuple{Cmd}","page":"Runner","text":"prepCmdForWrap(cmd::Cmd)\n\nStrip surrounding backticks from the string representation of cmd.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.prepCmdForWrap"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/runner/#ModelManager.prepareHPCCommand-Tuple{Cmd, Int64}","page":"Runner","text":"prepareHPCCommand(cmd::Cmd, simulation_id::Int)\n\nWrap cmd in an sbatch invocation using the global job options.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.prepareHPCCommand"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/runner/#ModelManager.prepareTrialHierarchy-Tuple{AbstractMonad}","page":"Runner","text":"prepareTrialHierarchy(T::AbstractTrial; kwargs...) → Bool\n\nRecurse down the trial hierarchy, creating output folders and calling the simulator's setupSampling and setupMonad hooks. Returns true on success, false if any hook fails (in which case the remaining hierarchy is skipped).\n\nkwargs are forwarded to both hooks — any simulator-specific flags flow through this channel. This function has no knowledge of console output and does not touch simulation status codes.\n\nDispatch behaviour:\n\nAbstractMonad (Simulation or Monad): mkpath + setupSampling on M (compile code, etc.) + setupMonad on M (prepare varied input folders).\nSampling: mkpath + setupSampling once for the whole sampling + mkpath and setupMonad for each constituent monad. setupSampling is called only once, not once-per-monad.\nTrial: mkpath + recurse into each sampling.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.prepareTrialHierarchy"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/runner/#ModelManager.processSimulationTask-Tuple{Any}","page":"Runner","text":"processSimulationTask(simulation_task; kwargs...)\n\nSchedule and fetch a simulation task, update the database with the outcome, then call postSimulationProcessing on the active simulator.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.processSimulationTask"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/runner/#ModelManager.runAbstractTrial-Tuple{AbstractTrial}","page":"Runner","text":"runAbstractTrial(T::AbstractTrial; kwargs...)\n\nDeprecated alias for run.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.runAbstractTrial"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/runner/#ModelManager.simulationFailed-Tuple{Simulation, Int64}","page":"Runner","text":"simulationFailed(simulation::Simulation, monad_id::Int)\nsimulationFailed(simulation_id::Int, monad_id::Int)\n\nMark a simulation as failed and remove it from its monad's constituent list.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.simulationFailed"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/runner/#ModelManager.updateDatabaseOnCompletion-Tuple{Int64, Int64, Bool}","page":"Runner","text":"updateDatabaseOnCompletion(simulation_id::Int, monad_id::Int, success::Bool)\n\nUpdate the simulation status in the database after it finishes.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.updateDatabaseOnCompletion"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#AbstractSimulator-interface","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"The extension point every simulator backend implements.","title":"AbstractSimulator interface"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#Public-API","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"","title":"Public API"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#Private-API","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"","title":"Private API"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#ModelManager.AbstractSimulator","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"AbstractSimulator\n\nAbstract supertype for simulator backends.\n\nConcrete subtypes are responsible for preparing and executing a single simulation via the runSimulation dispatch, and for providing simulator-specific metadata (version schema, display info, etc.).\n\nThis is the primary extension point for using the ModelManager infrastructure with any simulator. To support a new simulator:\n\nDefine MySimulator <: AbstractSimulator\nImplement the required interface methods listed below\n\nRequired interface methods\n\nrunSimulation(::MySimulator, spec::SimulationSpec)::SimulationProcess\nsimulatorDir(::MySimulator)::String\nsimulatorVersionSchema(::MySimulator)::String\nsimulatorVersionIDName(::MySimulator)::String\nsimulatorVersionTableName(::MySimulator)::String\nresolveSimulatorVersionID(::MySimulator)::Int\ncurrentSimulatorVersionID(::MySimulator)::Int\nsimulatorInfo(::MySimulator)::String\nsetupMonad(::MySimulator, M::AbstractMonad; kwargs...)::Bool\nsetupSampling(::MySimulator, S::AbstractSampling; kwargs...)::Bool\naddVariationRows(::MySimulator, inputs, reference_variation_id, loc_dicts)::Vector{VariationID}\n\nNote: variationLocation is not part of the ModelManager interface.  The calling framework (e.g. PhysiCellModelManager) is responsible for resolving variation targets to their locations before constructing variation objects — the location::Symbol argument must be passed explicitly when constructing DiscreteVariation or DistributedVariation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.AbstractSimulator"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#ModelManager.centralDBFileName-Tuple{AbstractSimulator}","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"centralDBFileName(sim::AbstractSimulator)::String\n\nReturn the filename (not full path) of the central SQLite database for this simulator. The file will be created inside dataDir().  The default is \"mm.db\".  Simulator packages can override this to use a different name or implement legacy-name detection.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.centralDBFileName"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#ModelManager.postInitDisplay-Tuple{AbstractSimulator}","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"postInitDisplay(sim::AbstractSimulator)\n\nPrint initialization information. The default implementation prints the generic ModelManager fields (data directory, database path, inputs config, HPC status, parallelism). Simulator packages can specialize this method to prepend a logo, version banner, and simulator-specific fields.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.postInitDisplay"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#ModelManager.clearSimulatorArtifacts-Tuple{AbstractSimulator}","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"clearSimulatorArtifacts(sim::AbstractSimulator)\n\nRemove all simulator-generated build artifacts from input folders during a database reset. The default implementation is a no-op.\n\nCalled by resetDatabase after all output folders have been deleted. Implementations should remove compiled executables, object files, and any other files generated by the simulator that do not belong to the base inputs.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.clearSimulatorArtifacts"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#ModelManager.currentSimulatorVersionID-Tuple{AbstractSimulator}","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"currentSimulatorVersionID(sim::AbstractSimulator)::Int\n\nReturn the integer row ID of the currently active simulator version.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.currentSimulatorVersionID"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#ModelManager.dbVersionTableName-Tuple{AbstractSimulator}","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"dbVersionTableName(sim::AbstractSimulator)::String\n\nReturn the name of the SQLite table used to persist the package version in the project database (e.g. \"pcmm_version\"). The generic upgrade machinery reads and writes this table to track which version a given database was last migrated to.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.dbVersionTableName"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#ModelManager.getInputFolderDescription-Tuple{AbstractSimulator, String}","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"getInputFolderDescription(sim::AbstractSimulator, path_to_folder::String)::String\n\nReturn a human-readable description for the input folder at path_to_folder.\n\nCalled by insertFolder when inserting a new folder into the database. The default implementation returns \"\".  Simulator packages may override this to read metadata from a file in the folder (e.g. a metadata.xml or TOML file).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.getInputFolderDescription"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#ModelManager.initializeInputFolder-Tuple{AbstractSimulator, Any}","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"initializeInputFolder(sim::AbstractSimulator, input_folder)\n\nPerform any simulator-specific initialization for a newly-inserted input folder.\n\nCalled by insertFolder after the folder row has been written to the database and the per-folder variations SQLite database has been created. The default implementation is a no-op.\n\nImplementations may, for example, compile an initial XML parameter file from a template, create derived assets, etc.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.initializeInputFolder"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#ModelManager.packageName-Tuple{AbstractSimulator}","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"packageName(sim::AbstractSimulator)::String\n\nReturn the registered Julia package name for this simulator framework (e.g. \"PhysiCellModelManager\"). Used by getPackageVersion to look up the runtime version via Pkg.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.packageName"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#ModelManager.postSimulationProcessing-Tuple{AbstractSimulator, Any}","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"postSimulationProcessing(sim::AbstractSimulator, simulation_process; kwargs...)\n\nPerform any simulator-specific work immediately after a simulation finishes.\n\nCalled by processSimulationTask for every completed simulation. The default implementation is a no-op; simulator packages override this to clean up error files, prune output, log diagnostics, etc.\n\nCommon keyword arguments (simulator-defined):\n\nprune_options — options controlling which output files to delete (used by PhysiCellModelManager).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.postSimulationProcessing"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#ModelManager.resolveSimulatorVersionID-Tuple{AbstractSimulator}","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"resolveSimulatorVersionID(sim::AbstractSimulator)::Int\n\nResolve the current simulator version against the database, inserting a new row if necessary. Returns the resolved integer version ID.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.resolveSimulatorVersionID"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#ModelManager.runSimulation-Tuple{AbstractSimulator, Vararg{Any}}","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"runSimulation(::AbstractSimulator, spec::SimulationSpec) -> SimulationProcess\n\nLaunch the simulation described by spec on the active simulator and return a SimulationProcess describing the outcome.\n\nThis is the simulator-dispatched workhorse called by run inside each @task. Each simulator package implements its own method dispatching on AbstractSimulator. Setup (compilation, varied input folders) is always performed by prepareTrialHierarchy before this function is called, so implementations can assume the monad is fully prepared. No kwargs are accepted — all per-simulation configuration is encoded in spec.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.runSimulation"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#ModelManager.setupMonad-Tuple{AbstractSimulator, Vararg{Any}}","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"setupMonad(sim::AbstractSimulator, M::AbstractMonad; kwargs...)::Bool\n\nPerform monad-level setup (prepare varied input folders, etc.) for M. Called by prepareTrialHierarchy after setupSampling has already run for the enclosing sampling or directly for the monad. Return true on success, false on failure.\n\nAccepts AbstractMonad so it handles both Simulation and Monad inputs without requiring a wrapping Sampling to be created.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.setupMonad"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#ModelManager.setupSampling-Tuple{AbstractSimulator, Vararg{Any}}","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"setupSampling(sim::AbstractSimulator, S::AbstractSampling; kwargs...)::Bool\n\nPerform sampling-level setup (typically: compile the shared custom code once for all monads sharing the same InputFolders). Called once per unique input-folder group by prepareTrialHierarchy. Return true on success, false on failure.\n\nAccepts AbstractSampling so it can be called on a Simulation, Monad, or Sampling without requiring a wrapping object to be created.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.setupSampling"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#ModelManager.simulatorDir-Tuple{AbstractSimulator}","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"simulatorDir(sim::AbstractSimulator)::String\n\nReturn the path to the simulator's root directory.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.simulatorDir"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#ModelManager.simulatorInfo-Tuple{AbstractSimulator}","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"simulatorInfo(sim::AbstractSimulator)::String\n\nReturn a human-readable string describing the current simulator version.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.simulatorInfo"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#ModelManager.simulatorVersionIDName-Tuple{AbstractSimulator}","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"simulatorVersionIDName(sim::AbstractSimulator)::String\n\nReturn the SQL column name used for the simulator version FK in the simulations, monads, and samplings tables (e.g. \"physicell_version_id\").\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.simulatorVersionIDName"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#ModelManager.simulatorVersionSchema-Tuple{AbstractSimulator}","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"simulatorVersionSchema(sim::AbstractSimulator)::String\n\nReturn the SQL sub-schema (as a String) for the simulator version table. Used when initializing the database.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.simulatorVersionSchema"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#ModelManager.simulatorVersionTableName-Tuple{AbstractSimulator}","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"simulatorVersionTableName(sim::AbstractSimulator)::String\n\nReturn the name of the simulator version table in the database (e.g. \"physicell_versions\").\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.simulatorVersionTableName"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#ModelManager.upgradeMilestones-Tuple{AbstractSimulator}","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"upgradeMilestones(sim::AbstractSimulator)::Vector{VersionNumber}\n\nReturn a sorted vector of milestone VersionNumbers that have associated database schema changes. upgradeToMilestone is called for each milestone between the current database version and the target package version.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.upgradeMilestones"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/abstract_simulator/#ModelManager.upgradeToMilestone-Tuple{AbstractSimulator, Vararg{Any}}","page":"AbstractSimulator interface","text":"upgradeToMilestone(sim::AbstractSimulator, version::VersionNumber, auto_upgrade::Bool)::Bool\n\nApply the database schema migration required to bring the project database up to version. Called by upgradePackage for each milestone that needs to be crossed. Return true on success, false to abort the upgrade chain.\n\nImplementations are responsible for:\n\nPrompting the user (when auto_upgrade is false) for any large/destructive migrations.\nMaking all necessary DDL/DML changes to the database.\nNot updating the version table — upgradePackage does that after a successful return.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.upgradeToMilestone"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/recorder/#Recorder","page":"Recorder","text":"Persisting and compressing constituent-ID lists.","title":"Recorder"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/recorder/#Public-API","page":"Recorder","text":"","title":"Public API"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/recorder/#Private-API","page":"Recorder","text":"","title":"Private API"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/recorder/#ModelManager._compressedIDStr-Tuple{Any}","page":"Recorder","text":"_compressedIDStr(ids) → String\n\nFormat a collection of IDs as a compact human-readable string for log messages and warnings.  Consecutive ranges appear as \"first-last\"; isolated IDs as plain integers; entries are comma-separated.\n\nExamples\n\n_compressedIDStr([1, 2, 3, 5, 7, 8])  # → \"1-3, 5, 7-8\"\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager._compressedIDStr"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/recorder/#ModelManager.compressIDs-Tuple{AbstractArray{<:Integer}}","page":"Recorder","text":"compressIDs(ids) → Vector{String}\n\nCompress a collection of IDs into a compact run-length representation.\n\nConsecutive ranges are stored as \"first:last\"; isolated IDs as plain integer strings.  The result is a Vector{String} — callers decide what to do with it:\n\nWrite to CSV: CSV.write(path, Tables.table(compressIDs(ids)); header=false)\nDisplay in a message: join(compressIDs(ids), \", \")\n\nThis format is read back by constituentIDs.\n\nExamples\n\ncompressIDs([1, 2, 3, 5, 7, 8])  # → [\"1:3\", \"5\", \"7:8\"]\ncompressIDs([4])                   # → [\"4\"]\ncompressIDs(Int[])                 # → String[]\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.compressIDs"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/recorder/#ModelManager.recordConstituentIDs-Tuple{Type{<:AbstractTrial}, Int64, Array{Int64}}","page":"Recorder","text":"recordConstituentIDs(T::Type{<:AbstractTrial}, id::Int, ids::Array{Int})\nrecordConstituentIDs(T::AbstractTrial, ids::Array{Int})\n\nWrite the constituent IDs of an AbstractTrial to a CSV file inside its output folder.  The file is named after the constituent type (e.g. simulations.csv inside a monad folder).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.recordConstituentIDs"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/globals/#Globals-and-initialization","page":"Globals & initialization","text":"Global project state and the initializeModelManager entry point.","title":"Globals & initialization"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/globals/#Public-API","page":"Globals & initialization","text":"","title":"Public API"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/globals/#Private-API","page":"Globals & initialization","text":"","title":"Private API"},{"category":"constant","location":"lib/globals/#ModelManager.mm_globals_ref","page":"Globals & initialization","text":"mm_globals_ref\n\nModule-level Ref holding the active ModelManagerGlobals instance.\n\nSet by the concrete simulator package in its __init__, e.g.:\n\nfunction __init__()\n    ModelManager.mm_globals_ref[] = ModelManagerGlobals(simulator = MySimulator(), ...)\nend\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.mm_globals_ref"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/globals/#ModelManager.ModelManagerGlobals","page":"Globals & initialization","text":"ModelManagerGlobals\n\nMutable struct holding all global state for a ModelManager project.\n\nThe active instance is accessed via mm_globals.  Concrete simulator packages (e.g. PhysiCellModelManager) create an instance of this struct and register it via mm_globals_ref in their __init__.\n\nFields\n\ninitialized::Bool: true after initializeModelManager succeeds.\ndata_dir::String: Absolute path to the project data/ directory.\nsimulator::AbstractSimulator: The active simulator backend.\ninputs_dict::Dict{Symbol,Any}: Parsed contents of inputs.toml.\nproject_locations::ProjectLocations: Derived from inputs_dict.\ndb::SQLite.DB: Connection to the central project database.\nrun_on_hpc::Bool: true when sbatch is available (auto-detected).\nsbatch_options::Dict{String,Any}: Options forwarded to sbatch.\nmax_number_of_parallel_simulations::Int: Concurrency limit.\ndiagnostics_task::Union{Nothing,Task}: The background Task running databaseDiagnostics, set by initializeModelManager. nothing before initialization or if diagnostics have not been launched. Use waitForDiagnostics to block until it completes.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.ModelManagerGlobals"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/globals/#ModelManager.assertInitialized-Tuple{}","page":"Globals & initialization","text":"assertInitialized()\n\nAssert that the model manager has been initialized, throwing an informative error if not.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.assertInitialized"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/globals/#ModelManager.centralDB-Tuple{}","page":"Globals & initialization","text":"centralDB()\n\nReturn the central SQLite.DB connection for the current project.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.centralDB"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/globals/#ModelManager.dataDir-Tuple{}","page":"Globals & initialization","text":"dataDir()\n\nReturn the path to the current project's data/ directory.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.dataDir"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/globals/#ModelManager.initializeModelManager-Tuple{AbstractSimulator, AbstractString}","page":"Globals & initialization","text":"initializeModelManager(simulator::AbstractSimulator, data_dir::AbstractString; auto_upgrade::Bool=false)\n\nInitialize ModelManager for a project rooted at data_dir using simulator as the concrete backend.\n\nThis is the generic entry point that simulator packages (e.g. PhysiCellModelManager) call from their own path-level overloads after setting any simulator-specific fields. It performs all framework-agnostic initialization steps in order:\n\nRegister simulator and data_dir on the active ModelManagerGlobals.\nOpen the central SQLite database (filename determined by centralDBFileName).\nResolve the package version, creating or upgrading the DB schema if needed.\nParse inputs.toml.\nInitialize the database schema (tables, folder registration).\nCall postInitDisplay to print startup information.\nLaunch databaseDiagnostics as a background @async task.\n\nReturns true on success, false on any initialization failure — including errors that would otherwise throw (e.g. an unwritable data_dir). All mutated globals are reset to a clean state before any false return so that subsequent retries start fresh.\n\nSimulator packages typically provide their own path-level overloads (e.g. accepting path_to_physicell and path_to_data) that validate paths, set simulator-specific state, then delegate here.\n\nnote: Note\nDatabase diagnostics run in the background and may print after this function returns. Call waitForDiagnostics if you need them to complete before proceeding.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.initializeModelManager"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/globals/#ModelManager.inputsDict-Tuple{}","page":"Globals & initialization","text":"inputsDict()\n\nReturn the parsed inputs.toml dictionary for the current project.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.inputsDict"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/globals/#ModelManager.isInitialized-Tuple{}","page":"Globals & initialization","text":"isInitialized()\n\nReturn true if the model manager has been successfully initialized.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.isInitialized"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/globals/#ModelManager.mm_globals-Tuple{}","page":"Globals & initialization","text":"mm_globals()::ModelManagerGlobals\n\nReturn the active ModelManagerGlobals instance.\n\nThrows an assertion error if no simulator package has registered its globals yet.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.mm_globals"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/globals/#ModelManager.projectLocations-Tuple{}","page":"Globals & initialization","text":"projectLocations()\n\nReturn the ProjectLocations for the current project.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.projectLocations"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/globals/#ModelManager.simulator-Tuple{}","page":"Globals & initialization","text":"simulator()\n\nReturn the active AbstractSimulator backend.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.simulator"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/globals/#ModelManager.waitForDiagnostics-Tuple{}","page":"Globals & initialization","text":"waitForDiagnostics()\n\nBlock until the background databaseDiagnostics task launched during initializeModelManager completes. Returns immediately if diagnostics have already finished or were never started.\n\ninitializeModelManager runs five read-only consistency checks (DB↔filesystem sync, orphaned entries, constituent ID integrity, simulation status) in a background task so initialization returns promptly. In interactive sessions the diagnostics typically finish during the first idle moment. In scripts and HPC jobs the task runs opportunistically during I/O-heavy work (e.g. simulation runs); call waitForDiagnostics() explicitly if you need the output before a particular step.\n\nExample\n\ninitializeModelManager(sim, data_dir)\n\n# Optional: block until database consistency checks have printed their results.\n# Useful in scripts that exit quickly or test suites that inspect diagnostic output.\n# waitForDiagnostics()\n\n# ... rest of your workflow ...\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.waitForDiagnostics"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/globals/#ModelManager.currentSimulatorVersionID-Tuple{}","page":"Globals & initialization","text":"currentSimulatorVersionID()\n\nReturn the current simulator version row ID from the database. Delegates to currentSimulatorVersionID(sim) on the active simulator.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.currentSimulatorVersionID"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/globals/#ModelManager.simulatorVersionIDName-Tuple{}","page":"Globals & initialization","text":"simulatorVersionIDName()\n\nReturn the SQL column name used for the simulator version FK. Delegates to simulatorVersionIDName(sim) on the active simulator.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.simulatorVersionIDName"},{"category":"section","location":"man/calibration/#calibration_man","page":"Calibration","text":"Calibration infers model parameters from data: given an observed summary statistic, find the parameter distributions that make the model reproduce it. ModelManager implements Approximate Bayesian Computation — Sequential Monte Carlo (ABC-SMC), a likelihood-free method that works for any simulator because it only needs to run the model and compare its output to data.\n\nThe workflow has three pieces: define a CalibrationProblem, choose a method (ABCSMC), and run it with runABC (or runCalibration).","title":"Calibration"},{"category":"section","location":"man/calibration/#Defining-the-problem","page":"Calibration","text":"A CalibrationProblem bundles the model, the parameters to infer, the data, and how to compare:\n\nusing Distributions\n\n# Fix non-calibrated parameters via a reference monad (n_replicates=0 just records the IDs).\nref = createTrial(inputs, DiscreteVariation(:config, [\"overall\",\"max_time\"], 120.0);\n                  n_replicates=0)\n\nobserved = Dict(\"default\" => 100.0)\n\nproblem = CalibrationProblem(\n    ref,                                              # base inputs + fixed parameters\n    [DistributedVariation(:config, xml_path, Uniform(1e-7, 1e-4))],  # parameters to infer\n    observed,                                         # observed data\n    monad_id -> summarize(monad_id),                 # summary statistic\n    mseDistance,                                      # distance function\n)\n\nThe parameters can be any mix of DistributedVariation, CoVariation{DistributedVariation}, or LatentVariation{<:Distribution} — they are converted to the internal CalibrationParameter representation automatically.\n\nTwo functions you supply:\n\nsummary_statistic — monad_id -> T. Called once per proposed particle; you decide how to aggregate over the monad's replicate simulations (average, pick one, etc.).\ndistance — (simulated, observed) -> Float64. The built-in mseDistance handles Dict, Vector, and scalar inputs; supply your own for anything else.\n\nSet n_replicates > 1 in the problem to average out stochastic noise per particle (at N× the compute cost).","title":"Defining the problem"},{"category":"section","location":"man/calibration/#Choosing-the-method","page":"Calibration","text":"ABCSMC controls the SMC run. The defaults are reasonable; the most common knobs:\n\nmethod = ABCSMC(\n    population_size  = 200,    # accepted particles per generation\n    max_nr_populations = 15,   # max SMC generations\n    minimum_epsilon  = 0.005,  # stop when accepted distance reaches this floor\n)\n\nEach generation accepts the population_size best particles, then tightens the acceptance threshold (epsilon) toward minimum_epsilon. By default the next threshold is the median of accepted distances (epsilon_quantile); you can instead supply an explicit epsilon_schedule.","title":"Choosing the method"},{"category":"section","location":"man/calibration/#Stopping-criteria","page":"Calibration","text":"Beyond minimum_epsilon and max_nr_populations, you can stop early when the run stops making progress:\n\nmin_acceptance_rate — stop when accepted/proposed drops below this.\nmin_epsilon_decrease — stop when epsilon's relative decrease per generation is too small.\nmin_ess_fraction — stop when the effective sample size falls below this fraction of population_size.\nmax_evaluations — a hard cap on total particle evaluations across the whole run.","title":"Stopping criteria"},{"category":"section","location":"man/calibration/#Perturbation-kernels","page":"Calibration","text":"Between generations, resampled particles are perturbed by a kernel. Choose one based on how the posterior is shaped:\n\nKernel Behavior\nGaussianKernel Global multivariate Gaussian (twice the weighted covariance). Default.\nComponentwiseKernel Independent per-parameter perturbation.\nLocalNNKernel Local scale from each particle's k nearest neighbors.\nLocalNNCovKernel Local covariance from k nearest neighbors.\n\nmethod = ABCSMC(population_size=200, perturbation_kernel=LocalNNKernel(k=15))","title":"Perturbation kernels"},{"category":"section","location":"man/calibration/#Running","page":"Calibration","text":"result = runABC(problem; method=method, progress=:auto)\n# or equivalently\nresult = runCalibration(problem, method)\n\nprogress controls console output: :auto (a live progress bar on a TTY, generation logs otherwise), :none, :generation, :batch, or :bar. Particle evaluations run through the ordinary parallel runner, so calibration benefits from setNumberOfParallelSims and HPC just like any other trial.","title":"Running"},{"category":"section","location":"man/calibration/#The-simulation-bank-and-CDF-grid-reuse","page":"Calibration","text":"Calibration can evaluate thousands of particles, many close together in parameter space. Setting cdf_grid_k on the method snaps proposals onto a dyadic grid in CDF space and reuses previously evaluated monads within a small box (the SimulationBank), avoiding redundant simulations. The grid refines each generation, so early generations are cheap and later ones precise. See the ABCSMC docstring for the exact semantics.","title":"The simulation bank and CDF-grid reuse"},{"category":"section","location":"man/calibration/#Results-and-resuming","page":"Calibration","text":"runABC returns an ABCResult. Inspect the inferred posterior with posterior and the run's diagnostics with ConvergenceSummary:\n\npost = posterior(result)                 # final-generation posterior\npost = posterior(result; generation=3)   # a specific generation\nsummary = ConvergenceSummary(result)\n\nCalibration state is persisted (generation CSVs, the problem manifest, and method.toml) under a Calibration record in the database, so an interrupted run can be resumed:\n\nresult = resumeABC(Calibration(calibration_id))   # no need to re-supply the problem","title":"Results and resuming"},{"category":"section","location":"man/calibration/#Visualizing","page":"Calibration","text":"When a plotting backend is loaded, RecipesBase recipes turn an ABCResult or Calibration into standard diagnostics:\n\nusing Plots\nplot(result; plot_type=:corner)        # pairwise posterior\nplot(result; plot_type=:ridgeline)     # posterior narrowing across generations\nplot(result; plot_type=:convergence)   # epsilon / acceptance / ESS over generations\nplot(result; plot_type=:transition)    # accepted vs. rejected proposals per generation\n\nSee the Calibration API reference for every type, kernel, and helper.","title":"Visualizing"},{"category":"section","location":"","page":"Home","text":"<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"assets/logo-hero.svg\" width=\"240\" alt=\"ModelManager.jl\"></p>","title":"Home"},{"category":"section","location":"#ModelManager.jl","page":"Home","text":"ModelManager.jl is simulator-agnostic infrastructure for managing agent-based modeling (ABM) campaigns in Julia. It provides the generic base layer — a trial hierarchy, parameter variations, an SQLite database, a parallel runner, global sensitivity analysis, and ABC-SMC calibration — that simulator-specific packages build on by implementing the AbstractSimulator interface.\n\nModelManager is not used directly to run a particular simulator. Instead, a backend such as PhysiCellModelManager.jl (PCMM) implements AbstractSimulator and exposes the user-facing workflow. ModelManager supplies everything underneath.\n\nNew here? Read What ModelManager is to understand where this package sits, then Installation. If you are building a backend, jump to Building a Simulator Backend.","title":"ModelManager.jl"},{"category":"section","location":"#Where-do-I-look?","page":"Home","text":"I want to… Go to\nUnderstand ModelManager's role in the ecosystem What ModelManager is\nAdd the package as a dependency Installation\nUnderstand Simulation / Monad / Sampling / Trial The trial hierarchy\nLearn how inputs.toml and the data/ directory work Project configuration\nUnderstand the database schema and run queries The database\nRun trials in parallel or on a cluster Running simulations, HPC support\nChange parameter values across runs Variations\nSweep with LHS, Sobol, or RBD designs Space-filling designs\nRun a global sensitivity analysis Sensitivity analysis\nCalibrate a model to data with ABC-SMC Calibration\nImplement a new simulator backend Building a Simulator Backend\nDelete simulations or reset the database Managing data\nLook up a function's signature the Alphabetical index","title":"Where do I look?"},{"category":"section","location":"#Issues","page":"Home","text":"Found a bug or have a question? Please open an issue on the ModelManager.jl GitHub page.","title":"Issues"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/package_version/#Package-version","page":"Package version","text":"Resolving and persisting the simulator-package version.","title":"Package version"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/package_version/#Public-API","page":"Package version","text":"","title":"Public API"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/package_version/#Private-API","page":"Package version","text":"","title":"Private API"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/package_version/#ModelManager.getDBPackageVersion-Tuple{AbstractSimulator, SQLite.DB}","page":"Package version","text":"getDBPackageVersion(sim::AbstractSimulator, db::SQLite.DB)::VersionNumber\n\nReturn the package version recorded in db under dbVersionTableName(sim).\n\nIf the table does not yet exist it is created and stamped with the current getPackageVersion — this handles fresh databases that pre-date the versioning system.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.getDBPackageVersion"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/package_version/#ModelManager.getPackageVersion-Tuple{AbstractSimulator}","page":"Package version","text":"getPackageVersion(sim::AbstractSimulator)::VersionNumber\n\nReturn the runtime version of the package that owns sim by querying Pkg.\n\nIf the current project IS that package (i.e. running tests from within the package itself), Pkg.project().version is returned directly. Otherwise, the loaded dependency list is searched by packageName.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.getPackageVersion"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/package_version/#ModelManager.resolvePackageVersion-Tuple{AbstractSimulator, SQLite.DB}","page":"Package version","text":"resolvePackageVersion(sim::AbstractSimulator, db::SQLite.DB; auto_upgrade::Bool=false)::Bool\n\nCompare the runtime package version with the version recorded in db and upgrade if needed.\n\nIf the database is newer than the package, prints an error and returns false (the user must upgrade their package).\nIf versions match, returns true immediately.\nIf the package is newer, calls upgradePackage and returns its result.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ModelManager.resolvePackageVersion"}]
}
